{"title_page": "Cameron van der Burgh", "text_new": "{{short description|South African swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Cameron van der Burgh\n| image          = Cameron van der Burgh.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Cameron van der Burgh\n| nicknames      =\n| national_team  = {{RSA}}\n| strokes        = [[Breaststroke]]\n| club           = Energy Standard\n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1988|5|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Pretoria]], South Africa\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = 1.85 m\n| weight         = 85 kg\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | South Africa}}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]|1|1|0\n|[[World Aquatics Championships|World Championships (LC)]]|2|3|5\n|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]|4|3|1\n|[[Swimming at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]|4|2|3\n|[[Swimming at the African Games|African Games]]|6|0|0\n|[[African Swimming Championships|African Championships]]|1|0|0\n|'''Total'''|'''18'''|'''9'''|'''9'''\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 World Aquatics Championships|2009 Rome]]|[[Swimming at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 Barcelona]]|[[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2013 Barcelona|[[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 Kazan]]|[[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2015 Kazan|[[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 Melbourne]]|[[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2009 Rome|[[Swimming at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2011 Shanghai]]|[[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2011 Shanghai|[[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 Budapest]]|[[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2010 Dubai]]|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2016 Windsor]]|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|{{nowrap|[[2008 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2008 Manchester]]}}|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalSilver|2010 Dubai|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 Doha]]|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2008 Manchester|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]]|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2010 Delhi|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]]|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]]|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2010 Delhi|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breastroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games - Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the African Games|African Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2007 All-Africa Games|2007 Algiers]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2007 Algiers|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2011 All-Africa Games|2011 Maputo]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2011 Maputo|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2015 All-Africa Games|2015 Brazzaville]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2015 Brazzaville|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[African Swimming Championships|African Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 African Swimming Championships|2016 Bloemfontein]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n}}\n\n'''Cameron van der Burgh'''  [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (born 25 May 1988) is a retired South African competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/teamsa-burgh.htm|title=Team SA profile \u2013 Cameron van der Burgh|publisher=SouthAfrica.info|accessdate=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812010743/http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/teamsa-burgh.htm#|archive-date=12 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and hedge fund analyst. He is Africa's first home-trained world record holder and individual male Olympic Champion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.supersport.com/olympics/south-africa/news/120729/Van_der_Burgh_bags_gold_medal|title=SuperSport - Olympics|website=www.supersport.com|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> He is married to long time partner Nefeli Valakelis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/WaterSport/cameron-van-der-burgh-ties-the-knot-20180703|title=Cameron van der Burgh ties the knot!|work=Sport|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming career==\nVan der Burgh trains with Dirk Lange and is based in Pretoria. He has represented South Africa at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] where he won the gold medal in the 100-meter breaststroke in a new world record, and the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/va/cameron-van-der-burgh-1.html |title=Cameron van der Burgh |access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/100m-breaststroke-men|title=Rio 2016 100m breaststroke men - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/200m-breaststroke-men|title=Rio 2016 200m breaststroke men - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref> He has won numerous World Championship medals since his debut in 2007 when he took a bronze medal. Three times he has won the FINA overall World Cup.\n\nVan der Burgh set his first world long-course record (27.06s) in the 50&nbsp;m breaststroke in the semifinals at South African nationals in April 2009, cutting 0.12 of a second from Oleg Lisogor's old world record set in 2002. He won the world title in the same year at the Rome championship, also in the 50&nbsp;m breaststroke.\n\nHe won the 50m breaststroke at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in a time of 27.18 seconds in a new games record and the 100m world title at the 2010 short course world championships. He won the 100m breaststroke gold medal at the 2012 Summer Olympics in a new world record time of 58.46 seconds,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/29/us-oly-swim-swm1br-idUSBRE86S0O320120729|title=South Africa's van der Burgh wins men's 100m breaststroke gold medal|accessdate=30 July 2012 | work=Reuters|first=Julian|last=Linden|date=29 July 2012}}</ref> and paid tribute to late world champion [[Alexander Dale Oen]] afterwards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/london-olympics-2012/2012/7/29/3200368/olympic-breastroke-winner-cameron-van-der-burgh-wins-gold-to-honor|title=Olympic Breastroke Winner Cameron Van Der Burgh Wins Gold To Honor Alexander Dale Oen|last=Buzinski|first=Jim|date=29 July 2012|work=SBNation.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> Van der Burgh later admitted to breaking the rules by utilising illegal [[dolphin kick]]s during the race which was confirmed by video replays showing Van der Burgh taking three dolphin kicks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/blog=olympic-talk/post/swimmer-admits-to-breaking-the-rules-during-gold-medal-performance-in-london.html|title=Swimmer admits to breaking the rules during gold-medal performance in London|last=Devaney|first=Jason|date=7 August 2012|website=NBC Olympics|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813103945/http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/blog=olympic-talk/post/swimmer-admits-to-breaking-the-rules-during-gold-medal-performance-in-london.html|archive-date=13 August 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=au>{{Cite news | url = http://www.news.com.au/sport/london-olympics/swimmer-cameron-van-der-burgh-says-hes-the-victim-in-dolphin-kicking-furore/story-fndpu6dv-1226447186974 | title = Swimmer Cameron van der Burgh says he's the 'victim' in dolphin-kicking furore |publisher = news.com.au |date = 10 August 2012 | accessdate = 25 August 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, [[FINA]] have suggested they may consider underwater video evidence to judge results, although van der Burgh's results and medal are not under threat.<ref name=au/>\n\nAt the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]], he won the gold in the men's 50 m breaststroke in a new games record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM030101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 50m Breaststroke Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref>  He won silver in the 100 m breaststroke behind Adam Peaty, and was part of the South African team that won bronze in the men's 4 x 100 m relay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM031101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 100m Breaststroke Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM451101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 4 x 100m Medley Relay Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref> The 2014 Commonwealth Games marked the beginning of his major rivalry with World and Olympic champion [[Adam Peaty]]. Although Peaty has maintained the upper hand at Olympic and World level, especially in the 100 metres breaststroke, Van Der Burgh has remained his main international rival, and remains the only swimmer to have beaten him since his breakthrough, on both occasions denying Peaty the only major silverware missing from his collection, the Commonwealth Games 50 metre breaststroke title (a race not on the Olympic calendar).\n\nIn 2015 Cameron went on to Break the World Record in the heats of the 50m Breaststroke at the World Championships but settled for silver in the final. He went on further to earn another silver in the 100m Breaststroke.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/bio/cameron-van-der-burgh/|title=Cameron Van Der Burgh|date=2015-10-23|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en-US}}</ref> Later that year he went on to record a 24 race unbeaten streak to win the overall men's World Cup, the third of his career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/Van-der-Burgh-wins-World-Cup-Series-20151107|title=Van der Burgh wins World Cup Series|work=Sport|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2016 Olympic Games Cameron secured the silver medal in the 100m Breaststroke earning his second Olympic Medal.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later that year he went on the win another World Championship title at the World Short Cours championships in the 50m Breaststroke.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/cameron-wins-gold-in-montreal-20161212|title=Cameron wins gold in Canada|work=Sport|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, van der Burgh announced his retirement from competitive swimming following the conclusion of the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 FINA Short Course World Swimming Championships]], where he won two individual gold medals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/cameron-van-der-burgh-ends-career-with-textile-wr-gold-medal-in-50-br/|title=CAMERON VAN DER BURGH ENDS CAREER WITH TEXTILE WR, GOLD MEDAL IN 50 BR|work=[[SwimSwam]]|date=2018-12-16|accessdate=2018-12-17 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVan der Burgh went to Glenstantia Primary as a young boy<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/reach-for-gold-cameron-tells-pupils-1382735|title=Reach for gold, Cameron tells pupils|last=Du Preez|first=Yolande|date=13 September 2012|work=IOL|access-date=12 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> but matriculated at Crawford College in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=7258|title=Crawford College Pretoria Crawfordian Cameron van der Burgh brings back GOLD|website=Crawford Schools|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702123831/http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=7258|archivedate=2 July 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He now studies Financial Management through UNISA part-time and is interested in becoming an entrepreneur after his swimming career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=2910|title=Cameron van der Burgh|website=Crawford Schools|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005084601/http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=2910|archivedate=5 October 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since the London Olympics, van der Burgh has received various awards including South African Style Icon 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2012/11/26/olympian-cameron-in-style|title=Olympian Cameron in style|last=Ndlovu|first=Andile|date=26 November 2012|website=www.timeslive.co.za|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126172647/http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2012/11/26/olympian-cameron-in-style|archive-date=26 November 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=26 November 2012}}</ref> GQ 7th best-dressed man 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615002849/http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/# |archive-date=15 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/|title=Ty Keogh wins GQ South Africa Best-Dressed Men Awards 2012 [pic]|date=23 October 2012|website=Life is Savage|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026013401/http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/|archive-date=26 October 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=26 October 2012}}</ref> and has gone on to make various magazine covers and appeared in South African TV shows. He has made many appearances around the country giving motivational speeches and attending gala dinners. He has been linked to a few charities and recently fed underprivileged kids in Alexandria with his Olympic earnings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/Cameron-donates-cow-to-charity-20120821|title=Cameron's cow to feed kids|date=21 August 2012|work=News24|access-date=11 January 2018}}</ref> Most recently he has become the ambassador for Steps, a charity that treats kids born with clubfoot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goodtaste.co.za/events-4/2017/6/6/clubfoot-champion-cameron-|title=Cameron van der Burgh partners with Steps|work=Good Taste|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, van der Burgh contracted [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide coronavirus pandemic]]. He called it \"by far the worst virus\" he has ever endured, despite \"being a healthy individual with strong lungs (no smoking/sport), living a healthy lifestyle and being young\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2882494-olympian-cameron-van-der-burgh-says-covid-19-is-by-far-the-worst-virus|last=Zucker|first=Joseph|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=March 22, 2020|title=Olympian Cameron van der Burgh Says COVID-19 Is 'By Far the Worst Virus'|website=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsors==\nVan der Burgh has signed many lucrative endorsement deals since the London Olympics. These include Arena,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arenainternational.com/athletes/cameron-van-der-burgh_en_0_4_787.html|title=South African Republic, Team - arena|website=www.arenainternational.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> Investec,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.investec.co.za/about-investec/sponsorship/other-sponsorships/cameron-van-der-burgh.html?gclid=CKO69sGJorYCFUfMtAodxjkAUw|title=Cameron van der Burg[sic] crowned South Africa's 2013 Sportsman of the Year|website=Investec Sponsorships|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827010140/http://www.investec.co.za/about-investec/sponsorship/other-sponsorships/cameron-van-der-burgh.html?gclid=CKO69sGJorYCFUfMtAodxjkAUw|archive-date=27 August 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=27 August 2014}}</ref> Audi,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/Olympics2012/New-wheels-for-Van-der-Burgh-20120813|title=New wheels for Van der Burgh|date=13 August 2012|work=Sport|access-date=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> USN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportindustry.co.za/news/view/5434/usn-partners-with-olympic-gold-medallist|title=USN Partners with Olympic Gold Medalist|date=27 March 2013|website=Sport Industry Group South Africa|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718061006/http://www.sportindustry.co.za/news/view/5434/usn-partners-with-olympic-gold-medallist|archive-date=18 July 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=18 July 2013}}</ref> and Tag Heuer,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.picotandmoss.co.za/news-and-events/latest-news/6/congratulations-cameron-van-der-burgh|title=Congratulations Cameron Van Der Burgh!|date=August 2012|website=Picot & Moss|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826161146/http://www.picotandmoss.co.za/news-and-events/latest-news/6/congratulations-cameron-van-der-burgh|archivedate=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with his most recent being a four-year deal with multi-brand corporation Procter & Gamble as the new Head and Shoulders ambassador, joining the likes of Michael Phelps, Lionel Messi and Jenson Button.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jucyafrica.com/another-sponsorship-deal-for-cameron-van-der-burgh|title=Another Sponsorship Deal For Cameron van der Burgh|last=Phatudi|first=Denis|date=4 April 2013|website=Juicy Africa|language=en-ZA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115630/http://www.jucyafrica.com/another-sponsorship-deal-for-cameron-van-der-burgh|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=26 August 2014}}</ref>  He is estimated to be earning between $200,000 and $400,000 per annum from sponsorship deals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/sport/swimming-stars-could-earn-millions-report-20120803/|title=Swimming stars could earn millions \u2013 report|date=3 August 2012|website=City Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216043003/http://www.citypress.co.za/sport/swimming-stars-could-earn-millions-report-20120803/|archivedate=16 February 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Investment career ==\nVan der Burgh created a big passion for the financial markets from a young age when he won the JSE School Challenge in 2005<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jsemagazine.co.za/market-place/adds/|title=IT ALL ADDS UP - JSE MAGAZINE|date=2015-06-01|work=JSE MAGAZINE|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> and has gone to further manage a portion of his own capital ever since. He recently revealed he enjoys commodities in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/316953/cameron-van-der-burgh-opens-up-about-money-totally-sounds-like-a-stock-broker|title=Cameron van der Burgh opens up about money (totally sounds like a stock broker!)|website=702|language=en|access-date=2018-09-09}}</ref>\n\nCameron joined Andurand Capital, a private hedge fund in London as an analyst in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/sas-swimming-champion-camerons-stock-is-on-the-rise-17274416|title=SA's swimming champion Cameron's stock is on the rise {{!}} Weekend Argus|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n*[[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bestsports.com.br/db/atlpag.php?atl=6338&lang=2 BEST sports \u2013 Profile]\n* {{FINA|cameron-van-der-burgh}}\n* {{IOC profile|cameron-van-der-burgh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Felipe Fran\u00e7a Silva]]\n| title = [[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke|Men's 50-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder]]\n| years = 29 July 2009 \u2013 22 August 2014\n| after = [[Adam Peaty]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Oleg Lisogor]]\n| title = [[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke#Short course|Men's 50-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (25m)]]\n| years = 8 November 2008 \u2013 present\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Brenton Rickard]]\n| title = [[World record progression 100 metres breaststroke|Men's 100-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (long course)]]\n| years = 29 July 2012 \u2013 17 April 2015\n| after = [[Adam Peaty]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Ed Moses (swimmer)|Ed Moses]]\n| title = [[World record progression 100 metres breaststroke|Men's 100-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (25m)]]\n| years = 9 November 2008 \u2013 present\n| after = Incumbent}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year|''Swimming World Magazine's''<br>African Swimmer of the Year]]\n| before = [[Oussama Mellouli]]\n| after = [[Chad le Clos]]\n| years = 2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Randall Bal]]<br>[[Chad le Clos]]|title=[[FINA Swimming World Cup|FINA World Cup]]<br>overall male winner\n| years = 2008, 2009<br>2015\n| after = [[Thiago Pereira]]<br>[[Vladimir Morozov (swimmer)|Vladimir Morozov]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 100 m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World LC Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 100m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 100m Breaststroke Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Der Burgh, Cameron}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:South African male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Male breaststroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:World record holders in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:African Games gold medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:African Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2014 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2007 All-Africa Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2011 All-Africa Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2015 African Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Cameron van der Burgh\n| image          = Cameron van der Burgh.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Cameron van der Burgh\n| nicknames      =\n| national_team  = {{RSA}}\n| strokes        = [[Breaststroke]]\n| club           = Energy Standard\n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1988|5|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Pretoria]], South Africa\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = 1.85 m\n| weight         = 85 kg\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | South Africa}}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]|1|1|0\n|[[World Aquatics Championships|World Championships (LC)]]|2|3|5\n|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]|4|3|1\n|[[Swimming at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]|4|2|3\n|[[Swimming at the African Games|African Games]]|6|0|0\n|[[African Swimming Championships|African Championships]]|1|0|0\n|'''Total'''|'''18'''|'''9'''|'''9'''\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 World Aquatics Championships|2009 Rome]]|[[Swimming at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 Barcelona]]|[[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2013 Barcelona|[[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 Kazan]]|[[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2015 Kazan|[[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 Melbourne]]|[[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2009 Rome|[[Swimming at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2011 Shanghai]]|[[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2011 Shanghai|[[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 Budapest]]|[[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2010 Dubai]]|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2016 Windsor]]|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|{{nowrap|[[2008 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2008 Manchester]]}}|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalSilver|2010 Dubai|[[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50&nbsp;m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 Doha]]|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2008 Manchester|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]]|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2010 Delhi|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]]|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]]|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 50 metre breaststroke|50 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2010 Delhi|[[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breaststroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Men's 100 metre breaststroke|100 m breastroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games - Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Swimming at the African Games|African Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2007 All-Africa Games|2007 Algiers]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2007 Algiers|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2011 All-Africa Games|2011 Maputo]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2011 Maputo|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Swimming at the 2015 All-Africa Games|2015 Brazzaville]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalGold|2015 Brazzaville|100 m breaststroke}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[African Swimming Championships|African Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 African Swimming Championships|2016 Bloemfontein]]|50 m breaststroke}}\n}}\n\n'''Cameron van der Burgh'''  [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (born 25 May 1988) is a retired South African competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/teamsa-burgh.htm|title=Team SA profile \u2013 Cameron van der Burgh|publisher=SouthAfrica.info|accessdate=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812010743/http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/teamsa-burgh.htm#|archive-date=12 August 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and hedge fund analyst. He is Africa's first home-trained world record holder and individual male Olympic Champion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.supersport.com/olympics/south-africa/news/120729/Van_der_Burgh_bags_gold_medal|title=SuperSport - Olympics|website=www.supersport.com|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> He is married to long time partner Nefeli Valakelis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/WaterSport/cameron-van-der-burgh-ties-the-knot-20180703|title=Cameron van der Burgh ties the knot!|work=Sport|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming career==\nVan der Burgh trains with Dirk Lange and is based in Pretoria. He has represented South Africa at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] where he won the gold medal in the 100-meter breaststroke in a new world record, and the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/va/cameron-van-der-burgh-1.html |title=Cameron van der Burgh |access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/100m-breaststroke-men|title=Rio 2016 100m breaststroke men - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/200m-breaststroke-men|title=Rio 2016 200m breaststroke men - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref> He has won numerous World Championship medals since his debut in 2007 when he took a bronze medal. Three times he has won the FINA overall World Cup.\n\nVan der Burgh set his first world long-course record (27.06s) in the 50&nbsp;m breaststroke in the semifinals at South African nationals in April 2009, cutting 0.12 of a second from Oleg Lisogor's old world record set in 2002. He won the world title in the same year at the Rome championship, also in the 50&nbsp;m breaststroke.\n\nHe won the 50m breaststroke at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in a time of 27.18 seconds in a new games record and the 100m world title at the 2010 short course world championships. He won the 100m breaststroke gold medal at the 2012 Summer Olympics in a new world record time of 58.46 seconds,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/29/us-oly-swim-swm1br-idUSBRE86S0O320120729|title=South Africa's van der Burgh wins men's 100m breaststroke gold medal|accessdate=30 July 2012 | work=Reuters|first=Julian|last=Linden|date=29 July 2012}}</ref> and paid tribute to late world champion [[Alexander Dale Oen]] afterwards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/london-olympics-2012/2012/7/29/3200368/olympic-breastroke-winner-cameron-van-der-burgh-wins-gold-to-honor|title=Olympic Breastroke Winner Cameron Van Der Burgh Wins Gold To Honor Alexander Dale Oen|last=Buzinski|first=Jim|date=29 July 2012|work=SBNation.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> Van der Burgh later admitted to breaking the rules by utilising illegal [[dolphin kick]]s during the race which was confirmed by video replays showing Van der Burgh taking three dolphin kicks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/blog=olympic-talk/post/swimmer-admits-to-breaking-the-rules-during-gold-medal-performance-in-london.html|title=Swimmer admits to breaking the rules during gold-medal performance in London|last=Devaney|first=Jason|date=7 August 2012|website=NBC Olympics|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813103945/http://www.nbcolympics.com/news-blogs/blog=olympic-talk/post/swimmer-admits-to-breaking-the-rules-during-gold-medal-performance-in-london.html|archive-date=13 August 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=au>{{Cite news | url = http://www.news.com.au/sport/london-olympics/swimmer-cameron-van-der-burgh-says-hes-the-victim-in-dolphin-kicking-furore/story-fndpu6dv-1226447186974 | title = Swimmer Cameron van der Burgh says he's the 'victim' in dolphin-kicking furore |publisher = news.com.au |date = 10 August 2012 | accessdate = 25 August 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, [[FINA]] have suggested they may consider underwater video evidence to judge results, although van der Burgh's results and medal are not under threat.<ref name=au/>\n\nAt the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]], he won the gold in the men's 50 m breaststroke in a new games record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM030101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 50m Breaststroke Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref>  He won silver in the 100 m breaststroke behind Adam Peaty, and was part of the South African team that won bronze in the men's 4 x 100 m relay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM031101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 100m Breaststroke Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://g2014results.thecgf.com/PEVU/PEVU_SWM451101.html|title=Glasgow 2014 - Men's 4 x 100m Medley Relay Final|last=|first=|date=|website=g2014results.thecgf.com|language=|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref> The 2014 Commonwealth Games marked the beginning of his major rivalry with World and Olympic champion [[Adam Peaty]]. Although Peaty has maintained the upper hand at Olympic and World level, especially in the 100 metres breaststroke, Van Der Burgh has remained his main international rival, and remains the only swimmer to have beaten him since his breakthrough, on both occasions denying Peaty the only major silverware missing from his collection, the Commonwealth Games 50 metre breaststroke title (a race not on the Olympic calendar).\n\nIn 2015 Cameron went on to Break the World Record in the heats of the 50m Breaststroke at the World Championships but settled for silver in the final. He went on further to earn another silver in the 100m Breaststroke.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/bio/cameron-van-der-burgh/|title=Cameron Van Der Burgh|date=2015-10-23|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en-US}}</ref> Later that year he went on to record a 24 race unbeaten streak to win the overall men's World Cup, the third of his career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/Van-der-Burgh-wins-World-Cup-Series-20151107|title=Van der Burgh wins World Cup Series|work=Sport|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2016 Olympic Games Cameron secured the silver medal in the 100m Breaststroke earning his second Olympic Medal.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later that year he went on the win another World Championship title at the World Short Cours championships in the 50m Breaststroke.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/cameron-wins-gold-in-montreal-20161212|title=Cameron wins gold in Canada|work=Sport|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, van der Burgh announced his retirement from competitive swimming following the conclusion of the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 FINA Short Course World Swimming Championships]], where he won two individual gold medals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/cameron-van-der-burgh-ends-career-with-textile-wr-gold-medal-in-50-br/|title=CAMERON VAN DER BURGH ENDS CAREER WITH TEXTILE WR, GOLD MEDAL IN 50 BR|work=[[SwimSwam]]|date=2018-12-16|accessdate=2018-12-17 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVan der Burgh went to Glenstantia Primary as a young boy<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/reach-for-gold-cameron-tells-pupils-1382735|title=Reach for gold, Cameron tells pupils|last=Du Preez|first=Yolande|date=13 September 2012|work=IOL|access-date=12 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> but matriculated at Crawford College in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=7258|title=Crawford College Pretoria Crawfordian Cameron van der Burgh brings back GOLD|website=Crawford Schools|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702123831/http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=7258|archivedate=2 July 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He now studies Financial Management through UNISA part-time and is interested in becoming an entrepreneur after his swimming career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=2910|title=Cameron van der Burgh|website=Crawford Schools|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005084601/http://crawfordschools.co.za/?p=2910|archivedate=5 October 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since the London Olympics, van der Burgh has received various awards including South African Style Icon 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2012/11/26/olympian-cameron-in-style|title=Olympian Cameron in style|last=Ndlovu|first=Andile|date=26 November 2012|website=www.timeslive.co.za|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126172647/http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2012/11/26/olympian-cameron-in-style|archive-date=26 November 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=26 November 2012}}</ref> GQ 7th best-dressed man 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615002849/http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/# |archive-date=15 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/|title=Ty Keogh wins GQ South Africa Best-Dressed Men Awards 2012 [pic]|date=23 October 2012|website=Life is Savage|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026013401/http://lifeissavage.com/2012/10/23/ty-keogh-wins-gq-south-africa-best-dressed-men-awards-2012-pic/|archive-date=26 October 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=26 October 2012}}</ref> and has gone on to make various magazine covers and appeared in South African TV shows. He has made many appearances around the country giving motivational speeches and attending gala dinners. He has been linked to a few charities and recently fed underprivileged kids in Alexandria with his Olympic earnings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/Cameron-donates-cow-to-charity-20120821|title=Cameron's cow to feed kids|date=21 August 2012|work=News24|access-date=11 January 2018}}</ref> Most recently he has become the ambassador for Steps, a charity that treats kids born with clubfoot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goodtaste.co.za/events-4/2017/6/6/clubfoot-champion-cameron-|title=Cameron van der Burgh partners with Steps|work=Good Taste|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, van der Burgh contracted [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide coronavirus pandemic]]. He called it \"by far the worst virus\" he has ever endured, despite \"being a healthy individual with strong lungs (no smoking/sport), living a healthy lifestyle and being young\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2882494-olympian-cameron-van-der-burgh-says-covid-19-is-by-far-the-worst-virus|last=Zucker|first=Joseph|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=March 22, 2020|title=Olympian Cameron van der Burgh Says COVID-19 Is 'By Far the Worst Virus'|website=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsors==\nVan der Burgh has signed many lucrative endorsement deals since the London Olympics. These include Arena,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arenainternational.com/athletes/cameron-van-der-burgh_en_0_4_787.html|title=South African Republic, Team - arena|website=www.arenainternational.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> Investec,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.investec.co.za/about-investec/sponsorship/other-sponsorships/cameron-van-der-burgh.html?gclid=CKO69sGJorYCFUfMtAodxjkAUw|title=Cameron van der Burg[sic] crowned South Africa's 2013 Sportsman of the Year|website=Investec Sponsorships|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827010140/http://www.investec.co.za/about-investec/sponsorship/other-sponsorships/cameron-van-der-burgh.html?gclid=CKO69sGJorYCFUfMtAodxjkAUw|archive-date=27 August 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=27 August 2014}}</ref> Audi,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/Olympics2012/New-wheels-for-Van-der-Burgh-20120813|title=New wheels for Van der Burgh|date=13 August 2012|work=Sport|access-date=11 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> USN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportindustry.co.za/news/view/5434/usn-partners-with-olympic-gold-medallist|title=USN Partners with Olympic Gold Medalist|date=27 March 2013|website=Sport Industry Group South Africa|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718061006/http://www.sportindustry.co.za/news/view/5434/usn-partners-with-olympic-gold-medallist|archive-date=18 July 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=18 July 2013}}</ref> and Tag Heuer,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.picotandmoss.co.za/news-and-events/latest-news/6/congratulations-cameron-van-der-burgh|title=Congratulations Cameron Van Der Burgh!|date=August 2012|website=Picot & Moss|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826161146/http://www.picotandmoss.co.za/news-and-events/latest-news/6/congratulations-cameron-van-der-burgh|archivedate=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with his most recent being a four-year deal with multi-brand corporation Procter & Gamble as the new Head and Shoulders ambassador, joining the likes of Michael Phelps, Lionel Messi and Jenson Button.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jucyafrica.com/another-sponsorship-deal-for-cameron-van-der-burgh|title=Another Sponsorship Deal For Cameron van der Burgh|last=Phatudi|first=Denis|date=4 April 2013|website=Juicy Africa|language=en-ZA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115630/http://www.jucyafrica.com/another-sponsorship-deal-for-cameron-van-der-burgh|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=26 August 2014}}</ref>  He is estimated to be earning between $200,000 and $400,000 per annum from sponsorship deals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/sport/swimming-stars-could-earn-millions-report-20120803/|title=Swimming stars could earn millions \u2013 report|date=3 August 2012|website=City Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216043003/http://www.citypress.co.za/sport/swimming-stars-could-earn-millions-report-20120803/|archivedate=16 February 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-03-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Investment career ==\nVan der Burgh created a big passion for the financial markets from a young age when he won the JSE School Challenge in 2005<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jsemagazine.co.za/market-place/adds/|title=IT ALL ADDS UP - JSE MAGAZINE|date=2015-06-01|work=JSE MAGAZINE|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> and has gone to further manage a portion of his own capital ever since. He recently revealed he enjoys commodities in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/316953/cameron-van-der-burgh-opens-up-about-money-totally-sounds-like-a-stock-broker|title=Cameron van der Burgh opens up about money (totally sounds like a stock broker!)|website=702|language=en|access-date=2018-09-09}}</ref>\n\nCameron joined Andurand Capital, a private hedge fund in London as an analyst in October where he now lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/sas-swimming-champion-camerons-stock-is-on-the-rise-17274416|title=SA's swimming champion Cameron's stock is on the rise {{!}} Weekend Argus|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n*[[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bestsports.com.br/db/atlpag.php?atl=6338&lang=2 BEST sports \u2013 Profile]\n* {{FINA|cameron-van-der-burgh}}\n* {{IOC profile|cameron-van-der-burgh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Felipe Fran\u00e7a Silva]]\n| title = [[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke|Men's 50-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder]]\n| years = 29 July 2009 \u2013 22 August 2014\n| after = [[Adam Peaty]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Oleg Lisogor]]\n| title = [[World record progression 50 metres breaststroke#Short course|Men's 50-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (25m)]]\n| years = 8 November 2008 \u2013 present\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Brenton Rickard]]\n| title = [[World record progression 100 metres breaststroke|Men's 100-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (long course)]]\n| years = 29 July 2012 \u2013 17 April 2015\n| after = [[Adam Peaty]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Ed Moses (swimmer)|Ed Moses]]\n| title = [[World record progression 100 metres breaststroke|Men's 100-metre breaststroke<br>world record-holder (25m)]]\n| years = 9 November 2008 \u2013 present\n| after = Incumbent}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year|''Swimming World Magazine's''<br>African Swimmer of the Year]]\n| before = [[Oussama Mellouli]]\n| after = [[Chad le Clos]]\n| years = 2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Randall Bal]]<br>[[Chad le Clos]]|title=[[FINA Swimming World Cup|FINA World Cup]]<br>overall male winner\n| years = 2008, 2009<br>2015\n| after = [[Thiago Pereira]]<br>[[Vladimir Morozov (swimmer)|Vladimir Morozov]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 100 m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World LC Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 100m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 50m Breaststroke Men}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 100m Breaststroke Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Der Burgh, Cameron}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:South African male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Male breaststroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:World record holders in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:African Games gold medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:African Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2014 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2007 All-Africa Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2011 All-Africa Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2015 African Games]]\n", "name_user": "FinnHK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestment career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cameron_van_der_Burgh"}
{"title_page": "Agent Carter (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Agent Carter\n| image          = Agent Carter One-Shot poster.jpg\n| caption        = Home media release poster\n| director       = Louis D'Esposito\n| producer       = [[Kevin Feige]]\n| screenplay     = [[Eric Pearson]]\n| based on       = {{based on |[[Peggy Carter]]|[[Stan Lee]]|[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Hayley Atwell]]\n* [[Bradley Whitford]]\n* [[Dominic Cooper]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Christopher Lennertz]]\n| cinematography = [[Gabriel Beristain]]\n| editing        = Peter S. Elliot\n| studio         = [[Marvel Studios]]\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Walt Disney Studios<br/>Home Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|9|3|digital|2013|9|24|physical}}\n| runtime        = 15 minutes<ref name=\"Variety\" />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Agent Carter''''' is a 2013 American [[direct-to-video]] [[short film]] featuring the [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Peggy Carter]], produced by [[Marvel Studios]] and distributed by [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment]]. It is a follow up to the 2011 feature film ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'', and is the fourth [[Marvel One-Shots|Marvel One-Shot]] short film. The film is directed by Louis D'Esposito from a screenplay by [[Eric Pearson]], and stars [[Hayley Atwell]] as Carter, along with [[Bradley Whitford]] and [[Dominic Cooper]]. In ''Agent Carter'', Peggy Carter sets out on a solo mission to acquire the mysterious [[Zodiac (comics)|Zodiac]] while facing sexism post-World War II at the SSR, a precursor to [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n\nA Marvel One-Shot featuring Peggy Carter was in the works for some time before Atwell signed on to star in it, reprising her role from the ''Captain America'' films. D'Esposito, co-president of Marvel Studios and an executive producer on the feature films, aimed to replicate the period setting of ''Captain America: The First Avenger'', while also giving the short a more modern, superhero feel. The film was a more ambitious production than previous One-Shots, with more action scenes and visual effects required than previously. Several other characters from Marvel Cinematic Universe films also appear, including Cooper reprising his role of [[Howard Stark]].\n\nThe short was released on the home media release of ''[[Iron Man 3]]'', and was received positively by critics and the audience from an earlier screening at [[San Diego Comic-Con]]. It won a [[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]]. This response led to [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] ordering a television series expansion of the short; ''[[Agent Carter (TV series)|Marvel's Agent Carter]]'' aired from January 2015 to March 2016, over two seasons.\n\n==Plot==\nOne year after the events of ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'',<ref name=\"CBRSDCC\" /> Agent [[Peggy Carter]] is now a member of the Strategic Scientific Reserve (SSR). She faces sexism from her boss, Agent John Flynn, who treats her condescendingly and keeps her compiling data and code breaking while assigning field cases to the male agents. The SSR's main concern is the mysterious [[Zodiac (comics)|Zodiac]], which they have been unable to recover for some time.\n\nOne night alone in the office while the men are out together, Carter answers the case line to hear of the location of the Zodiac. Though three to five agents are recommended, Carter decides to go to the location herself. Fighting off multiple guards, Carter is able to retrieve the Zodiac, a mysterious serum, herself. The next day, Flynn reprimands her for not going through the proper procedures to complete the mission, and dismisses the indignant Carter as just an \"old flame\" of [[Captain America]]'s who was given her current job out of pity for her bereavement. However, before he can officially punish her, the case line rings again, this time with [[Howard Stark]] on the other end, who informs Flynn that Carter will co-head the newly created [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], [[Dum Dum Dugan]] is seen poolside with Stark, marveling at two women wearing the newly created [[bikini]]s.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Hayley Atwell by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|Production on the short began when Hayley Atwell agreed to reprise her role from ''Captain America: The First Avenger''.]]\n\n* [[Hayley Atwell]] as [[Peggy Carter]]: <br />An SSR agent forced to work in data analysis and code breaking since the end of World War II,<ref name=\"TotalFilm\"/> Carter reprises her role from ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]''. On the character starring in her own short film, director [[Louis D'Esposito]] said that Marvel always wanted to do a Peggy Carter short since the character \"was a fan-favorite and a [[Marvel Studios]] favorite\". D'Esposito enjoyed the moment when Carter uses her [[Compact (cosmetics)|compact]] to view the bad guy, which was [[Ad libitum|ad libbed]] during filming, because \"that's the essence of what she's about and what the film's about. Not only is she\u2014especially in that time\u2014a woman in a man's world, she still maintains her femininity\".<ref name=\"MarvelCarter\" />\n* [[Bradley Whitford]] as John Flynn: Carter's SSR boss.<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /><ref name=\"JohnFlynn\" />\n* [[Dominic Cooper]] as [[Howard Stark]]: <br />The co-head and -founder of [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]],<ref name=\"TotalFilm\"/> Cooper reprises his role from ''Captain America: The First Avenger''. In the short, as an [[easter egg (media)|easter egg]], Stark is seen wearing the same robe that his son [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony]] wears in ''[[Iron Man 2]]''.<ref name=\"CBRSDCC\" />\n\n[[Neal McDonough]] reprises his role of [[Dum Dum Dugan|Timothy \"Dum Dum\" Dugan]] from previous [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films|Marvel Cinematic Universe films]], and [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] appears as [[Steve Rogers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Steve Rogers / Captain America]] via archive footage from ''The First Avenger''. [[Shane Black]], director and co-writer of ''[[Iron Man 3]]'', voices the \"Disembodied Voice\", the caller on the other end of the case line.<ref name=\"TotalFilm\"/>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn August 2011, [[Marvel Studios]] announced that a couple of short films would be released [[direct-to-video]],<ref name=\"ShortsAnnouncement\" /> which were designed to be self-contained stories and known as [[Marvel One-Shots]].<ref name=\"Variety\" /> Co-producer Brad Winderbaum said \"It's a fun way to experiment with new characters and ideas, but more importantly it's a way for us to expand the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] and tell stories that live outside the plot of our features.\"<ref name=\"ShortsAnnouncement\" /> One of the ideas developed as a potential One-Shot was a spin-off from ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'', following the story of [[Peggy Carter]] after the events of that film. The idea was looked at again when Marvel was deciding on a short film to produce for the home media release of ''[[Iron Man 3]]'' in 2013, and it was chosen for the spot, dependent on actress [[Hayley Atwell]]'s availability.<ref name=\"Nerdist\" />\n\nMarvel Studios co-president Louis D'Esposito, who directed the previous One-Shot, ''[[Item 47]]'', returned as director,<ref name=\"Nerdist\" /><ref name=\"CarterEW\" /> while writer [[Eric Pearson]] also returned from the previous One-Shots.<ref name=\"CBRSDCC\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" /> D'Esposito noted that the short had twice the budget of ''Item 47'', but the same amount of shooting time so \"the scope of it is much bigger. It's set in a period, there are more actors involved, the scale's bigger, there are three fight scenes\u2014we've never had that in any of [the previous One-Shots].\"<ref name=\"CBRBigger\" /> Atwell agreed to the project after watching ''Item 47'', and due to her love for the character and potential \"to show off some of her skill sets\" that were not seen in the film. Atwell worked for three days with the stunt team to rehearse the pre-choreographed fight sequences for the short.<ref name=\"Collider\" /> D'Esposito elaborated on the decision to focus on Carter, saying, \"It's telling the best story, and finding that story we want to tell\u2014whether it's connectivity to the Marvel Universe, or it's highlighting a character. In the case of Hayley, it's a little bit of both. We wanted to tell Peggy Carter's story\u2014she's been left back in the '40s. Announcing to the world that she was running S.H.I.E.L.D. with Howard Stark is a great connectivity.\"<ref name=\"CBRBigger\" />\n\n===Filming===\n''Agent Carter'' was filmed over five days,<ref name=\"CarterEW\" /> with Gabriel Beristain serving as [[cinematographer]]. The budget did not allow for a storyboard artist to be hired, so D'Esposito, Winderbaum, and Beristain worked together to plan a shot list for the production using stand-in actors. The stunts were also pre-filmed to show the actors. D'Esposito explained that having the shots planned helped with planning the visual effects for the film.<ref name=\"Nerdist\" /> The mid-credits scene with [[Neal McDonough]] as [[Dum Dum Dugan]] was planned to show the character in a pool, but had to be changed on set to taking place beside the pool when it was found that the muscle suit McDonough wears to portray the character could not get wet.<ref name=\"CBRSDCC\" />\n\nD'Esposito chose to differentiate the short from ''The First Avenger'' by avoiding the sepia tone used for that film by director [[Joe Johnston]], instead using a cooler blue color. The production used two old lenses (for both night and day) that gave the short some \"better\" lens flares that D'Esposito felt gave the period setting a more modern feel. D'Esposito used a [[Steadicam]] or a [[camera dolly]] for the action sequences, to avoid a \"quick cutty or blurry or shaky\" feel. D'Esposito said that the crew was ultimately \"pushing our limit\" to get the planned shots on schedule, and he eventually realized that he \"wasn't going to get every shot and I wasn't going to get every punch and kick, so what we do is get the optimum\".<ref name=\"Nerdist\" />\n\n===Post-production===\nVisual effects shots of 1940s New York from ''Captain America: The First Avenger'' were reused in the short for budgetary reasons.<ref name=\"PotentialShortsJuly2013\" /> D'Esposito noted the sequence where Carter comes \"flying with the gun into the door\" and the last fight, when Carter is \"being attacked by the big guy\", were both created with visual effects elements after they ran out of time to complete filming on them on set.<ref name=\"Nerdist\" /> In early 2013, Marvel approached visual effects company Perception to create the main-on-end [[title sequence]] for the short. Visual effects supervisor Sheena Duggal was told to retell the story of the short in 90 seconds, so she decided to use stylized versions of imagery from the period and the short itself. A mixture of 2D and 3D animation was used to achieve a final 2D look.<ref name=\"Perception\" />\n\n==Music==\nComposer [[Christopher Lennertz]], who previously collaborated with D'Esposito on the One-Shot ''Item 47'', composed the music for ''Agent Carter''.<ref name=\"Lennertz\" /> Like the rest of the short, D'Esposito wanted the music to reflect the period setting, but to have a modern feel to it as well, so he sent Lennertz [[Johnny Rivers]]' \"[[Secret Agent Man (Johnny Rivers song)|Secret Agent Man]]\" as a reference track, despite it having been released in the 1960s, since it had the feel and sentiment D'Esposito was looking for.<ref name=\"Nerdist\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Agent Carter'' was first shown in full at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]].<ref name=\"TotalFilm\"/> It was then released on the ''Iron Man 3'' home media, first on September 3, 2013 in [[Digital distribution|digital download]] form, and then on [[Blu-ray disc]] and [[3D Blu-ray]] on September 24, 2013.<ref name=\"HomeMedia\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" /> D'Esposito said that it was decided to release the short along with ''Iron Man 3'' because \"the time was right\", with the ''Iron Man 3'' home media being released before the opening of ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]'' in theaters.<ref name=\"CBRSDCC\" /> It is also included on the bonus-disc of the \"[[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films#Home media|Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Two Collection]]\" [[box set]], which includes all of the [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films#Phase Two|Phase Two]] films in the Marvel Cinematic Universe as well as the other [[Marvel One-Shots]]. The collection features audio commentary from D'Esposito and Atwell, and was released on December 8, 2015.<ref name=\"PhaseTwoBoxset\" />\n\n==Reception==\nRosie Fletcher of ''[[Total Film]]'' noted that the short was well received by the audience at Comic Con, and praised Atwell's performance. She said the short \"looks great and packs some euphoric action moments\".<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> Andy Hunsaker at Crave Online gave the short a score of 8.5 out of 10, calling it a fun treat that \"gives its title character the send-off she deserves\", and hoping that it would lead to further female-focused properties from Marvel.<ref name=\"CraveOnlineAgentCarter\" /> [[IGN]]'s Scott Collura called Atwell \"the big-screen female superhero we've all been waiting for. She kicks so much ass in this short story with such aplomb, using not just brawn but also brains, and it's all very clever and fun.\" He felt the short seemed more of a proof-of-concept that female-based superhero projects could work, but that \"Atwell never loses touch with her feminine side\" either.<ref name=\"IGNAgentCarter\" />\n\nThe Movie Ramblings review of the short highlighted its \"short, sharp and witty script mixed with some equally sharp action\" and D'Esposito's direction, naming it the best Marvel One-Shot at that point.<ref name=\"MovieRamblings\" /> Flickering Myth called the short \"a great effort. A nice, compact story that gives us a lot of great moments with the character.\" The reviewer felt Flynn made a \"great foil\" to Carter, and also noted the \"great cameos and a post credit scene that should put a smile on everybody's face....''Agent Carter'' is another great Marvel offering that shows how committed they are to the idea of an expanded universe where these great characters get time to shine.\"<ref name=\"FlickeringMyth\" />\n\nThe short won the [[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]] for Best Sound & Music Editing: Direct to Video \u2013 Live Action.<ref name=\"GoldenReel\" />\n\n==Television series==\n{{main|Agent Carter (TV series)}}\n''Marvel's Agent Carter'', a television series inspired by the short film also starring Hayley Atwell as Peggy Carter,<ref name=\"CarterTVConfirmed\" /> was ordered by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on May 8, 2014,<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" /> and began its [[Agent Carter (season 1)|first season]] of eight episodes on January 6, 2015.<ref name=\"Jan2015Premiere\" /> [[Dominic Cooper]] and Neal McDonough also reprised their role of Stark and Dugan in the series,<ref name=\"CooperTVOfficial\" /><ref name=\"McDonoughCarterTV\" /> while D'Esposito directed the first episode,<ref name=\"DEspositoTV\" /> and Christopher Lennertz returned to compose the music.<ref name=\"LennertzTVConfirmed\" /> The series was created by [[Christopher Markus & Stephen McFeely]], writers on the ''Captain America'' films, with Tara Butters, Michele Fazekas, and Chris Dingess serving as [[showrunners]].<ref name=\"CarterTVShowrunners\" /> The series takes place in the middle of the short, before Carter learns that she will be co-head of S.H.I.E.L.D.,<ref name=\"AgentCarterMar2014\" /> where she secretly assists Stark with a mission, unbeknownst to the SSR.<ref name=\"TVSynopsis\" /> The series was renewed for a [[Agent Carter (season 2)|second season]] on May 7, 2015,<ref name=\"S2Renewal\" /> consisting of 10 episodes.<ref name=\"S2Episodes\" /> ABC canceled ''Agent Carter'' on May 12, 2016.<ref name=\"TVSeriesCanceled\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"MarvelCarter\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/7/11/20872/agent_carter_lines_up_her_one-shot |title=Agent Carter Lines Up Her One-Shot |last=Strom |first=Marc |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OwWFenHq?url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/7/11/20872/agent_carter_lines_up_her_one-shot |archivedate=April 19, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TotalFilm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/marvel-s-agent-carter-one-shot-comic-con-2013-reaction |title=Marvel's Agent Carter reaction: Comic-Con 2013 |last=Fletcher |first=Rosie |work=[[Total Film]] |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OwXFbpwe?url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/marvel-s-agent-carter-one-shot-comic-con-2013-reaction |archivedate=April 19, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CarterEW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2013/07/11/marvel-one-shot-agent-carter-first-look/ |title='Marvel One-Shot: Agent Carter' \u2013 First Look at poster and three photos from the new short! |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=April 19, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OwXCPg3t?url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/07/11/marvel-one-shot-agent-carter-first-look/2/ |archivedate=April 19, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Lennertz\">{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/blog/2014/06/21/agent-carter-one-shot-composer-likely-headed-to-the-tv-series/ |title=Agent Carter