/tv/23612/marvels_agent_carter_marvels_agents_of_shield_set_premiere_return_dates |title=Marvel's Agent Carter & Marvel's Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. Set Premiere & Return Dates |last=Strom |first=Marc |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=November 5, 2014 |accessdate=November 6, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TtADAkLv?url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23612/marvels_agent_carter_marvels_agents_of_shield_set_premiere_return_dates |archivedate=November 6, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CooperTVOfficial\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23371/dominic_cooper_returns_as_howard_stark_in_marvels_agent_carter |title=Dominic Cooper Returns as Howard Stark in Marvel's Agent Carter |last=Strom |first=Marc |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=September 30, 2014 |accessdate=September 30, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SykKthrI?url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23371/dominic_cooper_returns_as_howard_stark_in_marvels_agent_carter |archivedate=September 30, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LennertzTVConfirmed\">{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/09/04/christopher-lennertz-to-score-marvels-agent-carter-tv-series/ |title=Christopher Lennertz to Score Marvel's \u2018Agent Carter\u2019 TV Series |publisher=Film Music Reporter |date=September 4, 2014 |accessdate=September 27, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6StDeHWqd?url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/09/04/christopher-lennertz-to-score-marvels-agent-carter-tv-series/ |archivedate=September 27, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DEspositoTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/21704-sdcc-2014-cap-1-and-2-directors-returning-to-direct-episodes-of-agent-carter.html |title=Major S.H.I.E.L.D. Casting Additions ... Plus a Surprise Avenger? |last=Arrant |first=Chris |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |date=July 25, 2014 |accessdate=July 25, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RLEagkZg?url=http://www.newsarama.com/21704-sdcc-2014-cap-1-and-2-directors-returning-to-direct-episodes-of-agent-carter.html |archivedate=July 25, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AgentCarterMar2014\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/agent-carter-tv-series-christopher-markus-stephen-mcfeely/ |title=Screenwriters Christopher Markus and Stephen McFeely Talk Agent Carter TV Series; Reveal Timeline, Plot and Planned Episode Count |last=Weintraub |first=Steve |publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=March 13, 2014 |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O3QNjO0I?url=http://collider.com/agent-carter-tv-series-christopher-markus-stephen-mcfeely/ |archivedate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TVSynopsis\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23536/see_whats_in_store_for_marvels_agent_carter_in_the_official_series_synopsis |title=See What's in Store for Marvel's Agent Carter in the Official Series Synopsis |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=October 27, 2014 |accessdate=October 27, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TeJvWFhF?url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23536/see_whats_in_store_for_marvels_agent_carter_in_the_official_series_synopsis |archivedate=October 28, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CarterTVShowrunners\">{{cite web|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/tv/agent-carter-hayley-atwell-reprises-capable-1940s-spy-for-marvel-tv-show/#/0 |title=\u2018Agent Carter': Hayley Atwell reprises capable 1940s spy for Marvel TV show |last=McIntrye |first=Gina |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 2, 2015 |accessdate=January 3, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VJSpovgW?url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/tv/agent-carter-hayley-atwell-reprises-capable-1940s-spy-for-marvel-tv-show/ |archivedate=January 3, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PhaseTwoBoxset\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/mcu-phase-2-box-set-image-bonus-features/ |title=\u2018Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Two Collection\u2019 Unveiled; Contains First Look at Phase 3 |last=Goldberg |first=Matt |publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=October 23, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cV3n4hc2?url=http://collider.com/mcu-phase-2-box-set-image-bonus-features/ |archivedate=October 23, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"S2Renewal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-renews-agents-shield-agent-792905 |title=ABC Renews 'Agents of SHIELD,' 'Agent Carter' |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 7, 2015 |accessdate=May 7, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YMUUba1y?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-renews-agents-shield-agent-792905 |archivedate=May 8, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"S2Episodes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s263/marvels-agent-carter/news/a648968/hayley-atwell-reveals-agent-carter-season-2-will-consist-of-10-episodes.html#~pdxSa6i4Xmg0tz |title=Hayley Atwell reveals Agent Carter season 2 will consist of 10 episodes |last=Finbow |first=Kelly |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |date=May 23, 2015 |accessdate=May 23, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YkUVpqqj?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s263/marvels-agent-carter/news/a648968/hayley-atwell-reveals-agent-carter-season-2-will-consist-of-10-episodes.html |archivedate=May 23, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GoldenReel\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/scene/news/mpse-golden-reel-awards-captain-phillips-gravity-the-great-gatsby-win-sound-editors-awards-1201108843/ |title=MPSE Golden Reel Awards: \u2018Captain Phillips,\u2019 \u2018Gravity,\u2019 \u2018The Great Gatsby\u2019 Win Sound Editors Awards |last=Johns |first=Nikara |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=February 17, 2014 |accessdate=May 3, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6hDXo2aeE?url=http://variety.com/2014/scene/news/mpse-golden-reel-awards-captain-phillips-gravity-the-great-gatsby-win-sound-editors-awards-1201108843/ |archivedate=May 3, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TVSeriesCanceled\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agent-carter-canceled-at-abc-893499 |title='Agent Carter' Canceled at ABC |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=May 12, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6hSgAdlC6?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agent-carter-canceled-at-abc-893499 |archivedate=May 13, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"JohnFlynn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/56889-what-happened-to-peggy-carter-in-captain-america-agent-carter-will-fill-in-the-gaps |title=What Happened To Peggy Carter in 'Captain America'? 'Agent Carter' Will Fill in the Gaps |last=Thomas |first=Leah |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=January 6, 2015 |accessdate=June 8, 2017 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6r4Ym4Zwr?url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/56889-what-happened-to-peggy-carter-in-captain-america-agent-carter-will-fill-in-the-gaps |archivedate=June 8, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"McDonoughCarterTV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=58275 |title=The Howling Commandos Return in New \"Agent Carter\" Promo |last=White |first=Brett |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VPbgy5au?url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=58275 |archivedate=January 7, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|3067038}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Peggy Carter}}\n{{Marvel Cinematic Universe}}\n{{Marvel Comics films}}\n{{Captain America}}\n\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 short films]]\n[[Category:2010s superhero films]]\n[[Category:Buena Vista Home Entertainment direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Christopher Lennertz]]\n[[Category:Marvel One-Shots]]\n[[Category:Peggy Carter]]\n[[Category:Captain America (film series)]]\n", "name_user": "Favre1fan93", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agent_Carter_(film)"}
{"title_page": "State Theatre Company of South Australia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\nThe '''State Theatre Company of South Australia''' ('''STCSA'''), formerly the '''South Australian Theatre Company''' ('''SATC'''), is [[South Australia]]'s leading professional [[theatre company]], and a [[statutory corporation]]. It was established as the official state theatre company by the ''State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972'', on the initiative of Premier [[Don Dunstan]].\n\nMany of the performances are staged at the Dunstan Playhouse and Space Theatre at the [[Adelaide Festival Centre]]. {{as of|2019}} the artistic director is Mitchell Butel. Notable actors, writers and directors, working with the Company have included [[Patrick White]], [[Neil Armfield]], [[Ruth Cracknell]], [[Andrew Bovell]],  [[Judy Davis]], [[Gale Edwards]], [[Mel Gibson]], [[Geoffrey Rush]], [[Jim Sharman]], [[Hugo Weaving]], [[Elena Carapetis]] and [[John Wood (Australian actor)|John Wood]].\n\n=={{anchor|history}}History==\nThe South Australian Theatre Company (SATC) was established in 1965 under the artistic direction of [[John Tasker (theatre director)|John Tasker]]. Tasker directed 10 plays before clashing with the Board and leaving in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University. National Centre of Biography|others=First published in hardcopy in Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 18, (MUP), 2012|first=Margaret|last=Leask|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/tasker-john-howard-15686|title=Tasker, John Howard (1933\u20131988)|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Actor Leslie Dayman took over from Tasker and Peter Batey followed Dayman.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe date of establishment as the state theatre company dates from the ''State Theatre Company of South Australia Act of 1972'',<ref>{{cite document|format=PDF|url=https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/lz/c/a/state%20theatre%20company%20of%20south%20australia%20act%201972/current/1972.38.auth.pdf|title=State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972, Version: 12.5.2011|date=2011|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=resp>{{cite web|publisher=Government of South Australia. Attorney-General's Dept|website=legislation.sa|url=https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/LZ/C/A/STATE%20THEATRE%20COMPANY%20OF%20SOUTH%20AUSTRALIA%20ACT%201972.aspx|title=State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> an initiative of then Premier Dunstan. The name of the company was changed to its current name in 1978{{#tag:ref|Although as of 2 August 2019, the About page, History section, cites 1980 as the date of the name change, quoting a 2004 work, the [[State Library of South Australia]] catalogue shows several works attributed to the STCSA name from 1978, and notes [https://encore.slsa.sa.gov.au/iii/encore/record/C__Rb2808963__Ssouth%20australian%20theatre%20company__Orightresult__U__X7?lang=eng&suite=cobalt here] that the entity \"appears to be operating under State Theatre Company name from August 1978\".|group=Note}} as a reflection of this Act.<ref>{{cite web|website=State Library of South Australia|url=https://encore.slsa.sa.gov.au/iii/encore/record/C__Rb2808963__Ssouth%20australian%20theatre%20company__Orightresult__U__X7?lang=eng&suite=cobalt|title=South Australian Theatre Company : [ephemera collection] |access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> The director of the company in its inaugural year was [[George Ogilvie]].<ref name=STChist>{{cite book|first=Geoffrey|date=2004|series=Australian playwrights ; monograph no. 10 |others=Series editor Veronica Kelly|last=Milne|title=Theatre Australia (un)limited: Australian theatre since the 1950s|via=State Theatre of South Australia: About|url=https://statetheatrecompany.com.au/about/|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, the SATC became the inaugural resident theatre company of the Adelaide Festival Centre, performing mostly in The Playhouse (later The Dunstan Playhouse and still the company's primary venue), and was the first state theatre company in Australia to hold its entire operations in one purpose-made building.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nIn 1977, '''Magpie Theatre''' was established as a [[theatre in education]] (TIE) branch of STCSA, for young people. After 20 years and numerous productions,<ref>{{cite web|website=Ausstage: The Australian Live Performance Database|title=Magpie Theatre Company|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/organisation/52|access-date=2 August 2019 \t\t\t\t\t\t\t \t\t\t\t\t\t\t}}</ref> it was terminated in 1997, partially due to loss of funding after reconstruction of [[Arts SA]].<ref name=STChist/>\n\nUnder the artistic direction of [[Jim Sharman]], the company was renamed '''Lighthouse''' from 1982\u20131983, operating as an ensemble theatre company with twelve actors: Robynne Bourne, [[Peter Cummins]], [[Melissa Jaffer]] (replaced in 1983 by Jacqy Phillips), [[Alan John]], [[Gillian Jones]], Melita Jurisic, [[Russell Kiefel]], Stuart McCreery, [[Robert Menzies (actor)|Robert Menzies]] (replaced by [[Robert Grubb]]), Geoffrey Rush, [[Kerry Walker]] and John Wood.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nThe company was subtitled '''Australian Playhouse''' from 1996\u20131997 during the tenure of Chris Westwood, the Company's first female Executive Producer, appointed in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|website=murraybramwell.com|url=https://murraybramwell.com/?p=2280|title=A head full of new ideas|date=1 December 1993|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> She aimed at presenting only Australian works until the end of the century; however, she resigned at the end of 1997.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nThe Board reported to [[Arts SA]] (later Arts South Australia) from 1993 until 2018, when it started reporting directly to the [[Department of the Premier and Cabinet (South Australia)|Department of the Premier and Cabinet]].<ref name=resp/><ref>{{cite web|website=South Australia. Dept of the Premier and Cabinet|url=https://dpc.sa.gov.au/responsibilities/arts-and-culture/about-arts-culture|title=About arts and culture|access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\n{{as of| 2019}}, the Company's administration offices are based at the [[Lion Arts Centre]], on the corner of [[Morphett Street, Adelaide|Morphett Street]] and [[North Terrace, Adelaide]].<ref name=venues>{{cite web|website=State Theatre of South Australia|title=Venues|url=https://statetheatrecompany.com.au/venues/|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's main venue is still the Dunstan Playhouse, but it also uses the Space Theatre, the Royalty Theatre in [[Angas Street, Adelaide]], [[Her Majesty's Theatre, Adelaide|Her Majesty's Theatre]] in Gouger Street, the Odeon Theatre in [[Norwood, South Australia|Norwood]], the Matthew Flinders Theatre at [[Flinders University]] and the Keith Michell Theatre in [[Port Pirie, South Australia]].<ref name=venues/>\n\n==Directors==\n*[[John Tasker (theatre director)|John Tasker]] (1965\u201367)\n*[[Leslie Dayman]] (1968\u201369)\n*Peter Batey (1970\u201371)\n*[[George Ogilvie]] (1972\u20131976)\n*Colin George (1977\u20131979)\n*Kevin Palmer (Artistic Director), [[Nick Enright]] (Associate Director) (1980\u201381) \n*[[Jim Sharman]] (Artistic Director), [[Neil Armfield]] and [[Louis Nowra]] (Associates) (1982\u201383) (as '''Lighthouse''')\n*Keith Gallasch (1984\u201385)\n*[[John Gaden]] (Artistic), [[Gale Edwards]] (Associate) (1986\u201389) \n*[[Simon Phillips (director)|Simon Phillips]] (1990\u201393)\n*Chris Westwood (Executive Producer) (1994\u201397)\n*Rodney Fisher (1998\u201399)\n*Rosalba Clemente (2000\u201304)\n*Adam Cook (2005\u20132012)\n*[[Geordie Brookman]] (2013\u20132018)\n*[[Mitchell Butel]] (2019 - present).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-12-18/mitchell-butel-named-new-artistic-director-state-theatre-company/10626686|title=Mitchell Butel named new artistic director of State Theatre Company.|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=18 December 2018|newspaper=ABC News|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n'''Associate Directors'''\n*Michael Hill (2006 - 2008)\n*Geordie Brookman (2008 - 2010)\n*Catherine Fitzgerald (2011)\n*Nescha Jelk (2013\u20132016)\n\n==New works==\nShows which have been developed by and/or have had their world premiere at STCSA include:\n* 2016 - ''[[Things I Know to Be True|Things I Know To Be True]]'' by [[Andrew Bovell]] (co-production with UK's [[Frantic Assembly]])\n* 2009 - ''[[Metro Street]]'' by [[Matthew Robinson (performer and composer)|Matthew Robinson]]\n* 2009 - ''[[Maestro (novel)|Maestro]]'' by [[Anna Goldsworthy]] and [[Peter Goldsworthy]] \n* 2008 - ''Architektin'' by [[Robyn Archer]]\n* 2008 - ''[[When the Rain Stops Falling|When The Rain Stops Falling]]'' by Andrew Bovell (co-presentation with [[Brink Productions]])\n* 2007 - ''Lion Pig Lion'' by Marty Denniss \n* 2006 - ''Honk If You Are Jesus'' by [[Peter Goldsworthy]] and Martin Laud Gray (winner of the 2006 Ruby Award for Best New Work or Event) \n* 2004 - ''Euripides' Trojan Women'' adapted by Rosalba Clemente and Dawn Langman \n* 2004 - ''Night Letters'' by Robert Dessaix adapted by Susan Rogers and Chris Drummond \n* 2003 - ''drowning in my ocean of You'' by Fiona Sprott \n* 2002 - ''My Life, My Love'' by Pat Rix \n* 2001 - ''Holy Day'' by Andrew Bovell  (winner of 2 [[Green Room Awards]])\n* 1986 - ''Dreams In An Empty City'' by [[Stephen Sewell (writer)|Stephen Sewell]]\n* 1985 - ''Beautland'' by [[Barry Dickins]]\n* 1983 - ''Sunrise'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1983 - ''[[The Blind Giant is Dancing|The Blind Giant Is Dancing]]'' by [[Stephen Sewell (writer)|Stephen Sewell]]\n* 1983 - ''Netherwood'' by [[Patrick White]]\n* 1982 - ''Spellbound'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1982 - ''Royal Show'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1982 - ''Signal Driver: A Morality Play for the Times'' by [[Patrick White]]\n* 1978 - ''A Manual of Trench Warfare'' by Clem Gorman\n* 1978 - ''Marx'' by Ron Blair\n* 1976 - ''[[A Handful of Friends]]'' by [[David Williamson]]\n* 1974 - ''[[The Department (play)|The Department]]'' by [[David Williamson]]\n\nIn addition, the company supports new work through its annual Young Playwrights' Award (formally Young Guns competition) for writers under 25, offering dramaturgy and a professional reading to the winning script, and the Jill Blewett Playwright's Award for the Creative Development of a play script by a South Australian Writer, presented at [[Adelaide Writer's Week]] during the [[Adelaide Festival]].\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | first=Peter|last=Ward| title = A singular act : twenty five years of the State Theatre Company of South Australia| publisher = Adelaide : State Theatre : Wakefield Press| year = 1992| isbn =  1-862-54273-2  }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080209171612/http://www.statetheatrecompany.com.au/Default.aspx?p=1 State Theatre Company]\n\n[[Category:Theatre companies in Australia]]\n[[Category:Performing arts in Adelaide]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\nThe '''State Theatre Company of South Australia''' ('''STCSA'''), formerly the '''South Australian Theatre Company''' ('''SATC'''), is [[South Australia]]'s leading professional [[theatre company]], and a [[statutory corporation]]. It was established as the official state theatre company by the ''State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972'', on the initiative of Premier [[Don Dunstan]].\n\nMany of the performances are staged at the Dunstan Playhouse and Space Theatre at the [[Adelaide Festival Centre]]. {{as of|2019}} the artistic director is Mitchell Butel. Notable actors, writers and directors, working with the Company have included [[Patrick White]], [[Neil Armfield]], [[Ruth Cracknell]], [[Andrew Bovell]],  [[Judy Davis]], [[Gale Edwards]], [[Mel Gibson]], [[Geoffrey Rush]], [[Jim Sharman]], [[Hugo Weaving]], [[Elena Carapetis]] and [[John Wood (Australian actor)|John Wood]].\n\n=={{anchor|history}}History==\nThe South Australian Theatre Company (SATC) was established in 1965 under the artistic direction of [[John Tasker (theatre director)|John Tasker]]. Tasker directed 10 plays before clashing with the Board and leaving in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University. National Centre of Biography|others=First published in hardcopy in Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 18, (MUP), 2012|first=Margaret|last=Leask|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/tasker-john-howard-15686|title=Tasker, John Howard (1933\u20131988)|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Actor Leslie Dayman took over from Tasker and Peter Batey followed Dayman.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe date of establishment as the state theatre company dates from the ''State Theatre Company of South Australia Act of 1972'',<ref>{{cite document|format=PDF|url=https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/lz/c/a/state%20theatre%20company%20of%20south%20australia%20act%201972/current/1972.38.auth.pdf|title=State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972, Version: 12.5.2011|date=2011|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=resp>{{cite web|publisher=Government of South Australia. Attorney-General's Dept|website=legislation.sa|url=https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/LZ/C/A/STATE%20THEATRE%20COMPANY%20OF%20SOUTH%20AUSTRALIA%20ACT%201972.aspx|title=State Theatre Company of South Australia Act 1972|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> an initiative of then Premier Dunstan. The name of the company was changed to its current name in 1978{{#tag:ref|Although as of 2 August 2019, the About page, History section, cites 1980 as the date of the name change, quoting a 2004 work, the [[State Library of South Australia]] catalogue shows several works attributed to the STCSA name from 1978, and notes [https://encore.slsa.sa.gov.au/iii/encore/record/C__Rb2808963__Ssouth%20australian%20theatre%20company__Orightresult__U__X7?lang=eng&suite=cobalt here] that the entity \"appears to be operating under State Theatre Company name from August 1978\".|group=Note}} as a reflection of this Act.<ref>{{cite web|website=State Library of South Australia|url=https://encore.slsa.sa.gov.au/iii/encore/record/C__Rb2808963__Ssouth%20australian%20theatre%20company__Orightresult__U__X7?lang=eng&suite=cobalt|title=South Australian Theatre Company : [ephemera collection] |access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> The director of the company in its inaugural year was [[George Ogilvie]].<ref name=STChist>{{cite book|first=Geoffrey|date=2004|series=Australian playwrights ; monograph no. 10 |others=Series editor Veronica Kelly|last=Milne|title=Theatre Australia (un)limited: Australian theatre since the 1950s|via=State Theatre of South Australia: About|url=https://statetheatrecompany.com.au/about/|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, the SATC became the inaugural resident theatre company of the Adelaide Festival Centre, performing mostly in The Playhouse (later The Dunstan Playhouse and still the company's primary venue), and was the first state theatre company in Australia to hold its entire operations in one purpose-made building.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nIn 1977, '''Magpie Theatre''' was established as a [[theatre in education]] (TIE) branch of STCSA, for young people. After 20 years and numerous productions,<ref>{{cite web|website=Ausstage: The Australian Live Performance Database|title=Magpie Theatre Company|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/organisation/52|access-date=2 August 2019 \t\t\t\t\t\t\t \t\t\t\t\t\t\t}}</ref> it was terminated in 1997, partially due to loss of funding after reconstruction of [[Arts SA]].<ref name=STChist/>\n\nUnder the artistic direction of [[Jim Sharman]], the company was renamed '''Lighthouse''' from 1982\u20131983, operating as an ensemble theatre company with twelve actors: Robynne Bourne, [[Peter Cummins]], [[Melissa Jaffer]] (replaced in 1983 by Jacqy Phillips), [[Alan John]], [[Gillian Jones]], Melita Jurisic, Russell Kiefel, Stuart McCreery, [[Robert Menzies (actor)|Robert Menzies]] (replaced by [[Robert Grubb]]), Geoffrey Rush, [[Kerry Walker]] and John Wood.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nThe company was subtitled '''Australian Playhouse''' from 1996\u20131997 during the tenure of Chris Westwood, the Company's first female Executive Producer, appointed in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|website=murraybramwell.com|url=https://murraybramwell.com/?p=2280|title=A head full of new ideas|date=1 December 1993|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> She aimed at presenting only Australian works until the end of the century; however, she resigned at the end of 1997.<ref name=STChist/>\n\nThe Board reported to [[Arts SA]] (later Arts South Australia) from 1993 until 2018, when it started reporting directly to the [[Department of the Premier and Cabinet (South Australia)|Department of the Premier and Cabinet]].<ref name=resp/><ref>{{cite web|website=South Australia. Dept of the Premier and Cabinet|url=https://dpc.sa.gov.au/responsibilities/arts-and-culture/about-arts-culture|title=About arts and culture|access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Venues==\n{{as of| 2019}}, the Company's administration offices are based at the [[Lion Arts Centre]], on the corner of [[Morphett Street, Adelaide|Morphett Street]] and [[North Terrace, Adelaide]].<ref name=venues>{{cite web|website=State Theatre of South Australia|title=Venues|url=https://statetheatrecompany.com.au/venues/|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's main venue is still the Dunstan Playhouse, but it also uses the Space Theatre, the Royalty Theatre in [[Angas Street, Adelaide]], [[Her Majesty's Theatre, Adelaide|Her Majesty's Theatre]] in Gouger Street, the Odeon Theatre in [[Norwood, South Australia|Norwood]], the Matthew Flinders Theatre at [[Flinders University]] and the Keith Michell Theatre in [[Port Pirie, South Australia]].<ref name=venues/>\n\n==Directors==\n*[[John Tasker (theatre director)|John Tasker]] (1965\u201367)\n*[[Leslie Dayman]] (1968\u201369)\n*Peter Batey (1970\u201371)\n*[[George Ogilvie]] (1972\u20131976)\n*Colin George (1977\u20131979)\n*Kevin Palmer (Artistic Director), [[Nick Enright]] (Associate Director) (1980\u201381) \n*[[Jim Sharman]] (Artistic Director), [[Neil Armfield]] and [[Louis Nowra]] (Associates) (1982\u201383) (as '''Lighthouse''')\n*Keith Gallasch (1984\u201385)\n*[[John Gaden]] (Artistic), [[Gale Edwards]] (Associate) (1986\u201389) \n*[[Simon Phillips (director)|Simon Phillips]] (1990\u201393)\n*Chris Westwood (Executive Producer) (1994\u201397)\n*Rodney Fisher (1998\u201399)\n*Rosalba Clemente (2000\u201304)\n*Adam Cook (2005\u20132012)\n*[[Geordie Brookman]] (2013\u20132018)\n*[[Mitchell Butel]] (2019 - present).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-12-18/mitchell-butel-named-new-artistic-director-state-theatre-company/10626686|title=Mitchell Butel named new artistic director of State Theatre Company.|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=18 December 2018|newspaper=ABC News|accessdate=}}</ref> \n\n'''Associate Directors'''\n*Michael Hill (2006 - 2008)\n*Geordie Brookman (2008 - 2010)\n*Catherine Fitzgerald (2011)\n*Nescha Jelk (2013\u20132016)\n\n==New works==\nShows which have been developed by and/or have had their world premiere at STCSA include:\n* 2016 - ''[[Things I Know to Be True|Things I Know To Be True]]'' by [[Andrew Bovell]] (co-production with UK's [[Frantic Assembly]])\n* 2009 - ''[[Metro Street]]'' by [[Matthew Robinson (performer and composer)|Matthew Robinson]]\n* 2009 - ''[[Maestro (novel)|Maestro]]'' by [[Anna Goldsworthy]] and [[Peter Goldsworthy]] \n* 2008 - ''Architektin'' by [[Robyn Archer]]\n* 2008 - ''[[When the Rain Stops Falling|When The Rain Stops Falling]]'' by Andrew Bovell (co-presentation with [[Brink Productions]])\n* 2007 - ''Lion Pig Lion'' by Marty Denniss \n* 2006 - ''Honk If You Are Jesus'' by [[Peter Goldsworthy]] and Martin Laud Gray (winner of the 2006 Ruby Award for Best New Work or Event) \n* 2004 - ''Euripides' Trojan Women'' adapted by Rosalba Clemente and Dawn Langman \n* 2004 - ''Night Letters'' by Robert Dessaix adapted by Susan Rogers and Chris Drummond \n* 2003 - ''drowning in my ocean of You'' by Fiona Sprott \n* 2002 - ''My Life, My Love'' by Pat Rix \n* 2001 - ''Holy Day'' by Andrew Bovell  (winner of 2 [[Green Room Awards]])\n* 1986 - ''Dreams In An Empty City'' by [[Stephen Sewell (writer)|Stephen Sewell]]\n* 1985 - ''Beautland'' by [[Barry Dickins]]\n* 1983 - ''Sunrise'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1983 - ''[[The Blind Giant is Dancing|The Blind Giant Is Dancing]]'' by [[Stephen Sewell (writer)|Stephen Sewell]]\n* 1983 - ''Netherwood'' by [[Patrick White]]\n* 1982 - ''Spellbound'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1982 - ''Royal Show'' by [[Louis Nowra]]\n* 1982 - ''Signal Driver: A Morality Play for the Times'' by [[Patrick White]]\n* 1978 - ''A Manual of Trench Warfare'' by Clem Gorman\n* 1978 - ''Marx'' by Ron Blair\n* 1976 - ''[[A Handful of Friends]]'' by [[David Williamson]]\n* 1974 - ''[[The Department (play)|The Department]]'' by [[David Williamson]]\n\nIn addition, the company supports new work through its annual Young Playwrights' Award (formally Young Guns competition) for writers under 25, offering dramaturgy and a professional reading to the winning script, and the Jill Blewett Playwright's Award for the Creative Development of a play script by a South Australian Writer, presented at [[Adelaide Writer's Week]] during the [[Adelaide Festival]].\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | first=Peter|last=Ward| title = A singular act : twenty five years of the State Theatre Company of South Australia| publisher = Adelaide : State Theatre : Wakefield Press| year = 1992| isbn =  1-862-54273-2  }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080209171612/http://www.statetheatrecompany.com.au/Default.aspx?p=1 State Theatre Company]\n\n[[Category:Theatre companies in Australia]]\n[[Category:Performing arts in Adelaide]]\n", "name_user": "JuneGloom07", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/State_Theatre_Company_of_South_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Rabbit haemorrhagic disease", "text_new": "{{Virusbox\n| image = Emd-1933.jpg\n| image_alt = CryoEM reconstruction of \"Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\" (RHDV) capsid. EMDB entry EMD-1933\n| image_caption = [[CryoEM]] reconstruction of ''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus'' (RHDV) [[capsid]]. [[EMDB]] entry {{PDBe|EMD-1933}}<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Luque | first1 = D. \n| last2 = Gonz\u00e1lez | first2 = J. M. \n| last3 = G\u00f3mez-Blanco | first3 = J. \n| last4 = Marabini | first4 = R. \n| last5 = Chich\u00f3n | first5 = J. \n| last6 = Mena | first6 = I. \n| last7 = Angulo | first7 = I. \n| last8 = Carrascosa | first8 = J. L. \n| last9 = Verdaguer | first9 = N. \n| last10 = Trus | first10 = B. L. \n| last11 = B\u00e1rcena | first11 = J. \n| last12 = Cast\u00f3n | first12 = J. R. \n| doi = 10.1128/JVI.07050-11 \n| title = Epitope Insertion at the N-Terminal Molecular Switch of the Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus T=3 Capsid Protein Leads to Larger T=4 Capsids \n| journal = Journal of Virology \n| volume = 86 \n| issue = 12 \n| pages = 6470\u20136480 \n| year = 2012 \n| pmid = 22491457 \n| pmc =3393579 \n| url = https://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/87867/1/Epitope%20insertion.pdf}}</ref>\n| taxon = Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\n| authority = \n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = Isolates\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Caliciviridae\">{{cite web |title=ICTV 9th Report (2011) ''Caliciviridae'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/253/caliciviridae |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |accessdate=9 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| subdivision = \n*RHDV [FRG/89] (RHDV-FRG)\n*RCV [ITL/95] (RHDV-RCV)\n*RCV-A1 [MIC-07/2007/AU] (RHDV-RCV-A1)\n*RHDV [Ashington/1998/UK] (RHDV-Ash)\n}}\n[[File:CSIRO ScienceImage 2009 Rabbit Calicivirus.jpg|thumb|Rabbit Calicivirus <small>CSIRO</small>]]\n\n'''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease''' ('''RHD''') is a highly infectious and lethal form of viral hepatitis that affects European rabbits ''(Oryctolagus cuniculus)''. Mortality rates in adult rabbits generally range from 70 to 100 percent.<ref name=Capucci2017>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Cavadini |first2=P. |last3=Schiavitto |first3=M. |last4=Lombardi |first4=G. |last5=Lavazza |first5=A. |title=Increased pathogenicity in rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus type 2 (RHDV2) |journal=Veterinary Record |date=29 April 2017 |volume=180 |issue=17 |page=426 |doi=10.1136/vr.104132}}</ref> The disease is caused by the [[lagovirus]] '''rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus''' ('''RHDV''') in the family [[Caliciviridae]]. The virus infects only rabbits, and has been used in some countries to control feral rabbit populations.\n\n== RHDVa and RHDV-2 ==\n\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease viruses (RHDV) are single strand RNA viruses in the genus Lagovirus and the family Caliciviridae. In the course of its evolution RHDV split into six distinct genotypes,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kerr |first1=P. J. |last2=Kitchen |first2=A. |last3=Holmes |first3=E. C. |title=Origin and Phylodynamics of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus |journal=Journal of Virology |date=16 September 2009 |volume=83 |issue=23 |pages=12129\u201312138 |doi=10.1128/JVI.01523-09|doi-access=free }}</ref> all of which are highly pathogenic. In addition, non-pathogenic rabbit caliciviruses related to but distinct from RHDV have been identified in Europe and Australia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Fusi |first2=P. |last3=Lavazza |first3=A. |last4=Pacciarini |first4=M.L. |last5=Rossi |first5=C. |title=Detection and preliminary characterization of a new rabbit calicivirus related to rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus but nonpathogenic |journal=Journal of Virology |date=December 1996 |volume=70 |issue=12 |pages=8614-8623}}</ref> Rabbit lagoviruses also include related caliciviruses such as European brown hare syndrome virus.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gleeson |first1=Molly |last2=Petritz |first2=Olivia A. |title=Emerging Infectious Diseases of Rabbits |journal=Veterinary Clinics of North America: Exotic Animal Practice |date=May 2020 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=249\u2013261 |doi=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cvex.2020.01.008}}</ref>\n\nThe two strains of rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus currently of medical significance are RHDVa and RHDV-2. RHDVa (also referred to as RHDV, RHDV1, or as classical RHD) only affects adult European rabbits (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''). This virus was first reported in China in 1984,<ref name=Liu1984>{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=S.J. |last2=Xue |first2=H.P. |last3=Pu |first3=B.Q. |last4=Qian |first4=N.H. |title=A new viral disease in rabbits |journal=Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Medicine (Xumu yu Shouyi) |date=1984 |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=253-255}}</ref> from which it spread to much of Asia, Europe, Australia, and elsewhere. There have been a few isolated outbreaks of RHDVa in the United States and Mexico, but they remained localized and were eradicated.\n\nIn 2010, a new lagovirus with a distinct antigenic profile was identified in France. This virus also caused rabbit hemorrhagic disease but behaved differently from RHDVa in that it affected vaccinated and young European rabbits as well as hares ''(Lepus spp.)''.<ref name=Capucci2017 /> All these features strongly suggested that the virus was not derived from RHDVa but from some other unknown source.<ref name=Capucci2017 />  The new virus was named rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (abbreviated as RHDV-2 or RHDVb). RHDV-2 is distinct enough from RHDVa that the two require different vaccines, which are only partially cross protective. Besides affecting the European rabbit, RHDV-2 has caused disease in Sardinian Cape hares ''(Lepus capensis mediterraneus)'', Italian hares ''(Lepus corsicanus)'' and mountain hares ''(Lepus timidus)''.\n<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> RHDV-2 has since spread to the majority of Europe as well as to Australia, Canada, and the United States.\n\n== History ==\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDVa first appeared in the Winter of 1983 in Jiangsu Province of the [[People's Republic of China]]. The virus was first isolated and characterized by S.J. Liu ''et al''. in 1984.<ref name=Merck>{{cite web | title = A New Viral Disease of Rabbit| work = The Merck Veterinary Manual | year = 2006 | url = http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/171330.htm | accessdate = 2007-06-17 }}</ref> The Chinese outbreak was spread by the [[angora rabbit]], which had originated in [[Europe]]. Fourteen million domesticated rabbits died within nine months in the outbreak.<ref name=IAS>[http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/rabbit_hemorrhagic_disease.pdf Center for Food Security and Public Health]</ref>\n\nFrom China, RHDVa spread westward and reached Europe in 1988. The virus has since appeared in Mexico, [[Cuba]], Australia, New Zealand, the United States and Canada.<ref name=Merck/> In 1992, the United Kingdom reported its first case of RHDVa in domestic show rabbits. By the late 1990s, RHDVa stretched to forty countries and had become [[endemic]] in [[Wild animal|wild]] and [[feral]] rabbit populations in Europe, Australia, New Zealand and [[Cuba]].<ref name=IAS/> In Europe, there was a rapid increase in research into RHD, due to the importance of the commercial breeding of rabbits for meat and fur production.\n\nThe first reported case of RHDVa in the United States was in Iowa on March 9, 2000. The affected breeds included [[List of rabbit breeds|Palominos]] and [[Californian rabbit|California Whites]]. By April 6, 25 of the 27 affected rabbits had died of the infection. In order to contain the disease, the remaining two rabbits were euthanized. No new introductions of rabbits were placed on the farm for two years after the discovery of RHDVa and August 1999 was the last time rabbits left and/or returned to the farm. The United States experienced other outbreaks of RHDVa in 2001 ([[Utah]], [[Illinois]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) and 2005 ([[Indiana]]).<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn 2010, a new virus variant called rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV-2) emerged in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Le Gall-Recul\u00e9|first=Ghislaine|last2=Lavazza|first2=Antonio|last3=Marchandeau|first3=St\u00e9phane|last4=Bertagnoli|first4=St\u00e9phane|last5=Zwingelstein|first5=Fran\u00e7oise|last6=Cavadini|first6=Patrizia|last7=Martinelli|first7=Nicola|last8=Lombardi|first8=Guerino|last9=Gu\u00e9rin|first9=Jean-Luc|date=2013-09-08|title=Emergence of a new lagovirus related to rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus|journal=Veterinary Research|language=En|volume=44|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-44-81|pmc=3848706|pmid=24011218|pages=81}}</ref> RHDV-2 has since spread from France to the rest of Europe, Great Britain, Australia, and New Zealand. Outbreaks of RHDV-2 started occurring in the United States and Vancouver Island Canada in 2019. In 2020, RHDV-2 has been reported in Washington State, New York, Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas.\n\n== World geographic distribution ==\n===Asia===\nThe first reported outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDVa occurred in 1984 in the Jiangsu Province of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=Liu1984 />  The outbreak occurred in a group of Angora rabbits that had been imported from Germany. The cause of the disease was determined to be a small non-enveloped RNA virus. An inactivated vaccine was developed from the isolated virus that proved effective in preventing disease.<ref name=Liu1984 /> In less than a year, the disease spread over an area of 50,000 square kilometers in China and killed 140 million domestic rabbits.<ref name=\"Abrantes2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Abrantes|first1=J|last2=van der Loo|first2=W|last3=Le Pendu|first3=J|last4=Esteves|first4=PJ|title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD) and rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus (RHDV): a review|journal=Veterinary Research|date=10 February 2012|volume=43|pages=12|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-43-12|pmid=22325049|pmc=3331820}}</ref>   [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]] was the next country in Asia to report RHD outbreaks following the importation of rabbit fur from China.<ref name=Abrantes2012 />  RHD has since spread to and become endemic in many countries in Asia, including India and the Middle East.\n\n===Americas (North and South)===\nSince 1993, RHDVa has been endemic in Cuba; it is also believed to be thriving in [[Bolivia]]. From 1988 to 1992 Mexico dealt with an RHDVa endemic in domestic rabbits, but was able to quarantine and eradicate the outbreak.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nRHDVa was unable to establish a foothold in the United States, where ''Oryctolagus cuniculus'' does not occur in the wild.<ref name=IAS/> Species native to the United States [[Eastern cottontail|cottontails]] ''(Sylvilagus floridanus)'', [[black-tailed jackrabbit]]s ''(Lepus californicus)'' and [[volcano rabbit]]s ''(Romerolagus diazzi)'' were not susceptible to RHDV1.<ref name=IAS/> Outbreaks of RHDV1 in domestic populations have occurred in 2000 (Iowa<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit calicivirus infection confirmed in Iowa rabbitry |url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/s051500d.aspx |website=www.avma.org |publisher=American Veterinary Medical Association |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2001 (Utah<ref>{{cite web |title=Viral Hemorrhagic Disease of Rabbits_ Utah 8_28_01 |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_domestic/ct_vhdr_utah0801 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>, Illinois<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Campagnolo |first1=Enzo R. |last2=Ernst |first2=Mark J. |last3=Berniger |first3=Mary L. |last4=Gregg |first4=Douglas A. |last5=Shumaker |first5=Thomas J. |last6=Boghossian |first6=Aida M. |title=Outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease in domestic lagomorphs |journal=Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association |date=October 2003 |volume=223 |issue=8 |pages=1151\u20135 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/9034795 |accessdate=22 June 2019|doi=10.2460/javma.2003.223.1151 |pmid=14584745 }}</ref>, and New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aglearn.usda.gov/customcontent/APHIS/Disposal/FAD/images/rabbitHemo.pdf|title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease (Calicivirus) in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=AgLearn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>) 2005 (Indiana<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease_ Indiana |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_archives/ct_rhdindiana061505 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2008, 2010, and 2018 (Ohio<ref>{{cite web |title=First report of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Type 2 In US found in Ohio |url=https://agri.ohio.gov/wps/portal/gov/oda/programs/animal-disease-diagnostic-lab/news-and-events/Rabbit-Hemorrhagic-Disease-Type-2-Found-In-Ohio |publisher=Ohio Department of Agriculture |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> and Pennsylvania<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease, United States of America (Jefferson County, Pennsylvania report) |url=http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=28906 |website=OiE |publisher=World Organization for Animal Health |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>). \n\nIn early 2018, the first outbreak of the RHDV-2 virus in British Columbia was discovered in feral rabbits on central Vancouver Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sterritt|first1=Spencer|title=Rare and lethal virus found in deceased Nanaimo rabbits; 1st case in B.C.|url=https://nanaimonewsnow.com/article/570436/rare-and-lethal-virus-found-deceased-nanaimo-rabbits-1st-case-bc|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=NanaimoNewsNOW|date=2 March 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, the Washington State Veterinarian's Office confirmed the first case of RHDV-2 in Washington State; the domesticated rabbit was bred on [[Orcas Island]].<ref>{{cite press release |last=McGann |first=Chris |date=19 June 2019 |title=Deadly rabbit disease confirmed on Orcas Island |url=https://agr.wa.gov/about-wsda/news-and-media-relations/news-releases?article=26243 |location=Olympia, WA |publisher=Washington State Department of Agriculture |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV-2 occurred at a veterinary hospital in New York. Thirteen pet rabbits were affected, and all died of the disease. The source of the virus has yet to be identified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease, United States of America |url=https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=33541 |website=www.oie.int |publisher=OIE |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV-2 began in New Mexico, Arizona, and Texas that is affecting wild jackrabbit and cottontail populations as well as domestic pet species.  <ref>http://www.wildlife.state.nm.us/rabbit-hemorrhagic-disease-cause-for-rabbit-mortality/</ref> This outbreak is spreading, and is unlikely to be contained. \n\n===Australia===\nIn 1991 a strain of the RHDVa virus, Czech CAPM 351RHDV, was imported to Australia<ref>{{cite book|title=Australia's War Against Rabbits |last=Cooke |first=Brian Douglas |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780643096127 |url= http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/6508.htm}}</ref> under strict [[quarantine]] conditions to research the safety and usefulness of the virus if it was used as a [[biological control agent]] against Australia and New Zealand's [[Rabbits in Australia|rabbit pest problem]]. Testing of the virus was undertaken on [[Wardang Island]] in [[Spencer Gulf]] off the coast of the [[Yorke Peninsula]], [[South Australia]]. In 1995 the virus escaped quarantine and subsequently killed 10 million rabbits within 8 weeks of its release.<ref name=strive>{{cite web|url=http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |format=pdf |title=Rabbit Calicivirus Disease (RCD) |last=Strive |first=Tanja |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |date=16 July 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415081441/http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017 a new Korean strain known as RHDV K5 was successfully released in a deliberate manner after almost a decade of research. This strain was chosen in part because it functions better in cool, wet regions where the previous Calicivirus was less effective.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Prue|title=K5 rabbit virus an early success, researchers say|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-01/k5-rabbit-virus-an-early-success-csiro-researchers-say/8400816|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn July 1997, after considering over 800 public submissions, the [[New Zealand Ministry of Health]] decided not to allow RHDVa to be imported into New Zealand to control rabbit populations. This was backed up in an early August review of the decision by the Director-General of Agriculture. However, in late August it was confirmed that RHDVa had been deliberately and illegally introduced to the [[Cromwell, New Zealand|Cromwell]] area of the [[South Island]]. An unsuccessful attempt was made by New Zealand officials to control the spread of the disease. It was, however, being intentionally spread, and several farmers (notably in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] area) admitted to processing rabbits that had died from the disease in kitchen blenders for further spreading.\n\nHad the disease been introduced at a better time, there would have been a more effective control of the population. However, it was released after breeding had commenced for the season, and rabbits under 2 weeks old at the time of the introduction were resistant to the disease. These young rabbits were therefore able to survive and breed rabbit numbers back up. Ten years on, rabbit populations (in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] in particular) are beginning to reach near pre-plague proportions once again though they have not yet returned to pre RCD levels.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Munro|editor1-first=Robert K. |editor2-last=Williams|editor2-first=Richard T. |title=Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease: Issues in Assessment for biological control |date=1994 |publisher=Bureau of Resource Sciences |location=Canberra |isbn=9780644335126}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Plan for 1080 drops in MacKenzie Basin |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/2441711/Mackenzie-1080-drop-plan |last=Williams |first=David |date=26 May 2009 |newspaper= The Press |accessdate = 2009-06-14}}</ref>\n\nResistance to RHD in New Zealand rabbits has led to the widespread use of [[1080 usage in New Zealand|Compound 1080 (Sodium fluoroacetate)]]. The Government and department of Conservation are having to increase their use of 1080 to protect Reserve land from rabbits and preserve the gains made in recent years through the use of RHD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1080facts.co.nz/ |title=Welcome to 1080: The Facts |publisher=1080facts.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nThe first report of RHDVa in Europe came from in Italy in 1986.<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> From there it spread to much of Europe.  Spain's first reported case was in 1988,<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> and France, Belgium, and [[Scandinavia]] followed in 1990. Spain experienced a large die-off of wild rabbits, which in turn caused a population decline in predators that normally ate rabbits, including the [[Iberian lynx]] and [[Spanish imperial eagle]].<ref name=sd110705>{{cite news | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/07/110705081111.htm | title = Iberian Lynx Depends On Rabbits for Survival | publisher = Science Daily | date = 5 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=sa110712>{{cite news | url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/extinction-countdown/2011/07/12/deadly-rabbit-disease-may-have-doomed-iberian-lynx/ | title = Deadly Rabbit Disease May Have Doomed Iberian Lynx | first = John R. | last = Platt | work = Scientific American | date = 12 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nRHD caused by RHDVa was reported for the first time in the United Kingdom in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chasey |first1=D. |title=Possible origin of rabbit haemorrhagic disease in the United Kingdom |journal=Veterinary Record |date=1994 |volume=135 |issue=21 |pages=469-499}}</ref> This initial epidemic was brought under control in the late 1990s using a combination of vaccination, strict biosecurity, and good husbandry.<ref name=Rocchi2018>{{cite journal |last1=Rocchi |first1=Mara S. |last2=Dagleish |first2=Mark P. |title=Diagnosis and prevention of rabbit viral haemorrhagic disease 2 |journal=In Practice |date=27 January 2018 |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1136/inp.k54}}</ref> The newer viral strain RHDV-2 was first detected in England and Wales in 2014, and soon spread to Scotland and Ireland.<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> \n\nIn April 2016, a highly lethal disease started affecting one of the northernmost feral rabbit populations in the world in [[Helsinki]], Finland. The outbreak has since been identified to be caused by the new RHDV2 strain of the virus, being the first appearance of RHD in the country. Cases of viral transmission to domesticated pet rabbits have been confirmed and vaccinating rabbits has been recommended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evira.fi/elaimet/elainlaakaripalvelut/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille/2016/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille-elokuu-2016/rhd-tauti-todettu-myos-lemmikkikaniinissa-erityisluvallista-rokotetta-saatavilla/|title=RHD-tauti todettu my\u00f6s lemmikkikaniinissa - erityisluvallista rokotetta saatavilla|website=Finnish Food Safety Authority (Finnish)|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\nTransmission of RHD viruses occurs by direct contact with an infected animal and [[fomite]]s. Rabbits acquire RHD through oral, nasal or [[conjunctival]] pathways. Urine, feces and respiratory secretions may also shed the virus. The virus may also be carried by the wind. Carriers of the virus may remain infectious for up to a month depending on climate conditions; however, the virus has been known to persist for as little as 2 days and as long as 215 days. An infected carcass or hairs from an infected animal may also transmit RHD. Fomites such as clothing, contaminated food, cages, bedding, feeders and water will also harbour the virus. Even though the virus cannot reproduce in other mammals, predators and scavengers such as foxes, ferrets and some birds can excrete the virus through their faeces after ingesting an infected rabbit carcass. Flies, rabbit fleas, and mosquitoes can also spread the virus between rabbits.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nClimate appears to play a crucial role in the transmission of RHD. In normal conditions, most outbreaks of RHD occur in winter or spring. High temperatures in late spring and summer will considerably reduce the spread of the virus. RHD will also be more prevalent in dry and semi-dry areas than in areas that are relatively cool and humid.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Signs ==\nRHD primarily infects only adult rabbits. In fact, research has shown that rabbits younger than 8 weeks of age are resistant to the virus. The incubation period for the RHD virus is between 1 and 3 days, with death following 1 to 2 days after the infection. There is a wide range of RHD symptoms. Most rabbits will show no signs of external symptoms of RHD.\n\nSymptomatic cases of RHD will display fever, squeals, and often coma leading to death within 12 to 36 hours. In less severe cases, rabbits may display uneasiness, excitement, [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], swollen eyelids, [[paralysis]], ocular [[haemorrhage]]s, and \"paddling\" or loss of skin. Convulsions may be seen as well. A fatal bloody discharge from the nose has been exhibited along with blood-stained cage floors, though these symptoms may have occurred after death. Rabbits who have recovered from the less severe symptoms usually develop severe [[jaundice]] with weight loss and [[lethargy]]. Diarrhoea, constipation and abdominal cramping are then exhibited right before death a few weeks later.<ref>?</ref>\n\nRHD causes rapid development of [[blood clot]] formation in major organs such as the heart, lungs and kidneys. The clots block blood vessels causing heart and respiratory failure. An infected rabbit that has died from RHD will often have its legs straight out and head over its neck.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nRHD may be indicated when several animals in the herd die after experiencing a fever and lethargy. [[Differential diagnosis]] includes [[pasteurellosis]], [[myxomatosis]], poisoning, heat exhaustion, and ''[[E. coli]]'' or ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]'' type E [[enterotoxemia]].\n\nRabbits that die from RHD are usually in good outward state. However, the most frequent post-mortem lesions are [[necrosis]] of the [[liver]], and [[splenomegaly]]. The liver of RHD rabbits may have a fine reticular pattern of necrosis outline each lobule and maybe yellow, gray or pale in colour. The liver is also usually [[friable]] and swollen. The spleen will be black in colour and also swollen with rounded edges, while the kidneys are dark brown in colour. [[Haemorrhages]] will also be seen many other organs and tissues. The trachea may present a foamy, bloody mucous. [[Enteritis]] of the small intestine and swollen [[meninges]] may also occur.\n\nLaboratory tests such as [[reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction]] (RT-PCR), [[Western blotting]], negative-staining immunoelectron microscopy, and [[ELISA]]s may be performed on samples from the liver, blood, spleen or other organs.\n\n== Morbidity, mortality, and immunity ==\nRHD is extremely hard to locate in the wild since about 75% of rabbits with RHD will die in their burrows underground. Due to this difficulty, the [[morbidity]] and [[Mortality rate|mortality]] estimates for RHD have a broad range. The morbidity rate ranges from 30% to 100% and the mortality rate from 40% to 100%; however, the typical mortality rate is usually around 90%.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn the wild, outbreaks in rabbits vary depending on the season, breeding cycles and geographical location. Some areas will see a high morbidity and mortality among its rabbit populations followed by calmer periods.\n\nMaternal antibodies such as [[immunoglobulin G]] (IgG), which are readily transmitted to the young across the placenta, may explain why very young rabbits are resistant to RHD. Some scientists also believe that the immature immune system of a young rabbit cannot produce the number of chemicals needed to initiate clotting in order to kill. Rabbits may develop immunity against other strains of the RHD virus, while others may endure persistent infections. The immunity does not survive through the next generation, leaving open the possibility of further outbreaks in the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marques|first1=Raquel M|last2=Teixeira|first2=Luzia|last3=\u00c1guas|first3=Artur P|last4=Ribeiro|first4=Joana C|last5=Costa-e-Silva|first5=Ant\u00f3nio|last6=Ferreira|first6=Paula G|title=Immunosuppression abrogates resistance of young rabbits to Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease (RHD)|journal=Veterinary Research|date=4 February 2014|volume=45|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-45-14|pmc=3926702|pmid=24490832|pages=14}}</ref>\n\n== Control ==\nCountries that are uninfected by RHD may place restrictions on importation from endemic countries. According to the [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]/[[Merial]] Manual For Pet Health, Home Edition, 2007, RHD is a reportable disease in the United States. If a diagnosis is made by a veterinarian, a notification to the \"appropriate government authorities\" must be made.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nBecause of the highly infectious nature of the disease, strict quarantine is necessary when outbreaks occur. Depopulation, disinfection, surveillance and quarantines are the only way to properly and effectively eradicate the disease. Good disinfectants include 10% [[sodium hydroxide]], 1-2% [[formalin]], 2% One-Stroke Environ, and 10% household [[bleach]]. The RHD virus is resistant to [[ethers]] and [[chloroform]]. Deceased rabbits must be removed immediately and discarded in a safe manner. Surviving rabbits are quarantined or humanely euthanized. Test rabbits may be used to monitor the virus on vaccinated farms.<ref name=\"IAS\" />\n\nThere are several vaccines available against VHD in the UK: Cylap, made by Fort Dodge Animal Health; Lapinject, made by CEVA Animal Health; Anivac, made by Animalcare Ltd and FILAVAC, made by Filavie. All last for 12 months and contain inactivated strains of VHD. A live combination vaccine, Nobivac Myxo-RHD, made by MSD Animal Health, has recently become available. Its active ingredient is a live myxoma-vectored RHD virus strain 009 and it offers a duration of immunity of 1 year against both RHD and [[myxomatosis]].<ref name=\"NOAH Compendium\">[http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html Therapeutic Indication:  For rabbits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526030329/http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html |date=2013-05-26 }}, National Office of Animal Health rabbit vaccines.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}.</ref> FILAVAC has been authorised by the VMD in April 2017; it is currently the only vaccine containing both classic and variant strain of VHD virus.<ref>http://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/ProductInformationDatabase/SPC_Documents/SPC_1170567.DOC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*New outbreak in Canada reported on Vancouver Island {{Cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-issues-warning-to-pet-rabbit-owners-as-virus-spreads-to-lower-mainland-1.4587233 | title=B.C. Issues warning to pet rabbit owners as virus spreads to Lower Mainland &#124; CBC News}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Animal_Health_in_the_World/docs/pdf/Disease_cards/RHD.pdf Disease card]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q994732}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease}}\n[[Category:Animal viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Rabbit diseases]]\n[[Category:Hemorrhagic fevers]]\n[[Category:Animal virology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Virusbox\n| image = Emd-1933.jpg\n| image_alt = CryoEM reconstruction of \"Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\" (RHDV) capsid. EMDB entry EMD-1933\n| image_caption = [[CryoEM]] reconstruction of ''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus'' (RHDV) [[capsid]]. [[EMDB]] entry {{PDBe|EMD-1933}}<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Luque | first1 = D. \n| last2 = Gonz\u00e1lez | first2 = J. M. \n| last3 = G\u00f3mez-Blanco | first3 = J. \n| last4 = Marabini | first4 = R. \n| last5 = Chich\u00f3n | first5 = J. \n| last6 = Mena | first6 = I. \n| last7 = Angulo | first7 = I. \n| last8 = Carrascosa | first8 = J. L. \n| last9 = Verdaguer | first9 = N. \n| last10 = Trus | first10 = B. L. \n| last11 = B\u00e1rcena | first11 = J. \n| last12 = Cast\u00f3n | first12 = J. R. \n| doi = 10.1128/JVI.07050-11 \n| title = Epitope Insertion at the N-Terminal Molecular Switch of the Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus T=3 Capsid Protein Leads to Larger T=4 Capsids \n| journal = Journal of Virology \n| volume = 86 \n| issue = 12 \n| pages = 6470\u20136480 \n| year = 2012 \n| pmid = 22491457 \n| pmc =3393579 \n| url = https://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/87867/1/Epitope%20insertion.pdf}}</ref>\n| taxon = Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus\n| authority = \n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = Isolates\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Caliciviridae\">{{cite web |title=ICTV 9th Report (2011) ''Caliciviridae'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/253/caliciviridae |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |accessdate=9 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| subdivision = \n*RHDV [FRG/89] (RHDV-FRG)\n*RCV [ITL/95] (RHDV-RCV)\n*RCV-A1 [MIC-07/2007/AU] (RHDV-RCV-A1)\n*RHDV [Ashington/1998/UK] (RHDV-Ash)\n}}\n[[File:CSIRO ScienceImage 2009 Rabbit Calicivirus.jpg|thumb|Rabbit Calicivirus <small>CSIRO</small>]]\n\n'''Rabbit hemorrhagic disease''' ('''RHD''') is a highly infectious and lethal form of viral hepatitis that affects European rabbits ''(Oryctolagus cuniculus)''. Mortality rates in adult rabbits generally range from 70 to 100 percent.<ref name=Capucci2017>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Cavadini |first2=P. |last3=Schiavitto |first3=M. |last4=Lombardi |first4=G. |last5=Lavazza |first5=A. |title=Increased pathogenicity in rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus type 2 (RHDV2) |journal=Veterinary Record |date=29 April 2017 |volume=180 |issue=17 |page=426 |doi=10.1136/vr.104132}}</ref> The disease is caused by the [[lagovirus]] '''rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus''' ('''RHDV''') in the family [[Caliciviridae]]. The virus infects only rabbits, and has been used in some countries to control feral rabbit populations.\n\n== RHDVa and RHDV-2 ==\n\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease viruses (RHDV) are single strand RNA viruses in the genus Lagovirus and the family Caliciviridae. In the course of its evolution RHDV split into six distinct genotypes,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kerr |first1=P. J. |last2=Kitchen |first2=A. |last3=Holmes |first3=E. C. |title=Origin and Phylodynamics of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus |journal=Journal of Virology |date=16 September 2009 |volume=83 |issue=23 |pages=12129\u201312138 |doi=10.1128/JVI.01523-09|doi-access=free }}</ref> all of which are highly pathogenic. In addition, non-pathogenic rabbit caliciviruses related to but distinct from RHDV have been identified in Europe and Australia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Capucci |first1=L. |last2=Fusi |first2=P. |last3=Lavazza |first3=A. |last4=Pacciarini |first4=M.L. |last5=Rossi |first5=C. |title=Detection and preliminary characterization of a new rabbit calicivirus related to rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus but nonpathogenic |journal=Journal of Virology |date=December 1996 |volume=70 |issue=12 |pages=8614-8623}}</ref> Rabbit lagoviruses also include related caliciviruses such as European brown hare syndrome virus.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gleeson |first1=Molly |last2=Petritz |first2=Olivia A. |title=Emerging Infectious Diseases of Rabbits |journal=Veterinary Clinics of North America: Exotic Animal Practice |date=May 2020 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=249\u2013261 |doi=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cvex.2020.01.008}}</ref>\n\nThe two strains of rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus currently of medical significance are RHDVa and RHDV-2. RHDVa (also referred to as RHDV, RHDV1, or as classical RHD) only affects adult European rabbits (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''). This virus was first reported in China in 1984,<ref name=Liu1984>{{cite journal |last1=Liu |first1=S.J. |last2=Xue |first2=H.P. |last3=Pu |first3=B.Q. |last4=Qian |first4=N.H. |title=A new viral disease in rabbits |journal=Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Medicine (Xumu yu Shouyi) |date=1984 |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=253-255}}</ref> from which it spread to much of Asia, Europe, Australia, and elsewhere. There have been a few isolated outbreaks of RHDVa in the United States and Mexico, but they remained localized and were eradicated.\n\nIn 2010, a new lagovirus with a distinct antigenic profile was identified in France. This virus also caused rabbit hemorrhagic disease but behaved differently from RHDVa in that it affected vaccinated and young European rabbits as well as hares ''(Lepus spp.)''.<ref name=Capucci2017 /> All these features strongly suggested that the virus was not derived from RHDVa but from some other unknown source.<ref name=Capucci2017 />  The new virus was named rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV-2). RHDV-2 is distinct enough from RHDVa that the two require different vaccines, which are only partially cross protective. Besides affecting the European rabbit, RHDV-2 has caused disease in Sardinian Cape hares ''(Lepus capensis mediterraneus)'', Italian hares ''(Lepus corsicanus)'' and mountain hares ''(Lepus timidus)''.\n<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> RHDV-2 has since spread to the majority of Europe as well as to Australia, Canada, and the United States.\n\n== History ==\nRabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDVa first appeared in the Winter of 1983 in Jiangsu Province of the [[People's Republic of China]]. The virus was first isolated and characterized by S.J. Liu ''et al''. in 1984.<ref name=Merck>{{cite web | title = A New Viral Disease of Rabbit| work = The Merck Veterinary Manual | year = 2006 | url = http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/171330.htm | accessdate = 2007-06-17 }}</ref> The Chinese outbreak was spread by the [[angora rabbit]], which had originated in [[Europe]]. Fourteen million domesticated rabbits died within nine months in the outbreak.<ref name=IAS>[http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/rabbit_hemorrhagic_disease.pdf Center for Food Security and Public Health]</ref>\n\nFrom China, RHDVa spread westward and reached Europe in 1988. The virus has since appeared in Mexico, [[Cuba]], Australia, New Zealand, the United States and Canada.<ref name=Merck/> In 1992, the United Kingdom reported its first case of RHDVa in domestic show rabbits. By the late 1990s, RHDVa stretched to forty countries and had become [[endemic]] in [[Wild animal|wild]] and [[feral]] rabbit populations in Europe, Australia, New Zealand and [[Cuba]].<ref name=IAS/> In Europe, there was a rapid increase in research into RHD, due to the importance of the commercial breeding of rabbits for meat and fur production.\n\nThe first reported case of RHDVa in the United States was in Iowa on March 9, 2000. The affected breeds included [[List of rabbit breeds|Palominos]] and [[Californian rabbit|California Whites]]. By April 6, 25 of the 27 affected rabbits had died of the infection. In order to contain the disease, the remaining two rabbits were euthanized. No new introductions of rabbits were placed on the farm for two years after the discovery of RHDVa and August 1999 was the last time rabbits left and/or returned to the farm. The United States experienced other outbreaks of RHDVa in 2001 ([[Utah]], [[Illinois]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) and 2005 ([[Indiana]]).<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn 2010, a new virus variant called rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus 2 (RHDV-2) emerged in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Le Gall-Recul\u00e9|first=Ghislaine|last2=Lavazza|first2=Antonio|last3=Marchandeau|first3=St\u00e9phane|last4=Bertagnoli|first4=St\u00e9phane|last5=Zwingelstein|first5=Fran\u00e7oise|last6=Cavadini|first6=Patrizia|last7=Martinelli|first7=Nicola|last8=Lombardi|first8=Guerino|last9=Gu\u00e9rin|first9=Jean-Luc|date=2013-09-08|title=Emergence of a new lagovirus related to rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus|journal=Veterinary Research|language=En|volume=44|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-44-81|pmc=3848706|pmid=24011218|pages=81}}</ref> RHDV-2 has since spread from France to the rest of Europe, Great Britain, Australia, and New Zealand. Outbreaks of RHDV-2 started occurring in the United States and Vancouver Island Canada in 2019. In 2020, RHDV-2 has been reported in Washington State, New York, Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas.\n\n== World geographic distribution ==\n===Asia===\nThe first reported outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease caused by RHDVa occurred in 1984 in the Jiangsu Province of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=Liu1984 />  The outbreak occurred in a group of Angora rabbits that had been imported from Germany. The cause of the disease was determined to be a small non-enveloped RNA virus. An inactivated vaccine was developed from the isolated virus that proved effective in preventing disease.<ref name=Liu1984 /> In less than a year, the disease spread over an area of 50,000 square kilometers in China and killed 140 million domestic rabbits.<ref name=\"Abrantes2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Abrantes|first1=J|last2=van der Loo|first2=W|last3=Le Pendu|first3=J|last4=Esteves|first4=PJ|title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD) and rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus (RHDV): a review|journal=Veterinary Research|date=10 February 2012|volume=43|pages=12|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-43-12|pmid=22325049|pmc=3331820}}</ref>   [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]] was the next country in Asia to report RHD outbreaks following the importation of rabbit fur from China.<ref name=Abrantes2012 />  RHD has since spread to and become endemic in many countries in Asia, including India and the Middle East.\n\n===Americas (North and South)===\nSince 1993, RHDVa has been endemic in Cuba; it is also believed to be thriving in [[Bolivia]]. From 1988 to 1992 Mexico dealt with an RHDVa endemic in domestic rabbits, but was able to quarantine and eradicate the outbreak.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nRHDVa was unable to establish a foothold in the United States, where ''Oryctolagus cuniculus'' does not occur in the wild.<ref name=IAS/> Species native to the United States [[Eastern cottontail|cottontails]] ''(Sylvilagus floridanus)'', [[black-tailed jackrabbit]]s ''(Lepus californicus)'' and [[volcano rabbit]]s ''(Romerolagus diazzi)'' were not susceptible to RHDV1.<ref name=IAS/> Outbreaks of RHDV1 in domestic populations have occurred in 2000 (Iowa<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit calicivirus infection confirmed in Iowa rabbitry |url=https://www.avma.org/News/JAVMANews/Pages/s051500d.aspx |website=www.avma.org |publisher=American Veterinary Medical Association |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2001 (Utah<ref>{{cite web |title=Viral Hemorrhagic Disease of Rabbits_ Utah 8_28_01 |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_domestic/ct_vhdr_utah0801 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>, Illinois<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Campagnolo |first1=Enzo R. |last2=Ernst |first2=Mark J. |last3=Berniger |first3=Mary L. |last4=Gregg |first4=Douglas A. |last5=Shumaker |first5=Thomas J. |last6=Boghossian |first6=Aida M. |title=Outbreak of rabbit hemorrhagic disease in domestic lagomorphs |journal=Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association |date=October 2003 |volume=223 |issue=8 |pages=1151\u20135 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/9034795 |accessdate=22 June 2019|doi=10.2460/javma.2003.223.1151 |pmid=14584745 }}</ref>, and New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aglearn.usda.gov/customcontent/APHIS/Disposal/FAD/images/rabbitHemo.pdf|title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease (Calicivirus) in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=AgLearn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>) 2005 (Indiana<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease_ Indiana |url=https://www.aphis.usda.gov/wcm/connect/aphis_content_library/sa_our_focus/sa_animal_health/sa_emerging_issues/sa_impact_worksheets/sa_archives/ct_rhdindiana061505 |website=www.aphis.usda.gov |publisher=Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>), 2008, 2010, and 2018 (Ohio<ref>{{cite web |title=First report of Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Type 2 In US found in Ohio |url=https://agri.ohio.gov/wps/portal/gov/oda/programs/animal-disease-diagnostic-lab/news-and-events/Rabbit-Hemorrhagic-Disease-Type-2-Found-In-Ohio |publisher=Ohio Department of Agriculture |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> and Pennsylvania<ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit haemorrhagic disease, United States of America (Jefferson County, Pennsylvania report) |url=http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=28906 |website=OiE |publisher=World Organization for Animal Health |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>). \n\nIn early 2018, the first outbreak of the RHDV-2 virus in British Columbia was discovered in feral rabbits on central Vancouver Island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sterritt|first1=Spencer|title=Rare and lethal virus found in deceased Nanaimo rabbits; 1st case in B.C.|url=https://nanaimonewsnow.com/article/570436/rare-and-lethal-virus-found-deceased-nanaimo-rabbits-1st-case-bc|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=NanaimoNewsNOW|date=2 March 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, the Washington State Veterinarian's Office confirmed the first case of RHDV-2 in Washington State; the domesticated rabbit was bred on [[Orcas Island]].<ref>{{cite press release |last=McGann |first=Chris |date=19 June 2019 |title=Deadly rabbit disease confirmed on Orcas Island |url=https://agr.wa.gov/about-wsda/news-and-media-relations/news-releases?article=26243 |location=Olympia, WA |publisher=Washington State Department of Agriculture |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV-2 occurred at a veterinary hospital in New York. Thirteen pet rabbits were affected, and all died of the disease. The source of the virus has yet to be identified. <ref>{{cite web |title=Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease, United States of America |url=https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=33541 |website=www.oie.int |publisher=OIE |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March of 2020 an outbreak of RHDV-2 began in New Mexico, Arizona, and Texas that is affecting wild jackrabbit and cottontail populations as well as domestic pet species.  <ref>http://www.wildlife.state.nm.us/rabbit-hemorrhagic-disease-cause-for-rabbit-mortality/</ref> This outbreak is spreading, and is unlikely to be contained. \n\n===Australia===\nIn 1991 a strain of the RHDVa virus, Czech CAPM 351RHDV, was imported to Australia<ref>{{cite book|title=Australia's War Against Rabbits |last=Cooke |first=Brian Douglas |publisher=CSIRO Publishing |year=2014 |isbn=9780643096127 |url= http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/6508.htm}}</ref> under strict [[quarantine]] conditions to research the safety and usefulness of the virus if it was used as a [[biological control agent]] against Australia and New Zealand's [[Rabbits in Australia|rabbit pest problem]]. Testing of the virus was undertaken on [[Wardang Island]] in [[Spencer Gulf]] off the coast of the [[Yorke Peninsula]], [[South Australia]]. In 1995 the virus escaped quarantine and subsequently killed 10 million rabbits within 8 weeks of its release.<ref name=strive>{{cite web|url=http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |format=pdf |title=Rabbit Calicivirus Disease (RCD) |last=Strive |first=Tanja |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |date=16 July 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415081441/http://www.csiro.au/Outcomes/Food-and-Agriculture/RCDFactsheet.aspx |archivedate=April 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017 a new Korean strain known as RHDV K5 was successfully released in a deliberate manner after almost a decade of research. This strain was chosen in part because it functions better in cool, wet regions where the previous Calicivirus was less effective.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Prue|title=K5 rabbit virus an early success, researchers say|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-01/k5-rabbit-virus-an-early-success-csiro-researchers-say/8400816|accessdate=2018-05-20|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn July 1997, after considering over 800 public submissions, the [[New Zealand Ministry of Health]] decided not to allow RHDVa to be imported into New Zealand to control rabbit populations. This was backed up in an early August review of the decision by the Director-General of Agriculture. However, in late August it was confirmed that RHDVa had been deliberately and illegally introduced to the [[Cromwell, New Zealand|Cromwell]] area of the [[South Island]]. An unsuccessful attempt was made by New Zealand officials to control the spread of the disease. It was, however, being intentionally spread, and several farmers (notably in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] area) admitted to processing rabbits that had died from the disease in kitchen blenders for further spreading.\n\nHad the disease been introduced at a better time, there would have been a more effective control of the population. However, it was released after breeding had commenced for the season, and rabbits under 2 weeks old at the time of the introduction were resistant to the disease. These young rabbits were therefore able to survive and breed rabbit numbers back up. Ten years on, rabbit populations (in the [[Mackenzie Basin]] in particular) are beginning to reach near pre-plague proportions once again though they have not yet returned to pre RCD levels.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Munro|editor1-first=Robert K. |editor2-last=Williams|editor2-first=Richard T. |title=Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease: Issues in Assessment for biological control |date=1994 |publisher=Bureau of Resource Sciences |location=Canberra |isbn=9780644335126}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Plan for 1080 drops in MacKenzie Basin |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/2441711/Mackenzie-1080-drop-plan |last=Williams |first=David |date=26 May 2009 |newspaper= The Press |accessdate = 2009-06-14}}</ref>\n\nResistance to RHD in New Zealand rabbits has led to the widespread use of [[1080 usage in New Zealand|Compound 1080 (Sodium fluoroacetate)]]. The Government and department of Conservation are having to increase their use of 1080 to protect Reserve land from rabbits and preserve the gains made in recent years through the use of RHD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1080facts.co.nz/ |title=Welcome to 1080: The Facts |publisher=1080facts.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nThe first report of RHDVa in Europe came from in Italy in 1986.<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> From there it spread to much of Europe.  Spain's first reported case was in 1988,<ref name=Abrantes2012 /> and France, Belgium, and [[Scandinavia]] followed in 1990. Spain experienced a large die-off of wild rabbits, which in turn caused a population decline in predators that normally ate rabbits, including the [[Iberian lynx]] and [[Spanish imperial eagle]].<ref name=sd110705>{{cite news | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/07/110705081111.htm | title = Iberian Lynx Depends On Rabbits for Survival | publisher = Science Daily | date = 5 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=sa110712>{{cite news | url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/extinction-countdown/2011/07/12/deadly-rabbit-disease-may-have-doomed-iberian-lynx/ | title = Deadly Rabbit Disease May Have Doomed Iberian Lynx | first = John R. | last = Platt | work = Scientific American | date = 12 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nRHD caused by RHDVa was reported for the first time in the United Kingdom in 1992.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chasey |first1=D. |title=Possible origin of rabbit haemorrhagic disease in the United Kingdom |journal=Veterinary Record |date=1994 |volume=135 |issue=21 |pages=469-499}}</ref> This initial epidemic was brought under control in the late 1990s using a combination of vaccination, strict biosecurity, and good husbandry.<ref name=Rocchi2018>{{cite journal |last1=Rocchi |first1=Mara S. |last2=Dagleish |first2=Mark P. |title=Diagnosis and prevention of rabbit viral haemorrhagic disease 2 |journal=In Practice |date=27 January 2018 |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1136/inp.k54}}</ref> The newer viral strain RHDV-2 was first detected in England and Wales in 2014, and soon spread to Scotland and Ireland.<ref name=Rocchi2018 /> \n\nIn April 2016, a highly lethal disease started affecting one of the northernmost feral rabbit populations in the world in [[Helsinki]], Finland. The outbreak has since been identified to be caused by the new RHDV2 strain of the virus, being the first appearance of RHD in the country. Cases of viral transmission to domesticated pet rabbits have been confirmed and vaccinating rabbits has been recommended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evira.fi/elaimet/elainlaakaripalvelut/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille/2016/saparo-uutiskirje-elainlaakareille-elokuu-2016/rhd-tauti-todettu-myos-lemmikkikaniinissa-erityisluvallista-rokotetta-saatavilla/|title=RHD-tauti todettu my\u00f6s lemmikkikaniinissa - erityisluvallista rokotetta saatavilla|website=Finnish Food Safety Authority (Finnish)|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\nTransmission of RHD viruses occurs by direct contact with an infected animal and [[fomite]]s. Rabbits acquire RHD through oral, nasal or [[conjunctival]] pathways. Urine, feces and respiratory secretions may also shed the virus. The virus may also be carried by the wind. Carriers of the virus may remain infectious for up to a month depending on climate conditions; however, the virus has been known to persist for as little as 2 days and as long as 215 days. An infected carcass or hairs from an infected animal may also transmit RHD. Fomites such as clothing, contaminated food, cages, bedding, feeders and water will also harbour the virus. Even though the virus cannot reproduce in other mammals, predators and scavengers such as foxes, ferrets and some birds can excrete the virus through their faeces after ingesting an infected rabbit carcass. Flies, rabbit fleas, and mosquitoes can also spread the virus between rabbits.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nClimate appears to play a crucial role in the transmission of RHD. In normal conditions, most outbreaks of RHD occur in winter or spring. High temperatures in late spring and summer will considerably reduce the spread of the virus. RHD will also be more prevalent in dry and semi-dry areas than in areas that are relatively cool and humid.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Signs ==\nRHD primarily infects only adult rabbits. In fact, research has shown that rabbits younger than 8 weeks of age are resistant to the virus. The incubation period for the RHD virus is between 1 and 3 days, with death following 1 to 2 days after the infection. There is a wide range of RHD symptoms. Most rabbits will show no signs of external symptoms of RHD.\n\nSymptomatic cases of RHD will display fever, squeals, and often coma leading to death within 12 to 36 hours. In less severe cases, rabbits may display uneasiness, excitement, [[Anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]], swollen eyelids, [[paralysis]], ocular [[haemorrhage]]s, and \"paddling\" or loss of skin. Convulsions may be seen as well. A fatal bloody discharge from the nose has been exhibited along with blood-stained cage floors, though these symptoms may have occurred after death. Rabbits who have recovered from the less severe symptoms usually develop severe [[jaundice]] with weight loss and [[lethargy]]. Diarrhoea, constipation and abdominal cramping are then exhibited right before death a few weeks later.<ref>?</ref>\n\nRHD causes rapid development of [[blood clot]] formation in major organs such as the heart, lungs and kidneys. The clots block blood vessels causing heart and respiratory failure. An infected rabbit that has died from RHD will often have its legs straight out and head over its neck.<ref name=strive/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nRHD may be indicated when several animals in the herd die after experiencing a fever and lethargy. [[Differential diagnosis]] includes [[pasteurellosis]], [[myxomatosis]], poisoning, heat exhaustion, and ''[[E. coli]]'' or ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]'' type E [[enterotoxemia]].\n\nRabbits that die from RHD are usually in good outward state. However, the most frequent post-mortem lesions are [[necrosis]] of the [[liver]], and [[splenomegaly]]. The liver of RHD rabbits may have a fine reticular pattern of necrosis outline each lobule and maybe yellow, gray or pale in colour. The liver is also usually [[friable]] and swollen. The spleen will be black in colour and also swollen with rounded edges, while the kidneys are dark brown in colour. [[Haemorrhages]] will also be seen many other organs and tissues. The trachea may present a foamy, bloody mucous. [[Enteritis]] of the small intestine and swollen [[meninges]] may also occur.\n\nLaboratory tests such as [[reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction]] (RT-PCR), [[Western blotting]], negative-staining immunoelectron microscopy, and [[ELISA]]s may be performed on samples from the liver, blood, spleen or other organs.\n\n== Morbidity, mortality, and immunity ==\nRHD is extremely hard to locate in the wild since about 75% of rabbits with RHD will die in their burrows underground. Due to this difficulty, the [[morbidity]] and [[Mortality rate|mortality]] estimates for RHD have a broad range. The morbidity rate ranges from 30% to 100% and the mortality rate from 40% to 100%; however, the typical mortality rate is usually around 90%.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nIn the wild, outbreaks in rabbits vary depending on the season, breeding cycles and geographical location. Some areas will see a high morbidity and mortality among its rabbit populations followed by calmer periods.\n\nMaternal antibodies such as [[immunoglobulin G]] (IgG), which are readily transmitted to the young across the placenta, may explain why very young rabbits are resistant to RHD. Some scientists also believe that the immature immune system of a young rabbit cannot produce the number of chemicals needed to initiate clotting in order to kill. Rabbits may develop immunity against other strains of the RHD virus, while others may endure persistent infections. The immunity does not survive through the next generation, leaving open the possibility of further outbreaks in the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marques|first1=Raquel M|last2=Teixeira|first2=Luzia|last3=\u00c1guas|first3=Artur P|last4=Ribeiro|first4=Joana C|last5=Costa-e-Silva|first5=Ant\u00f3nio|last6=Ferreira|first6=Paula G|title=Immunosuppression abrogates resistance of young rabbits to Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease (RHD)|journal=Veterinary Research|date=4 February 2014|volume=45|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1297-9716-45-14|pmc=3926702|pmid=24490832|pages=14}}</ref>\n\n== Control ==\nCountries that are uninfected by RHD may place restrictions on importation from endemic countries. According to the [[Merck & Co.|Merck]]/[[Merial]] Manual For Pet Health, Home Edition, 2007, RHD is a reportable disease in the United States. If a diagnosis is made by a veterinarian, a notification to the \"appropriate government authorities\" must be made.<ref name=IAS/>\n\nBecause of the highly infectious nature of the disease, strict quarantine is necessary when outbreaks occur. Depopulation, disinfection, surveillance and quarantines are the only way to properly and effectively eradicate the disease. Good disinfectants include 10% [[sodium hydroxide]], 1-2% [[formalin]], 2% One-Stroke Environ, and 10% household [[bleach]]. The RHD virus is resistant to [[ethers]] and [[chloroform]]. Deceased rabbits must be removed immediately and discarded in a safe manner. Surviving rabbits are quarantined or humanely euthanized. Test rabbits may be used to monitor the virus on vaccinated farms.<ref name=\"IAS\" />\n\nThere are several vaccines available against VHD in the UK: Cylap, made by Fort Dodge Animal Health; Lapinject, made by CEVA Animal Health; Anivac, made by Animalcare Ltd and FILAVAC, made by Filavie. All last for 12 months and contain inactivated strains of VHD. A live combination vaccine, Nobivac Myxo-RHD, made by MSD Animal Health, has recently become available. Its active ingredient is a live myxoma-vectored RHD virus strain 009 and it offers a duration of immunity of 1 year against both RHD and [[myxomatosis]].<ref name=\"NOAH Compendium\">[http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html Therapeutic Indication:  For rabbits] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526030329/http://www.noahcompendium.co.uk/Therapeutic_Indication/Therapeutic_Indication/-148.html |date=2013-05-26 }}, National Office of Animal Health rabbit vaccines.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}.</ref> FILAVAC has been authorised by the VMD in April 2017; it is currently the only vaccine containing both classic and variant strain of VHD virus.<ref>http://www.vmd.defra.gov.uk/ProductInformationDatabase/SPC_Documents/SPC_1170567.DOC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rabbits in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*New outbreak in Canada reported on Vancouver Island {{Cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-issues-warning-to-pet-rabbit-owners-as-virus-spreads-to-lower-mainland-1.4587233 | title=B.C. Issues warning to pet rabbit owners as virus spreads to Lower Mainland &#124; CBC News}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Animal_Health_in_the_World/docs/pdf/Disease_cards/RHD.pdf Disease card]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q994732}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease}}\n[[Category:Animal viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Rabbit diseases]]\n[[Category:Hemorrhagic fevers]]\n[[Category:Animal virology]]\n", "name_user": "Rabbit Vet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRHDVa and RHDV-2:clarification of the (too) many names for these viral strains!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit_haemorrhagic_disease"}
{"title_page": "Zellers", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian retail company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n<!-- Please do not replace the current infobox for the defunct infobox until all stores have closed. Thank you for your understanding -->\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Zellers\n| logo = Zellers logo.svg\n| type = Subsidiary\n| founder = Walter P. Zeller\n| fate = Most store leases acquired by [[Target Canada]], [[Walmart Canada]] or closed outright. Selected locations were retained to serve as liquidation centres for other HBC retail chains until 2020\n| industry = Discount retail store\n| defunct = March 2013 (as a chain) <br/>\nJan. 2020 (liquidation stores)\n| products = Clothing, grocery, footwear, bedding, furniture, jewelry, beauty products, electronics, toys, sports equipment, appliances, housewares\n| owner = Hudson's Bay Company<ref>cite web|url=http://www.hbc.com/hbc/about/contacts/|title=Contacts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719100513/http://www.hbc.com/hbc/about/contacts/|archive-date=July 19, 2010|website=Hudson's Bay Company access-date=July 7, 2010</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| foundation = 1931\n| location = Brampton, Ontario, Canada\n| locations = 350 (1999)<ref name=\"350 stores\"/>\n| website = [https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.zellers.com  zellers.com] archive\n}}\n\n'''Zellers''' was a Canadian chain [[Discount store|discount department retailer]] that was based in [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]]. It was founded in 1931 and was acquired by [[Hudson's Bay Company]] (HBC) in 1978.\n\nA series of acquisitions and expansions allowed Zellers to reach its peak in the 1990s, with 350 stores across the country in 1999.<ref name=\"350 stores\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MARTHA+STEWART,+ZELLARS+NAMED+IN+LAWSUIT.-a056083276| title=\"MARTHA STEWART, ZELLARS [''sic''] NAMED IN LAWSUIT\"\n| first      = Brian |last=Dunn \n| newspaper  = HFN The Weekly Newspaper for the Home Furnishing Network\n| date       = October 4, 1999|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref> However, fierce competition by [[Walmart Canada]] and an inability to adjust to [[Retail apocalypse|the increasingly volatile retailing industry]] resulted in Zellers losing significant ground in the 2000s. At the same time, HBC's new owner [[NRDC Equity Partners]] was focusing on bolstering and re-positioning Zellers' sister chain, [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]], with an upscale and fashion-oriented direction, and saw Zellers as a detriment to the turnaround.\n\nIn January 2011, HBC announced that it would sell the lease agreements for up to 220 Zellers stores to the US. chain [[Target Corporation|Target]] for $1.825 billion. In turn, Target announced its intent to convert many of them to [[Target Canada|Canadian locations of Target]], and re-sell the remainder to other parties such as [[Walmart Canada]], resulting in their liquidation and eventual closure. While HBC retained 64 Zellers locations, it announced on July 26, 2012 that the majority of them would be liquidated and closed by March 31, 2013 due to their lack of profitability. After the chain went under, HBC operated some Zellers-branded locations as liquidation outlets for The Bay, with the last of those stores closed on January 26, 2020.<ref name=\"January 26, 2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/zellers-closing-memorabilia-1.5425471|title=As final Zellers stores close, former employees swap memories, memorabilia|last=Watters|first=Haydn|date=January 19, 2020|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nOn Saturday August 4, 1928 Zellers Ltd was born in [[London, Ontario]]. Walter P. Zeller, its founder, opened his new store & head office at 176 Dundas Street after working for years for Metropolitan Department Stores, F.W. Woolworth Company and Kresges. This new store was to be a part of a chain of Canadian department stores. The plan at the start was to have stores opened in London, St. Catharines, Niagara Falls, Fort Williams and St. John N.B. The London store had a street frontage of 53 feet and a depth of 137 feet. It had a total of 7,000 square feet of space on the ground floor with 2,000 square feet of counter space spread out around the store. Sixty women were hired for the opening day working in 21 different departments. Within months Zellers was doing such good business that they were bought out by the American firm Schulte-United Ltd. Within two years the rebranded stores went bankrupt. Walter Zeller promptly bought most of the failed Schulte stores and relaunched Zellers in late 1931. Zellers Department Store remained at 176 Dundas Street until the late 1980s.<ref>London Free Press August 3rd, 1928 edition, http://torontoist.com/2015/01/vintage-toronto-ads-zellers/ & http://www.hbcheritage.ca/\u2026/hist\u2026/people/builders/zeller.asp</ref>\n\n===1930s\u20131960s: Early years, partnership with W.T. Grant===\n[[File:Zellers 1931 Toronto.jpg|thumb|Zellers advertisement in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' for its 1931 grand opening in Toronto. The announced location later became part of the [[Toronto Eaton Centre]].]]\nThe company was founded in 1931 by [[Walter P. Zeller]] as stores for thrifty Canadians.<ref name=\"Zellers history\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/acquisitions/retail/zellers |title=HBC Heritage: The Zellers Story |work=Hudson's Bay Company |year=2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> The chain began with the purchase of the fourteen Canadian locations of American retailer [[H. L. Green Company|Schulte-United]], all of which were in Southern Ontario. Almost immediately, Zellers initiated an aggressive expansion strategy. Within 25 years, Zellers operated 60 stores and employed 3,000 people.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In 1952, in a move to expand into Atlantic Canada, it acquired the [[Federal Stores]] chain of [[variety store]]s, adding more than 12 new Zellers locations.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\nDuring this period of expansion, Zellers concluded a deal with [[W.T. Grant]], a similar chain of American mass merchandise department stores.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> This arrangement allowed W.T. Grant to purchase 10% of Zellers shares and eventually a 51% ownership in 1959.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>  In exchange, the Grant Company made available to Zellers its experience in merchandising, real estate, store development, and general administration. Zellers employees were sent to Grant stores and head office for training and the two companies made common buying trips to east Asia.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In the 1950s, the chain again began opening new locations and in 1956, opened its first self-serve location at the [[Norgate shopping centre]] in [[Saint-Laurent, Quebec]].<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> Stores opened in 1960 employed many new innovations, including the first in store restaurant, the first automotive centre and the first suburban location.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\n===1970s\u20131980s: Zellers acquires Fields, HBC acquires Zellers===\nIn 1975, Zellers adopted its final logo. By 1976, Zellers had grown to a chain of 155 stores, with annual sales of $407 million.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\nAlthough Zellers was prospering, W.T. Grant was facing intense competition in the United States, and was forced to withdraw entirely from its Canadian operations. In 1976, [[Fields (department store)|Fields]], a clothing retailer based in Vancouver, British Columbia, offered to purchase a 50.1% stake in Zellers for $32,675,000. Zellers' shareholders, unhappy with the idea of Zellers becoming a subsidiary of Fields, reversed the takeover and purchased Fields and its hardware store division, [[Marshall Wells]]. This sale added 70 Fields stores and 162 franchised Marshall Wells stores to the company. Fields president and founder, Joseph Segal was appointed as president of Zellers.<ref name=\"fields\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/acquisitions/retail/fields |title=HBC Heritage: Fields, The Strength of an Idea |work=Hudson's Bay Company |year=2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1978, Zellers presented a bid to acquire 100% ownership of the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] (HBC). HBC management, recognizing Zellers profitability and the potential to enter a new retail segment, decided to purchase Zellers instead. Zellers and Fields, operating in very different retail segments from HBC, were kept intact and established as separate divisions of the company. HBC acquired full ownership of Zellers and Fields in 1981 and Marshall Wells in 1982. By 1985, HBC had sold Marshall Wells for $20 million, because it was not relevant to its department store business.\n\nCounterfeit video games for the [[Atari 2600]] were manufactured in Taiwan and sold by Zellers in the 1980s, usually under new names and artwork and occasionally with [[ROM hacking|modified graphics]]. All games were [[Copyright infringement|pirated]] copies of titles created either by [[Atari, Inc.|Atari]] itself or by third-party developers, such as [[Activision]]. Zellers was eventually forced by Atari to stop selling these games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512093632/http://retronouveau.tumblr.com/post/17268200307/les-jeux-atari-2600-de-zellers|title=Les jeux Atari 2600 de Zellers|author=Retro Nouveau|publisher=Tumblr|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512093632/http://retronouveau.tumblr.com/post/17268200307/les-jeux-atari-2600-de-zellers|archive-date=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news | url=http://www.ottawasun.com/2014/04/03/zellers-reopens-its-doors-in-bells-corners?token=93bac5c80986d88d4baeb7111f167a0e | title=Zellers reopens its doors in Bells Corners | work=[[Ottawa Sun]] | date=3 April 2014 | accessdate=3 April 2014 | author=Desrosiers, Sophie}}</ref> Zellers released 18 games for the Atari 2600 in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite web\n|title = AtariAge - Companies - Zellers\n|url=https://www.atariage.com/company_page.php?SystemID=2600&CompanyID=61\n|accessdate = 2015-09-13}}</ref>\n\n===1990s: Further acquisitions===\nIn 1990, Hudson's Bay Company acquired the 51 stores of the [[Towers Department Stores|Towers/Bonimart]] chain from the [[Oshawa Group]], and converted most of them to Zellers outlets, including its flagship location in [[Toronto]]. Zellers advertisements at the time featured both the Towers [[mascot]], Sparky, and the Zellers mascot, Zeddy, walking arm in arm. During this period, Zellers used the slogan \"the lowest price is the law.\"\n\nIn 1993, Hudson's Bay Company purchased the assets of the bankrupt [[Woodward's]] chain, including 21 store locations.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> These were converted into Zellers and The Bay stores, and greatly expanded the company's presence in Western Canada.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In 1998, Hudson's Bay Company acquired [[Kmart]]'s Canadian division, and merged it with the Zellers division to create a larger combined chain under the Zellers name.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> While some Kmart locations were closed, many sites became full Zellers outlets.\n\nIn 1996, Hudson's Bay Company closed its Zellers head office in [[Montreal]], Quebec and merged it with the Hudson's Bay Company headquarters in downtown Toronto. By 1998, Hudson's Bay Company regained a Zellers head office after Zellers took over Kmart's Canadian head office in [[Brampton]], Ontario.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\n===2000s: Decline===\nOn February 28, 2006, Hudson's Bay Company was taken private by [[South Carolina]] businessman [[Jerry Zucker (businessman)|Jerry Zucker]]. In Hudson's Bay Company's last year as a publicly traded company, Zellers had 291 stores and lost $107 million on sales of $4.2 billion.<ref name=\"atzellers\">{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215044435/https://www.thestar.com/business/2009/07/31/at_zellers_lowest_price_is_still_prime_focus.html|title=At Zellers, lowest price is still prime focus|last=Flavelle|first=Dana|date=July 31, 2009|newspaper=Toronto Star|access-date=|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nMark Foote, who had headed general merchandise at [[Loblaw Companies]] and was president of [[Canadian Tire]] Corp's retail division, was appointed President and CEO of Zellers in 2008 and he was credited with stabilizing the chain, though it still struggled against Walmart Canada.<ref name=\"atzellers\" /><ref name=\"theglobeandmail1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/zellers-ceo-rewrites-the-book-on-liquidation/article4182420/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Zellers CEO rewrites the book on liquidation | date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Zucker's death in 2008, Hudson's Bay Company and its subsidiaries including Zellers came under the ownership of a New York based company, [[NRDC Equity Partners]], which was headed by [[Richard A. Baker (businessman)|Richard Baker]]. NRDC owns the [[Lord & Taylor]] upscale specialty retail department store chain in the United States.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113080235/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/us-chains-circle-zellers-properties/article1866399/|title=US. chains circle Zellers properties|last1=Strauss|first1=Marina|last2=Ladurantaye|first2=Steve|date=January 11, 2011|work=The Globe and Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113080235/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/us-chains-circle-zellers-properties/article1866399/|archive-date=January 13, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, NRDC invested heavily in The Bay and managed a turnaround by repositioning it as an upscale, fashion forward retailer. However the Zellers chain was still struggling and was seen as a drag on the parent company and its American owner.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2012/07/26/zellers_to_close_last_64_stores_as_target_moves_into_canada.html |title=Zellers to close last 64 stores as Target moves into Canada |first=Dana |last=Flavelle  |work=Toronto Star |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/07/27/zellers-closing-local-stores |title=Zellers closing local stores |publisher=[[Sudbury Star]] |date=July 27, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: Lease acquisitions by Target, liquidation and closures===\n[[File:Zellers Walmart comparison.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The former Zellers (Store 289) location in Ottawa's [[Gloucester, Ontario]] district during its closeout sale, compared with the Walmart it now is]]\nOn January 13, 2011, it was announced that US. retail chain [[Target Corporation]] would purchase the lease agreements of up to 220 Zellers stores for $1.825 billion.<ref name=\"target-reuters\">John Tilak, [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1326316220110113 \"UPDATE 2-Target to enter Canada with Zellers deal, own plans: Target plans to open up to 150 stores in Canada\"], [[Reuters]] January 13, 2011.</ref> Under the agreement, Zellers would sublease the properties and continue to operate them as Zellers locations until January 2012 at the earliest, and at the latest the end of March 2013.<ref name=\"target-sec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27419/000104746911002032/a2201861zex-2_a.htm|title=Transaction Agreement between Zellers Inc., Hudson's Bay Company, Target Corporation and Target Canada Co.|date=2011-01-12|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> At the time of this announcement, Zellers operated 273 stores, well below the 350 stores it had in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/targets-canadian-foray-hits-cost-hurdle/article580809/|title=Target's Canadian foray hits cost hurdle|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"350 stores\"/><ref name=\"thestar.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1232336--retailer-hudson-s-bay-co-to-close-most-of-its-remaining-64-zellers-stores |title= Zellers to close last 64 stores as Target moves into Canada |first=  Dana   |last=Flavelle | newspaper=Toronto Star  |  date=July 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Truro_Daily_2013_04_01\">{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801074749/https://www.trurodaily.com/Business/2013-04-01/article-3211211/Emotions-run-deep-during-Zellers&rsquo-last-day-in-Truro/1|title=Emotions run deep during Zellers' last day in Truro|last=Chiasson|first=Monique|date=April 1, 2013|work=Truro Daily News|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUpon the announcement, it was reported that once the Zellers stores at these locations were closed, Target would renovate 100 to 150 of them to reopen the stores under the Target banner during 2013 and 2014. The remaining acquired sites would be transferred to other retailers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116180142/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/target-heads-north-in-zellers-deal/article1868308/|title=Target heads north in Zellers deal|author=Marina Strauss and Steve Ladurantaye|first=|date=2011-01-13|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=2011-01-13|location=Toronto}}</ref>  HBC had said that it would continue to operate the remaining Zellers stores as a smaller chain in specific communities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2011/01/13/target-zelles-takeover.html|title=Target buys Zellers leases for $1.8B|work=CBC News|date=2011-01-13|accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>\n\nOf the maximum 220 locations, 105 to be transferred to Target were identified in late May 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529123111/http://pressroom.target.com/pr/news/target-selects-initial-zellers-204201.aspx|title=Target Selects Initial Zellers Leases, Vast Majority to Become Target Stores|author=[[Target Corporation]]|date=2011-05-26|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> and another lot of 84 locations in late September 2011, bringing the total number of Zellers stores acquired by Target to 189.<ref name=\"Canada Free Press\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadafreepress.com/index.php/article/40622|title=Hudson's Bay Company Confirms Final List of 189 Zellers Locations to be Assumed by Target|date=September 23, 2011 |publisher=Canada Free Press}}</ref> Of these 189 stores, 125\u2013135 stores would be converted into Target stores,{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} 39 others were resold to [[Walmart Canada]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2011/06/24/walmart-zellers-leases-target.html|title=Walmart picks up 39 Zellers sites from Target|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=CBC |location=Canada |date=2011-06-24|accessdate=2011-06-24}}</ref> and the remaining 15\u201325 leases were either sold to other retailers or returned to the landlords who own the sites.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n[[RioCan Real Estate Investment Trust|RioCan REIT]] was significantly affected, as many of its mall properties include Zellers locations.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\"/><ref name=\"theglobeandmail2\">{{cite web|first=Marina |last=Strauss |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/hbc-seeks-to-close-books-on-zellers-leases/article5011029/ |title=HBC seeks to close books on Zellers leases |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=November 6, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> In addition, the [[United Food and Commercial Workers]] Union planned to hold demonstrations as many Zellers staffers were to be laid off instead of being retained by Target or Walmart. This was in marked contrast to the takeover of Woolco by [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 1994, where all Woolco employees of the acquired stores were retained.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824100704/http://metronews.ca:80/news/canada/340753/zellers-employees-walk-away-empty-handed-in-1-825-billion-deal/|title=Zellers employees walk away empty-handed in $1.825-billion deal|date=August 17, 2012|publisher=[[Metro International|Metro News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824100704/http://metronews.ca:80/news/canada/340753/zellers-employees-walk-away-empty-handed-in-1-825-billion-deal/|archive-date=August 24, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe President and CEO of Zellers, Mark Foote, had a mandate to liquidate the 273 Zellers stores in preparing it for Target's takeover by October 2011. Foote's strategy was to use a blueprint of a retail liquidation, but without the typical insolvency and desperation that plagued failing chains. Foote focused on raising profits, even if that meant losing market share and reducing store traffic, by ramping up inventory levels of higher margin goods over loss leaders such as apparel over deeply discounted paper towels and detergent, and slashing costs. Foote also replaced the expensive fall television ad campaign with a social media blitz on Facebook. Reportedly, the strategy was paying off as Zellers operating profit was \"well ahead of expectations and the retailer had performed very well in 2011.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail1\"/>\n\nIn March 2012, the first 50 Zellers stores were put in liquidation. This included all 39 Zellers stores slated to become Walmart outlets. By mid-June, the latter locations were closed to the public. On June 25, 2012, 17 more stores in Ontario were put in liquidation.<ref name=\"Liquid1\">[http://www.zellers.com/liquidation/en/ Liquidation]. Zellers. Retrieved May 1, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe Hudson's Bay Company announced on July 26, 2012, that it would close most of the 64 remaining stores that were supposed to continue operating as Zellers outlets. A company spokesperson stated that these stores employ 6,400 people, or approximately 100 per location, range in size from 48,000 to 128,000 square feet and are mostly in small towns. The closings of these stores were to happen at the latest on March 31, 2013 which coincided with the deadline date the HBC had to vacate the sites acquired by Target. The HBC's main reason for closing the 64 remaining stores was due to Zellers lack of profitability.<ref name=\"thestar.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalnews.ca/canadas%20remaining%2064%20zellers%20stores%20to%20close/6442686687/story.html|title=Global News - Latest & Current News - Weather, Sports & Health News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/07/26/zellers-closure.html?cmp=rss |work=CBC News |title=Most remaining Zellers stores to close by March 2013 |date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727083617/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/07/26/zellers-closure.html?cmp=rss |archivedate=July 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/hudsons-bay-to-close-remaining-zellers-stores/article4442797/ |title=Hudson's Bay to close remaining Zellers stores |first=Josh |last=O'Kane |work=The Globe and Mail |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> The HBC also remarked that it would not be viable to keep Zellers as an ongoing chain due to the geographical locations of the remaining 64 stores.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Economie/2012/07/26/009-zellers-fermeture-fin.shtml| work=Radio-Canada|title=La fin de Zellers| date=July 26, 2012}}</ref> The HBC did not exclude the possibility of keeping some stores open and converting them as [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]] or [[Home Outfitters]] outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://affaires.lapresse.ca/economie/quebec/201207/26/01-4559709-la-plupart-des-zellers-restants-fermeront.php|title=La plupart des Zellers restants fermeront - Qu\u00e9bec|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the deal with Target Corporation, HBC still a burden in half{{ambiguous|date=December 2016}} of the $226.4-million of Zellers lease obligations remaining through 2016, with the rent for 2012 alone being almost half of HBC's adjusted profit. With HBC preparing an initial public offering in late 2012, it either had terminated these liabilities with landlords at steep discounts or find new tenants to sublet the space.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ari |last=Altstedter |url=http://business.financialpost.com/2012/11/05/outstanding-zellers-rents-to-hit-hudson-bays-ipo/ |title=Hudson's Bay IPO: Share price could be dragged down by Zellers rents |publisher=[[Financial Post]] |date=November 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"theglobeandmail2\"/>\n\nThe final closing Zellers stores started their liquidation sale on December 26, 2012 and the company stopped accepting returns on January 31, 2013. Liquidators sold nearly all of Zellers merchandise, store fixtures and shopping carts at discounted prices.\n\n===2013\u20132020: Zellers as a liquidator===\n[[File:A re-opened Zellers store at Bells Corners in Ottawa.jpg|thumb|The store front of the re-opened Zellers in Bells Corners, part of Nepean in Ottawa.]]\n\nIn January 2013, HBC revised its strategy and decided to keep a total of three stores open under the Zellers banner after March 31, 2013.<ref name=\"three Zellers stores\">{{cite web| title =Zellers will stick around Canada's three biggest cities after Target arrives| url=http://o.canada.com/2013/01/08/zellers-will-stick-around-canadas-three-biggest-cities-after-target-arrives/| accessdate =January 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HBC store locator\">{{cite web| title = HBC store locator| url = http://www.hbc.com/storelocator/?langid=en&src=hbc| accessdate = February 23, 2014| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140311201749/http://www.hbc.com/storelocator/?langid=en&src=hbc| archivedate = March 11, 2014| df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Surrey Now\"/>  Originally these included the store at [[Place Bourassa]] in [[Montr\u00e9al-Nord|Montreal North]], [[Quebec]] but it closed in early 2014. Replacing it was a previously closed Zellers in [[Nepean, Ontario]], which reopened on April 3, 2014, keeping the number of stores at three.<ref>{{cite web|title = Ottawa Metro newspaper ad, page 9 | url=http://reader.metronews.ca/digital_launch.aspx?id=1bc30598-6ee6-4456-b9ba-c81a09224ac9&pnum=9 | accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Zeddy's not dead: A closed Zellers store is actually reopening in Ottawa | url =http://o.canada.com/business/zellers-zeddy-reincarnation/ | accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Zellers returns to Ottawa | url = http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/zellers-returns-to-ottawa-1.1754241 | accessdate=April 3, 2014 }}</ref>  In September 2014, the last Zellers in Western Canada located at [[Semiahmoo Shopping Centre]] in [[Surrey, British Columbia]] was closed, leaving only two stores remaining nationwide: at Kipling Queensway Mall in [[Etobicoke, Ontario]] and Bells Corners in [[Nepean, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Semiahmoo Shopping Centre cites Zellers exit as 'great news' | url=http://www.peacearchnews.com/business/263363491.html | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> Both locations were closed by January 26, 2020.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/zellers-last-two-stores-closing-toronto-ottawa-1.5273710</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/canada-s-two-remaining-zellers-stores-slated-to-close-1.4580805|title=Canada's two remaining Zellers stores slated to close|first=Christy|last=Somos|date=September 6, 2019|website=CTVNews}}</ref><ref name=close>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blogto.com/fashion_style/2020/01/zellers-toronto-close-early-massive-lineups/|title=The last Zellers in Toronto is being forced to close early due to massive lineups|website=www.blogto.com}}</ref>\n\nThese locations no longer operated as  discount department stores, but instead as liquidation outlets for sister chain [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/five-burning-questions-as-zellers-final-two-stores-set-to-close-1.1326514|title=Five burning questions as Zellers' final two stores set to close - BNN Bloomberg|first=Paige|last=Ellis|date=October 4, 2019|website=BNN}}</ref> HBC communications manager Tiffany Bourr\u00e9 described these locations as featuring fashion apparel and a refined home product offering with more from other HBC banners.<ref name=\"three Zellers stores\"/><ref name=\"HBC store locator\"/><ref name=\"Surrey Now\">{{cite web\n |title       = Zellers store to stay open at Semiahmoo Shopping Centre\n |url         = http://www.thenownewspaper.com/business/Zellers+store+stay+open+Semiahmoo+Shopping+Centre/7800250/story.html#ixzz2Hz7zrhhS\n |accessdate  = January 14, 2013\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130130013814/http://www.thenownewspaper.com/business/Zellers+store+stay+open+Semiahmoo+Shopping+Centre/7800250/story.html#ixzz2Hz7zrhhS\n |archivedate = January 30, 2013\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2015, Target Canada ultimately filed for bankruptcy, and began the process of liquidating and closing its 133 locations.<ref name=torstar-condoproject>{{cite news|last1=Pigg|first1=Susan|title=Target pullout leaves condo project in the lurch|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/01/15/target-pullout-leaves-condo-project-in-the-lurch.html|accessdate=March 14, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref> The locations were sold in turn to other parties, such as [[Giant Tiger]], [[Lowe's]], [[Super C (supermarket)|Super C]] and Walmart.<ref name=cp-walmartbuy>{{cite news|title=Walmart to buy 13 former Target Canada stores and a distribution centre|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/walmart-to-buy-13-former-target-canada-stores-and-a-distribution-centre-1.3066182|accessdate=8 May 2015|agency=Canadian Press}}</ref><ref name=torstar-lowes>{{cite news|title=Lowe's to buy 13 Target stores|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/health_wellness/2015/05/11/lowes-to-buy-13-target-stores.html|accessdate=12 May 2015|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=eb-superccarrefour>{{cite news|title=Les travaux pour le Super C s'amorcent au Carrefour Saint-Georges centre|url=http://www.enbeauce.com/actualites/affaires/278243/les-travaux-pour-le-super-c-samorcent-au-carrefour-saint-georges|accessdate=7 November 2015|agency=EnBeauce.com}}</ref><ref name=lapresse-sherbrooke>{{cite news|title=Super Cemm\u00e9nagera dans l'ancien Target|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/economie-et-innovation/201505/30/01-4873911-super-c-emmenagera-dans-lancien-target.php|date=November 2015|work=La Presse}}</ref>\n\n==Stores==\n[[File:Zellersstoreinmoncton.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Zellers location (Store 158) in [[Moncton]]. Closed in 2012, became a [[Target Canada|Target]] in 2013 or 2014, closed again in 2015, and became a [[Canadian Tire]] in 2016.]]\n[[File:ZellersSelect.png|thumb|right|Zellers Select logo]]\nZellers operated stores from St. John's, Newfoundland, to Victoria, British Columbia and employed over 35,000 people. The average store size was 94,000 square feet (8,700 m2). Zellers Select stores were designed for smaller markets with populations under 25,000, with stores averaged 45,000 square feet (4,200 m<sup>2</sup>). Some multi level stores were equipped with a shopping cart system known as the Cartveyor, designed to transport shopping carts between floors next to a standard escalator, while there were few that were so small, they were equipped with elevators open to shoppers, such as with the [[Lawrence Square Shopping Centre]] location in the North York district of Toronto.\n\nIn July 2010, Zellers unveiled prototype store designs in five Winnipeg locations, with two more originally planned for late 2010 and early 2011. One store opened on the lower floor of the downtown Winnipeg Bay store making it the first Bay Zellers hybrid store in the HBC family of stores.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Restaurant===\n'''The Skillet''', Zellers in-store restaurant brand, launched in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chapin|first1=Angelina|title=The Ode: Zellers (1931 - 2011) - Canadian Business - Your Source For Business News|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lifestyle/the-ode-zellers-1931-2011/|website=Canadian Business|accessdate=November 17, 2017|date=January 14, 2011|quote=In 1960, Zellers opened its first in-store restaurant, The Skillet, as well as an auto-centre, and its first store in a suburban mall.}}</ref> The restaurants underwent several revisions and were branded as '''Zellers Family Restaurant''' before their demise.\n\n===Pharmacy===\nAlmost every Zellers location had a pharmacy in it with a few stores in Quebec also having them. Prescription records were sold to other pharmacies in 2011 and Zellers pharmacies ceased operation throughout 2012. Zellers was subject to controversy regarding its sale of patient records.{{clarify|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Liquidation centres===\nAlthough Zellers remained open until 2020 as a store liquidator for [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|Hudson's Bay]] and [[Home Outfitters]], the Zellers chain had also operated a few liquidation centres for its own merchandise. Those were typically former regular Zellers stores that had been converted as liquidation centres for a limited time before closing down for good. The Zellers Family restaurants continued operating in these liquidation centres.\n\n==Products==\nProducts sold at Zellers included clothing, grocery, toys, electronics, furniture, and home supplies.\n\n===Grocery===\nAll Zellers sold basic groceries such as dry snacks and other prepackaged foods. The Neighbourhood Market, which used to be available at some locations, was Zellers expanded section of grocery items, which included frozen and dairy aisles. Prototype stores in Winnipeg featured full grocery departments including fresh produce and baked goods. Such plans were dropped following Target Canada's acquisition of many Zellers leases. Some stores removed their The Neighbourhood Market section.\n\n===Exclusive labels===\nZellers carried many of its own labels and also had exclusive rights in Canada to some other labels:\n<!--Please do not add labels that are found outside of Zellers/Target-->\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Alfred Sung]] Home\n* Beaumark\n* Big Star\n* Big Z {{small|(pillows)}}\n* Home Studio\n* Homestyles\n* Hunt Club\n* Marketsquare\n* Midtown\n* Nest by House & Home\n* Request {{small|(promoted by [[Ashlee Simpson]])}}\n* Sportek {{small|(unrelated to [[Sport Chek]])}}\n* [[Stuff by Hilary Duff]]\n* Truly\n* [[X Games]]\n* Zeddy {{small|(baby products)}}\n}}\n\n====Acquired labels====\nSome labels exclusive to [[Target Corporation]] in the United States were previously exclusive to Zellers in Canada. After Target's acquisition of Zellers leases until its closure, [[Target Canada]] became the exclusive store for the following brands\n*[[Cherokee Inc.|Cherokee]]\n* [[Mossimo]]\n*[[Wabasso Design Ideas|Wabasso]]\n\nHowever, Target Canada closed in 2015, leaving Wabasso, and Mossimo unavailable in Canada since then. Cherokee was then carried by [[Sears Canada]] for a short period, until it too closed in January 2018. With the demise of Zellers, Target Canada and Sears Canada, none of these brands are carried in Canada.\n\n==Customer service==\nOn January 6, 2012, [[CBC Television]]'s ''[[Marketplace (Canadian TV program)|Marketplace]]'' announced that Zellers received the title of Canada's Worst Customer Service as a department store, based on a survey conducted by CBC with the [[L\u00e9ger Marketing]] research firm in eight metropolitan areas. The retailer refused to be interviewed by ''Marketplace'' host [[Erica Johnson]] regarding its ranking, providing her with a written statement instead. Zellers also did not offer a refund to the mystery shopper who bought a used coffeemaker that was presented as new, and attempted to return the product after the advertised 30 day return period. Zellers Customer Service did not respond to this customer's Twitter message seeking satisfactory resolution.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/marketplace/episodes/2012-episodes/canadas-worst-customer-service-store-edition |title=Canada's Worst Customer Service |publisher=CBC |accessdate=2015-01-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105224451/http://www.cbc.ca/marketplace/episodes/2012-episodes/canadas-worst-customer-service-store-edition |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Advertising==\nZellers ran a Festive Finale advertising campaign in late 2011. Zeddy was also used as a mascot to advertise the retailer's toy selection.\n\n===Festive Finale===\nThe Festive Finale campaign was used to advertise Zellers last Christmas and holiday season sale in December 2011. There was a website called Zellers Facebook.ca which allowed customers to vote for their favourite coupon and musical genre. While Zellers recommended that customers have a Facebook account and Like the company, both of these steps were optional. It was also possible to record a radio commercial for Zellers Moonlight Madness sale by using a computer microphone and reading the site's [[teleprompter]]. Zellers also had social networking service accounts on Twitter and YouTube. Festive Finale was criticized for its Boxing Week coupon.\n\n===Loyalty program===\nAs a [[Hudson's Bay Company]] subsidiary, Zellers promoted the [[Hudson's Bay Rewards]] program also available at [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|Hudson's Bay]] and [[Home Outfitters]]. It had been known as Club Z and HBC Rewards. The program used a points card, available at no charge but only accepted by Zellers and other partners. A Hudson's Bay MasterCard issued by Capital One is also available, which rewards customers with one point per dollar spent on the card at any retailer. Any Zellers cashier failing to inform a customer about the HBC MasterCard had to give that customer 10,000 HBC points. This is equivalent to 250 Hudson's Bay points, or one eighth of the requirement for a $10 gift card. Hudson's Bay points can still be redeemed for Hudson's Bay gift cards.\n\n===Slogans===\nNumerous slogans were used by Zellers:\n* Early 1980s: The low prices of Zellers are in the news (Zellers low prices are making headlines)\n* 1980s: Only you'll know how little you paid\n* 1980s: Shopping anywhere else is pointless\n* Late 1980s and 1990s Where the lowest price is the law!, followed by Where the lowest price is the law everyday and Because the lowest price is the law. as revisions including a few animated commercials featured Batman and Robin with the villains like the Joker, the Penguin, Catwoman and the Riddler.\n* 1990s Truly Canadian\n* 1997\u20132000 Better and Better\n* 2000\u20132013 Everything from A to Z\n<!--Please don't add the \"Expect More, Pay Less\" slogan, as it is Target's slogan and Zellers never used it-->\n\n===Zeddy===\n[[File:Zeddy Wheel.ogg|thumb|Zeddy encourages children to ride the Zeddy Wheel attraction at Zellers.]]\nZeddy is a teddy bear mascot used by Zellers all over Canada. He was first used in 1986<ref name=\"Zeddy contest\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.hbc.com/hbc/mediacentre/press/hbc/press.asp?prId=438 | title = Zellers Announces Everything Must Go\u2026 Including Zeddy\n| publisher = Zellers | accessdate = 2012-12-21}}</ref> as an advertising campaign, and then rose to his popularity by the early 1990s. The main purpose of Zeddy was to advertise Toyland, the toy section in Zellers stores. Zellers provided a stuffed Zeddy bear for any child who had a birthday party sponsored by Zellers. There was also a Zellers employee in a giant Zeddy costume hosting the party. Lineup toys of Zeddy were also created.<ref name=\"JasonFinale\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKs2mh0mY8U | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130810010039/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKs2mh0mY8U | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-08-10 | title = Zellers' Festive Finale presents: \"Pick the Playlist\" with Jason the Cashier | publisher = Zellers | accessdate = 2011-11-28}}</ref> In the final months before the last of the Zellers stores were closed permanently, the company distributed a large batch of stuffed Zeddy Bears for sale in stores throughout the network.\n[[File:Zeddy.jpg|thumb|right|195px|A Zeddy Bear, as sold in the chain's last months]]\nMany stores feature a Zeddy Wheel ride, which accommodates one young child on a miniature [[ferris wheel]] type ride. The ride costs $1 and plays carnival music when in use. When no one is riding the wheel, Zeddy says on a regular basis Come ride with me! All aboard the Zeddy Wheel! in an attempt to attract customers.<!--this was included with <ref> tags; updated to comment December 2016: Voice clips and pictures coming soon.-->  Despite Zeddy being withdrawn as Zellers official mascot in 2005, the Zeddy Wheel remained in operation at stores featuring it unless it is out of service, and the voice track was unchanged over the years. Some wheels removed the big Zeddy sticker in favour of multiple, small generic stickers.\n\nZeddy remains used as a baby brand for products such as diapers and baby bath products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zellers.com/content/en/kids/Zeddy/Zeddy.aspx |title=Zeddy |publisher=Zellers |accessdate=2011-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927115252/http://www.zellers.com/content/en/kids/Zeddy/Zeddy.aspx |archivedate=September 27, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nDuring the Festive Finale campaign in 2011, Zeddy was reintroduced in weekly flyers for Zellers Toyland before closing their stores for Target or Walmart. The character was used as a static picture, but no animated television commercials of him were made during this season. However, some employees decided to wear the Zeddy costume to celebrate the return of this teddy bear. Shortly thereafter, in December 2011, Zellers launched a Zeddy Bucks promotion. Those who spent at least $50 before taxes on toys received a pair of red [[2012 Summer Olympics]] mittens, plus a $10 Zeddy Bucks voucher. This voucher could only be used on a later date.<ref>Zellers December 2011 Flyer.</ref>\n\nWith the last Zellers stores set to close in 2013, the Hudson Bay Company announced in September 2012 that it was looking for a charity organization to adopt Zeddy so that the mascot could live on after Zellers.<ref name=\"Zeddy contest\"/> In a social media ad campaign, ''Zellers Everything Must GO Including Zeddy'', Zeddy was featured in an online video where the mascot was abandoned in the woods by a Zellers executive telling Zeddy that Zellers was liquidating, and everything must go, including him. Organizations were invited to submit on Zellers Facebook page what their plans for Zeddy were.<ref name=\"Zeddy after Zellers\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1257789--zellers-prepares-to-close-so-what-happens-to-zeddy-the-bear | location=Toronto | work=The Star | title=Zellers prepares to close, so what happens to Zeddy the bear? - thestar.com | date=September 17, 2012}}</ref> There were over 30,000 votes, and the final three contenders were Autism Ontario, Camp Trillium and [[Cystic Fibrosis Canada]]. Voters selected Camp Trillium as the winner and chosen adopter. There are several notable Zeddy iterations including most famously, bush pilot Zeddy.<ref name=\"Camp Trillium\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120015756/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1072675/zellers-iconic-mascot-zeddy-finds-new-home-with-camp-trillium|title=Zellers Iconic Mascot Zeddy Finds New Home With Camp Trillium|website=www.newswire.ca|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120015756/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1072675/zellers-iconic-mascot-zeddy-finds-new-home-with-camp-trillium|archive-date=November 20, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=National News: Zellers Iconic Mascot Zeddy Finds New Home With Camp Trillium|url=http://www.northumberlandview.ca/index.php?module=news&type=user&func=display&sid=18633|accessdate=17 November 2012|newspaper=Northumberland View|date=16 November 2012|location=Roseneath ON}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Zeddy4.jpg|1 \u2013 2003\nFile:Zeddy-Festive-Finale.png|2 \u2013 November 2011\n</gallery>\n#Zeddy, on the far right, is walking in a parade in 2003.\n#Zeddy appears in the Toyland section of Toyland in November 2011.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario|Canada}}\nOther discount retailer that once operated in Canada and similar concept as Zellers\n* Kmart opened first store in 1929 as Kresge and closed Canadian operations in 1998 some stores sold to Zellers\n* [[Woolco]] appeared in the 1960s and closed operations completely in 1994 most stores sold to Walmart some later acquired by Zellers\n* Towers Department Stores emerged in 1960 and ceased operations in 1991; all stores sold to Zellers \n* [[Horizon (store)|Horizon]], a competitor in the 1970s, created by the [[T. Eaton Company]]\nSuccessor of Zellers:\n* Target Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/business/target-leaving-canada-losing-money-every-day-1.2189973|title=Target leaving Canada: 'Losing money every day'|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> opened in 2013 after acquiring a number of former Zellers leases [[Retail apocalypse|all stores were closed in 2015]].\n\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Interior of a Zellers store.jpg|The inside of a Zellers store (Store 106) at Meadowlark Mall in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]] in 2007. Closed in May 2012, became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2013.\nFile:Zellers Etobicoke, ON, Canada 3 (35419700636).jpg|The former Kipling Queensway Mall Zellers in [[Etobicoke]], [[Ontario]] in 2017.\nFile:Zellers cornwall.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 6) in the Eastcourt Mall, [[Cornwall]], [[Ontario]], in 2013. Closed later that year, and has now been expanded into [[Ardene]], [[No Frills (grocery store)|No Frills]], [[Dollarama]], and Urban Planet.\nFile:Lawrence Square Shopping Centre.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 75) in the Lawrence Square shopping centre in [[North York]], [[Ontario]] in 2008. Closed in 2012, sat vacant for 3 and a half years, until [[Marshalls]] and [[HomeSense]] took over Zellers' former space in 2016. [[PetSmart]] was added in 2019.\nFile:County Fair Mall Thunder Bay.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 116) in the County Fair Mall in [[Thunder Bay]], [[Ontario]] in 2008. Closed in 2012, and became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2013.\nFile:Fairview Mall - panoramio.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 253) along with a [[Mark's]] and a former [[Future Shop]] at the Fairview Mall in [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]], in 2007. Zellers closed in 2012 and became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2012 or 2013. [[Future Shop]] closed in 2015 and became an [[IKEA]] in 2016.\nFile:Plaza C\u00f4te-Des-Neiges Listing Zellers Closing Inside Mall.JPG|A Zellers store (Store 213) during its' closing sale at Plaza Cote-Des-Neiges in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], in May 2012. As stated from the last days sign, this store closed on June 6, 2012 and got replaced by a Walmart in 2013.\nFile:Zellers Laval, QC 1 (8274483942).jpg|A Zellers store (Store 72) at the Les Galeries Laval in [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]], [[Quebec]] in 2012. This store closed in 2013 and became an EconoMax in 2014.\nFile:Zellers Mega Centre Notre Dame Laval, QC 2 (8274486332).jpg|A Zellers store (Store 409) during its' closing sale at Mega Centre in [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]], [[Quebec]] in 2012. Closed in 2013 and became a [[Target Canada|Target]] later that year. [[Target Canada|Target]] closed in 2015, then in 2016 or 2017, the former space became a [[Jysk]]. A [[Super C (supermarket)|Super C]] can be seen in the background.\nFile:Market-Mall.jpg|A sign for the Market Mall in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]], which includes [[Safeway (Canada)|Safeway]], [[Shoppers Drug Mart]], a liquor store, and Zellers. The Zellers part of the sign, along with the store, closed in 2012, sat vacant for 2 years and a half, but got replaced by a mini golf attraction in 2015. The liquor store part of the sign along with the store closed in 2018. It is unknown if the sign is still standing as of 2020.\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Zellers}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.zellers.com Official website] (from the [[Wayback Machine|Internet Archives Wayback Machine]])\n*[http://www.hbcheritage.ca/history/acquisitions/zellers Zellers history] at Hudson's Bay Company website\n\n{{Hudson's_Bay_Trading_Company,_L.P.}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Brampton]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Department stores of Canada]]\n[[Category:Hudson's Bay Company]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1978 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian retail company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n<!-- Please do not replace the current infobox for the defunct infobox until all stores have closed. Thank you for your understanding -->\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Zellers\n| logo = Zellers logo.svg\n| type = Subsidiary\n| founder = Walter P. Zeller\n| fate = Most store leases acquired by [[Target Canada]], [[Walmart Canada]] or closed outright. Selected locations were retained to serve as liquidation centres for other HBC retail chains until 2020\n| industry = Discount retail store\n| defunct = March 2013 (as a chain) <br/>\nJan. 2020 (liquidation stores)\n| products = Clothing, grocery, footwear, bedding, furniture, jewelry, beauty products, electronics, toys, sports equipment, appliances, housewares\n| owner = Hudson's Bay Company<ref>cite web|url=http://www.hbc.com/hbc/about/contacts/|title=Contacts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719100513/http://www.hbc.com/hbc/about/contacts/|archive-date=July 19, 2010|website=Hudson's Bay Company access-date=July 7, 2010</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| foundation = 1931\n| location = Brampton, Ontario, Canada\n| locations = 350 (1999)<ref name=\"350 stores\"/>\n| website = [https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.zellers.com  zellers.com] archive\n}}\n\n'''Zellers''' was a Canadian chain [[Discount store|discount department retailer]] that was based in [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]]. It was founded in 1931 and was acquired by [[Hudson's Bay Company]] (HBC) in 1978.\n\nA series of acquisitions and expansions allowed Zellers to reach its peak in the 1990s, with 350 stores across the country in 1999.<ref name=\"350 stores\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MARTHA+STEWART,+ZELLARS+NAMED+IN+LAWSUIT.-a056083276| title=\"MARTHA STEWART, ZELLARS [''sic''] NAMED IN LAWSUIT\"\n| first      = Brian |last=Dunn \n| newspaper  = HFN The Weekly Newspaper for the Home Furnishing Network\n| date       = October 4, 1999|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref> However, fierce competition by [[Walmart Canada]] and an inability to adjust to [[Retail apocalypse|the increasingly volatile retailing industry]] resulted in Zellers losing significant ground in the 2000s. At the same time, HBC's new owner [[NRDC Equity Partners]] was focusing on bolstering and re-positioning Zellers' sister chain, [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]], with an upscale and fashion-oriented direction, and saw Zellers as a detriment to the turnaround.\n\nIn January 2011, HBC announced that it would sell the lease agreements for up to 220 Zellers stores to the US. chain [[Target Corporation|Target]] for $1.825 billion. In turn, Target announced its intent to convert many of them to [[Target Canada|Canadian locations of Target]], and re-sell the remainder to other parties such as [[Walmart Canada]], resulting in their liquidation and eventual closure. While HBC retained 64 Zellers locations, it announced on July 26, 2012 that the majority of them would be liquidated and closed by March 31, 2013 due to their lack of profitability. After the chain went under, HBC operated some Zellers-branded locations as liquidation outlets for The Bay, with the last of those stores closed on January 26, 2020.<ref name=\"January 26, 2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/zellers-closing-memorabilia-1.5425471|title=As final Zellers stores close, former employees swap memories, memorabilia|last=Watters|first=Haydn|date=January 19, 2020|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nOn Saturday August 4, 1928 Zellers Ltd was born in [[London, Ontario]]. Walter P. Zeller, its founder, opened his new store & head office at 176 Dundas Street after working for years for Metropolitan Department Stores, F.W. Woolworth Company and Kresges. This new store was to be a part of a chain of Canadian department stores. The plan at the start was to have stores opened in London, St. Catharines, Niagara Falls, Fort Williams and St. John N.B. The London store had a street frontage of 53 feet and a depth of 137 feet. It had a total of 7,000 square feet of space on the ground floor with 2,000 square feet of counter space spread out around the store. Sixty women were hired for the opening day working in 21 different departments. Within months Zellers was doing such good business that they were bought out by the American firm Schulte-United Ltd. Within two years the rebranded stores went bankrupt. Walter Zeller promptly bought most of the failed Schulte stores and relaunched Zellers in late 1931. Zellers Department Store remained at 176 Dundas Street until the late 1980s.<ref>London Free Press August 3rd, 1928 edition, http://torontoist.com/2015/01/vintage-toronto-ads-zellers/ & http://www.hbcheritage.ca/\u2026/hist\u2026/people/builders/zeller.asp</ref>\n\n===1930s\u20131960s: Early years, partnership with W.T. Grant===\n[[File:Zellers 1931 Toronto.jpg|thumb|Zellers advertisement in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' for its 1931 grand opening in Toronto. The announced location later became part of the [[Toronto Eaton Centre]].]]\nThe company was founded in 1931 by [[Walter P. Zeller]] as stores for thrifty Canadians.<ref name=\"Zellers history\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/acquisitions/retail/zellers |title=HBC Heritage: The Zellers Story |work=Hudson's Bay Company |year=2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> The chain began with the purchase of the fourteen Canadian locations of American retailer [[H. L. Green Company|Schulte-United]], all of which were in Southern Ontario. Almost immediately, Zellers initiated an aggressive expansion strategy. Within 25 years, Zellers operated 60 stores and employed 3,000 people.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In 1952, in a move to expand into Atlantic Canada, it acquired the [[Federal Stores]] chain of [[variety store]]s, adding more than 12 new Zellers locations.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\nDuring this period of expansion, Zellers concluded a deal with [[W.T. Grant]], a similar chain of American mass merchandise department stores.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> This arrangement allowed W.T. Grant to purchase 10% of Zellers shares and eventually a 51% ownership in 1959.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>  In exchange, the Grant Company made available to Zellers its experience in merchandising, real estate, store development, and general administration. Zellers employees were sent to Grant stores and head office for training and the two companies made common buying trips to east Asia.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In the 1950s, the chain again began opening new locations and in 1956, opened its first self-serve location at the [[Norgate shopping centre]] in [[Saint-Laurent, Quebec]].<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> Stores opened in 1960 employed many new innovations, including the first in store restaurant, the first automotive centre and the first suburban location.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\n===1970s\u20131980s: Zellers acquires Fields, HBC acquires Zellers===\nIn 1975, Zellers adopted its final logo. By 1976, Zellers had grown to a chain of 155 stores, with annual sales of $407 million.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\nAlthough Zellers was prospering, W.T. Grant was facing intense competition in the United States, and was forced to withdraw entirely from its Canadian operations. In 1976, [[Fields (department store)|Fields]], a clothing retailer based in Vancouver, British Columbia, offered to purchase a 50.1% stake in Zellers for $32,675,000. Zellers' shareholders, unhappy with the idea of Zellers becoming a subsidiary of Fields, reversed the takeover and purchased Fields and its hardware store division, [[Marshall Wells]]. This sale added 70 Fields stores and 162 franchised Marshall Wells stores to the company. Fields president and founder, Joseph Segal was appointed as president of Zellers.<ref name=\"fields\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hbcheritage.ca/hbcheritage/history/acquisitions/retail/fields |title=HBC Heritage: Fields, The Strength of an Idea |work=Hudson's Bay Company |year=2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1978, Zellers presented a bid to acquire 100% ownership of the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] (HBC). HBC management, recognizing Zellers profitability and the potential to enter a new retail segment, decided to purchase Zellers instead. Zellers and Fields, operating in very different retail segments from HBC, were kept intact and established as separate divisions of the company. HBC acquired full ownership of Zellers and Fields in 1981 and Marshall Wells in 1982. By 1985, HBC had sold Marshall Wells for $20 million, because it was not relevant to its department store business.\n\nCounterfeit video games for the [[Atari 2600]] were manufactured in Taiwan and sold by Zellers in the 1980s, usually under new names and artwork and occasionally with [[ROM hacking|modified graphics]]. All games were [[Copyright infringement|pirated]] copies of titles created either by [[Atari, Inc.|Atari]] itself or by third-party developers, such as [[Activision]]. Zellers was eventually forced by Atari to stop selling these games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512093632/http://retronouveau.tumblr.com/post/17268200307/les-jeux-atari-2600-de-zellers|title=Les jeux Atari 2600 de Zellers|author=Retro Nouveau|publisher=Tumblr|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512093632/http://retronouveau.tumblr.com/post/17268200307/les-jeux-atari-2600-de-zellers|archive-date=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-09-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Sun\">{{cite news | url=http://www.ottawasun.com/2014/04/03/zellers-reopens-its-doors-in-bells-corners?token=93bac5c80986d88d4baeb7111f167a0e | title=Zellers reopens its doors in Bells Corners | work=[[Ottawa Sun]] | date=3 April 2014 | accessdate=3 April 2014 | author=Desrosiers, Sophie}}</ref> Zellers released 18 games for the Atari 2600 in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite web\n|title = AtariAge - Companies - Zellers\n|url=https://www.atariage.com/company_page.php?SystemID=2600&CompanyID=61\n|accessdate = 2015-09-13}}</ref>\n\n===1990s: Further acquisitions===\nIn 1990, Hudson's Bay Company acquired the 51 stores of the [[Towers Department Stores|Towers/Bonimart]] chain from the [[Oshawa Group]], and converted most of them to Zellers outlets, including its flagship location in [[Toronto]]. Zellers advertisements at the time featured both the Towers [[mascot]], Sparky, and the Zellers mascot, Zeddy, walking arm in arm. During this period, Zellers used the slogan \"the lowest price is the law.\"\n\nIn 1993, Hudson's Bay Company purchased the assets of the bankrupt [[Woodward's]] chain, including 21 store locations.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> These were converted into Zellers and The Bay stores, and greatly expanded the company's presence in Western Canada.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> In 1998, Hudson's Bay Company acquired [[Kmart]]'s Canadian division, and merged it with the Zellers division to create a larger combined chain under the Zellers name.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/> While some Kmart locations were closed, many sites became full Zellers outlets.\n\nIn 1996, Hudson's Bay Company closed its Zellers head office in [[Montreal]], Quebec and merged it with the Hudson's Bay Company headquarters in downtown Toronto. By 1998, Hudson's Bay Company regained a Zellers head office after Zellers took over Kmart's Canadian head office in [[Brampton]], Ontario.<ref name=\"Zellers history\"/>\n\n===2000s: Decline===\nOn February 28, 2006, Hudson's Bay Company was taken private by [[South Carolina]] businessman [[Jerry Zucker (businessman)|Jerry Zucker]]. In Hudson's Bay Company's last year as a publicly traded company, Zellers had 291 stores and lost $107 million on sales of $4.2 billion.<ref name=\"atzellers\">{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215044435/https://www.thestar.com/business/2009/07/31/at_zellers_lowest_price_is_still_prime_focus.html|title=At Zellers, lowest price is still prime focus|last=Flavelle|first=Dana|date=July 31, 2009|newspaper=Toronto Star|access-date=|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nMark Foote, who had headed general merchandise at [[Loblaw Companies]] and was president of [[Canadian Tire]] Corp's retail division, was appointed President and CEO of Zellers in 2008 and he was credited with stabilizing the chain, though it still struggled against Walmart Canada.<ref name=\"atzellers\" /><ref name=\"theglobeandmail1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/zellers-ceo-rewrites-the-book-on-liquidation/article4182420/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Zellers CEO rewrites the book on liquidation | date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Zucker's death in 2008, Hudson's Bay Company and its subsidiaries including Zellers came under the ownership of a New York based company, [[NRDC Equity Partners]], which was headed by [[Richard A. Baker (businessman)|Richard Baker]]. NRDC owns the [[Lord & Taylor]] upscale specialty retail department store chain in the United States.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113080235/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/us-chains-circle-zellers-properties/article1866399/|title=US. chains circle Zellers properties|last1=Strauss|first1=Marina|last2=Ladurantaye|first2=Steve|date=January 11, 2011|work=The Globe and Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113080235/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/us-chains-circle-zellers-properties/article1866399/|archive-date=January 13, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, NRDC invested heavily in The Bay and managed a turnaround by repositioning it as an upscale, fashion forward retailer. However the Zellers chain was still struggling and was seen as a drag on the parent company and its American owner.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2012/07/26/zellers_to_close_last_64_stores_as_target_moves_into_canada.html |title=Zellers to close last 64 stores as Target moves into Canada |first=Dana |last=Flavelle  |work=Toronto Star |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/07/27/zellers-closing-local-stores |title=Zellers closing local stores |publisher=[[Sudbury Star]] |date=July 27, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: Lease acquisitions by Target, liquidation and closures===\n[[File:Zellers Walmart comparison.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The former Zellers (Store 289) location in Ottawa's [[Gloucester, Ontario]] district during its closeout sale, compared with the Walmart it now is]]\nOn January 13, 2011, it was announced that US. retail chain [[Target Corporation]] would purchase the lease agreements of up to 220 Zellers stores for $1.825 billion.<ref name=\"target-reuters\">John Tilak, [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1326316220110113 \"UPDATE 2-Target to enter Canada with Zellers deal, own plans: Target plans to open up to 150 stores in Canada\"], [[Reuters]] January 13, 2011.</ref> Under the agreement, Zellers would sublease the properties and continue to operate them as Zellers locations until January 2012 at the earliest, and at the latest the end of March 2013.<ref name=\"target-sec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/27419/000104746911002032/a2201861zex-2_a.htm|title=Transaction Agreement between Zellers Inc., Hudson's Bay Company, Target Corporation and Target Canada Co.|date=2011-01-12|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=2011-03-28}}</ref> At the time of this announcement, Zellers operated 273 stores, well below the 350 stores it had in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/targets-canadian-foray-hits-cost-hurdle/article580809/|title=Target's Canadian foray hits cost hurdle|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"350 stores\"/><ref name=\"thestar.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1232336--retailer-hudson-s-bay-co-to-close-most-of-its-remaining-64-zellers-stores |title= Zellers to close last 64 stores as Target moves into Canada |first=  Dana   |last=Flavelle | newspaper=Toronto Star  |  date=July 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Truro_Daily_2013_04_01\">{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801074749/https://www.trurodaily.com/Business/2013-04-01/article-3211211/Emotions-run-deep-during-Zellers&rsquo-last-day-in-Truro/1|title=Emotions run deep during Zellers' last day in Truro|last=Chiasson|first=Monique|date=April 1, 2013|work=Truro Daily News|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUpon the announcement, it was reported that once the Zellers stores at these locations were closed, Target would renovate 100 to 150 of them to reopen the stores under the Target banner during 2013 and 2014. The remaining acquired sites would be transferred to other retailers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116180142/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/target-heads-north-in-zellers-deal/article1868308/|title=Target heads north in Zellers deal|author=Marina Strauss and Steve Ladurantaye|first=|date=2011-01-13|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=2011-01-13|location=Toronto}}</ref>  HBC had said that it would continue to operate the remaining Zellers stores as a smaller chain in specific communities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2011/01/13/target-zelles-takeover.html|title=Target buys Zellers leases for $1.8B|work=CBC News|date=2011-01-13|accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>\n\nOf the maximum 220 locations, 105 to be transferred to Target were identified in late May 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529123111/http://pressroom.target.com/pr/news/target-selects-initial-zellers-204201.aspx|title=Target Selects Initial Zellers Leases, Vast Majority to Become Target Stores|author=[[Target Corporation]]|date=2011-05-26|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> and another lot of 84 locations in late September 2011, bringing the total number of Zellers stores acquired by Target to 189.<ref name=\"Canada Free Press\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadafreepress.com/index.php/article/40622|title=Hudson's Bay Company Confirms Final List of 189 Zellers Locations to be Assumed by Target|date=September 23, 2011 |publisher=Canada Free Press}}</ref> Of these 189 stores, 125\u2013135 stores would be converted into Target stores,{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} 39 others were resold to [[Walmart Canada]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2011/06/24/walmart-zellers-leases-target.html|title=Walmart picks up 39 Zellers sites from Target|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|publisher=CBC |location=Canada |date=2011-06-24|accessdate=2011-06-24}}</ref> and the remaining 15\u201325 leases were either sold to other retailers or returned to the landlords who own the sites.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n[[RioCan Real Estate Investment Trust|RioCan REIT]] was significantly affected, as many of its mall properties include Zellers locations.<ref name=\"circle-zellers\"/><ref name=\"theglobeandmail2\">{{cite web|first=Marina |last=Strauss |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/hbc-seeks-to-close-books-on-zellers-leases/article5011029/ |title=HBC seeks to close books on Zellers leases |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=November 6, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> In addition, the [[United Food and Commercial Workers]] Union planned to hold demonstrations as many Zellers staffers were to be laid off instead of being retained by Target or Walmart. This was in marked contrast to the takeover of Woolco by [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 1994, where all Woolco employees of the acquired stores were retained.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824100704/http://metronews.ca:80/news/canada/340753/zellers-employees-walk-away-empty-handed-in-1-825-billion-deal/|title=Zellers employees walk away empty-handed in $1.825-billion deal|date=August 17, 2012|publisher=[[Metro International|Metro News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824100704/http://metronews.ca:80/news/canada/340753/zellers-employees-walk-away-empty-handed-in-1-825-billion-deal/|archive-date=August 24, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe President and CEO of Zellers, Mark Foote, had a mandate to liquidate the 273 Zellers stores in preparing it for Target's takeover by October 2011. Foote's strategy was to use a blueprint of a retail liquidation, but without the typical insolvency and desperation that plagued failing chains. Foote focused on raising profits, even if that meant losing market share and reducing store traffic, by ramping up inventory levels of higher margin goods over loss leaders such as apparel over deeply discounted paper towels and detergent, and slashing costs. Foote also replaced the expensive fall television ad campaign with a social media blitz on Facebook. Reportedly, the strategy was paying off as Zellers operating profit was \"well ahead of expectations and the retailer had performed very well in 2011.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail1\"/>\n\nIn March 2012, the first 50 Zellers stores were put in liquidation. This included all 39 Zellers stores slated to become Walmart outlets. By mid-June, the latter locations were closed to the public. On June 25, 2012, 17 more stores in Ontario were put in liquidation.<ref name=\"Liquid1\">[http://www.zellers.com/liquidation/en/ Liquidation]. Zellers. Retrieved May 1, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe Hudson's Bay Company announced on July 26, 2012, that it would close most of the 64 remaining stores that were supposed to continue operating as Zellers outlets. A company spokesperson stated that these stores employ 6,400 people, or approximately 100 per location, range in size from 48,000 to 128,000 square feet and are mostly in small towns. The closings of these stores were to happen at the latest on March 31, 2013 which coincided with the deadline date the HBC had to vacate the sites acquired by Target. The HBC's main reason for closing the 64 remaining stores was due to Zellers lack of profitability.<ref name=\"thestar.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalnews.ca/canadas%20remaining%2064%20zellers%20stores%20to%20close/6442686687/story.html|title=Global News - Latest & Current News - Weather, Sports & Health News|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/07/26/zellers-closure.html?cmp=rss |work=CBC News |title=Most remaining Zellers stores to close by March 2013 |date=July 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727083617/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/07/26/zellers-closure.html?cmp=rss |archivedate=July 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/hudsons-bay-to-close-remaining-zellers-stores/article4442797/ |title=Hudson's Bay to close remaining Zellers stores |first=Josh |last=O'Kane |work=The Globe and Mail |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> The HBC also remarked that it would not be viable to keep Zellers as an ongoing chain due to the geographical locations of the remaining 64 stores.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Economie/2012/07/26/009-zellers-fermeture-fin.shtml| work=Radio-Canada|title=La fin de Zellers| date=July 26, 2012}}</ref> The HBC did not exclude the possibility of keeping some stores open and converting them as [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]] or [[Home Outfitters]] outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://affaires.lapresse.ca/economie/quebec/201207/26/01-4559709-la-plupart-des-zellers-restants-fermeront.php|title=La plupart des Zellers restants fermeront - Qu\u00e9bec|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the deal with Target Corporation, HBC still a burden in half{{ambiguous|date=December 2016}} of the $226.4-million of Zellers lease obligations remaining through 2016, with the rent for 2012 alone being almost half of HBC's adjusted profit. With HBC preparing an initial public offering in late 2012, it either had terminated these liabilities with landlords at steep discounts or find new tenants to sublet the space.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ari |last=Altstedter |url=http://business.financialpost.com/2012/11/05/outstanding-zellers-rents-to-hit-hudson-bays-ipo/ |title=Hudson's Bay IPO: Share price could be dragged down by Zellers rents |publisher=[[Financial Post]] |date=November 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"theglobeandmail2\"/>\n\nThe final closing Zellers stores started their liquidation sale on December 26, 2012 and the company stopped accepting returns on January 31, 2013. Liquidators sold nearly all of Zellers merchandise, store fixtures and shopping carts at discounted prices.\n\n===2013\u20132020: Zellers as a liquidator===\n[[File:A re-opened Zellers store at Bells Corners in Ottawa.jpg|thumb|The store front of the re-opened Zellers in Bells Corners, part of Nepean in Ottawa.]]\n\nIn January 2013, HBC revised its strategy and decided to keep a total of three stores open under the Zellers banner after March 31, 2013.<ref name=\"three Zellers stores\">{{cite web| title =Zellers will stick around Canada's three biggest cities after Target arrives| url=http://o.canada.com/2013/01/08/zellers-will-stick-around-canadas-three-biggest-cities-after-target-arrives/| accessdate =January 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HBC store locator\">{{cite web| title = HBC store locator| url = http://www.hbc.com/storelocator/?langid=en&src=hbc| accessdate = February 23, 2014| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140311201749/http://www.hbc.com/storelocator/?langid=en&src=hbc| archivedate = March 11, 2014| df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Surrey Now\"/>  Originally these included the store at [[Place Bourassa]] in [[Montr\u00e9al-Nord|Montreal North]], [[Quebec]] but it closed in early 2014. Replacing it was a previously closed Zellers in [[Nepean, Ontario]], which reopened on April 3, 2014, keeping the number of stores at three.<ref>{{cite web|title = Ottawa Metro newspaper ad, page 9 | url=http://reader.metronews.ca/digital_launch.aspx?id=1bc30598-6ee6-4456-b9ba-c81a09224ac9&pnum=9 | accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Zeddy's not dead: A closed Zellers store is actually reopening in Ottawa | url =http://o.canada.com/business/zellers-zeddy-reincarnation/ | accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Zellers returns to Ottawa | url = http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/zellers-returns-to-ottawa-1.1754241 | accessdate=April 3, 2014 }}</ref>  In September 2014, the last Zellers in Western Canada located at [[Semiahmoo Shopping Centre]] in [[Surrey, British Columbia]] was closed, leaving only two stores remaining nationwide: at Kipling Queensway Mall in [[Etobicoke, Ontario]] and Bells Corners in [[Nepean, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Semiahmoo Shopping Centre cites Zellers exit as 'great news' | url=http://www.peacearchnews.com/business/263363491.html | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> Both locations were closed by January 26, 2020.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/zellers-last-two-stores-closing-toronto-ottawa-1.5273710</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/canada-s-two-remaining-zellers-stores-slated-to-close-1.4580805|title=Canada's two remaining Zellers stores slated to close|first=Christy|last=Somos|date=September 6, 2019|website=CTVNews}}</ref><ref name=close>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blogto.com/fashion_style/2020/01/zellers-toronto-close-early-massive-lineups/|title=The last Zellers in Toronto is being forced to close early due to massive lineups|website=www.blogto.com}}</ref>\n\nThese locations no longer operated as  discount department stores, but instead as liquidation outlets for sister chain [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|The Bay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/five-burning-questions-as-zellers-final-two-stores-set-to-close-1.1326514|title=Five burning questions as Zellers' final two stores set to close - BNN Bloomberg|first=Paige|last=Ellis|date=October 4, 2019|website=BNN}}</ref> HBC communications manager Tiffany Bourr\u00e9 described these locations as featuring fashion apparel and a refined home product offering with more from other HBC banners.<ref name=\"three Zellers stores\"/><ref name=\"HBC store locator\"/><ref name=\"Surrey Now\">{{cite web\n |title       = Zellers store to stay open at Semiahmoo Shopping Centre\n |url         = http://www.thenownewspaper.com/business/Zellers+store+stay+open+Semiahmoo+Shopping+Centre/7800250/story.html#ixzz2Hz7zrhhS\n |accessdate  = January 14, 2013\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130130013814/http://www.thenownewspaper.com/business/Zellers+store+stay+open+Semiahmoo+Shopping+Centre/7800250/story.html#ixzz2Hz7zrhhS\n |archivedate = January 30, 2013\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2015, Target Canada ultimately filed for bankruptcy, and began the process of liquidating and closing its 133 locations.<ref name=torstar-condoproject>{{cite news|last1=Pigg|first1=Susan|title=Target pullout leaves condo project in the lurch|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/real_estate/2015/01/15/target-pullout-leaves-condo-project-in-the-lurch.html|accessdate=March 14, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref> The locations were sold in turn to other parties, such as [[Giant Tiger]], [[Lowe's]], [[Super C (supermarket)|Super C]] and Walmart.<ref name=cp-walmartbuy>{{cite news|title=Walmart to buy 13 former Target Canada stores and a distribution centre|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/walmart-to-buy-13-former-target-canada-stores-and-a-distribution-centre-1.3066182|accessdate=8 May 2015|agency=Canadian Press}}</ref><ref name=torstar-lowes>{{cite news|title=Lowe's to buy 13 Target stores|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/health_wellness/2015/05/11/lowes-to-buy-13-target-stores.html|accessdate=12 May 2015|work=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=eb-superccarrefour>{{cite news|title=Les travaux pour le Super C s'amorcent au Carrefour Saint-Georges centre|url=http://www.enbeauce.com/actualites/affaires/278243/les-travaux-pour-le-super-c-samorcent-au-carrefour-saint-georges|accessdate=7 November 2015|agency=EnBeauce.com}}</ref><ref name=lapresse-sherbrooke>{{cite news|title=Super Cemm\u00e9nagera dans l'ancien Target|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/la-tribune/economie-et-innovation/201505/30/01-4873911-super-c-emmenagera-dans-lancien-target.php|date=November 2015|work=La Presse}}</ref>\n\n==Stores==\n[[File:Zellersstoreinmoncton.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Zellers location (Store 158) in [[Moncton]]. Closed in 2012, became a [[Target Canada|Target]] in 2013 or 2014, closed again in 2015, and became a [[Canadian Tire]] in 2016.]]\n[[File:ZellersSelect.png|thumb|right|Zellers Select logo]]\nZellers operated stores from St. John's, Newfoundland, to Victoria, British Columbia and employed over 35,000 people. The average store size was 94,000 square feet (8,700 m2). Zellers Select stores were designed for smaller markets with populations under 25,000, with stores averaged 45,000 square feet (4,200 m<sup>2</sup>). Some multi level stores were equipped with a shopping cart system known as the Cartveyor, designed to transport shopping carts between floors next to a standard escalator, while there were few that were so small, they were equipped with elevators open to shoppers, such as with the [[Lawrence Square Shopping Centre]] location in the North York district of Toronto.\n\nIn July 2010, Zellers unveiled prototype store designs in five Winnipeg locations, with two more originally planned for late 2010 and early 2011. One store opened on the lower floor of the downtown Winnipeg Bay store making it the first Bay Zellers hybrid store in the HBC family of stores.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Restaurant===\n'''The Skillet''', Zellers in-store restaurant brand, launched in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chapin|first1=Angelina|title=The Ode: Zellers (1931 - 2011) - Canadian Business - Your Source For Business News|url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lifestyle/the-ode-zellers-1931-2011/|website=Canadian Business|accessdate=November 17, 2017|date=January 14, 2011|quote=In 1960, Zellers opened its first in-store restaurant, The Skillet, as well as an auto-centre, and its first store in a suburban mall.}}</ref> The restaurants underwent several revisions and were branded as '''Zellers Family Restaurant''' before their demise.\n\n===Pharmacy===\nAlmost every Zellers location had a pharmacy in it with a few stores in Quebec also having them. Prescription records were sold to other pharmacies in 2011 and Zellers pharmacies ceased operation throughout 2012. Zellers was subject to controversy regarding its sale of patient records.{{clarify|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Liquidation centres===\nAlthough Zellers remained open until 2020 as a store liquidator for [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|Hudson's Bay]] and [[Home Outfitters]], the Zellers chain had also operated a few liquidation centres for its own merchandise. Those were typically former regular Zellers stores that had been converted as liquidation centres for a limited time before closing down for good. The Zellers Family restaurants continued operating in these liquidation centres.\n\n==Products==\nProducts sold at Zellers included clothing, grocery, toys, electronics, furniture, and home supplies.\n\n===Grocery===\nAll Zellers sold basic groceries such as dry snacks and other prepackaged foods. The Neighbourhood Market, which used to be available at some locations, was Zellers expanded section of grocery items, which included frozen and dairy aisles. Prototype stores in Winnipeg featured full grocery departments including fresh produce and baked goods. Such plans were dropped following Target Canada's acquisition of many Zellers leases. Some stores removed their The Neighbourhood Market section.\n\n===Exclusive labels===\nZellers carried many of its own labels and also had exclusive rights in Canada to some other labels:\n<!--Please do not add labels that are found outside of Zellers/Target-->\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Alfred Sung]] Home\n* Beaumark\n* Big Star\n* Big Z {{small|(pillows)}}\n* Home Studio\n* Homestyles\n* Hunt Club\n* Marketsquare\n* Midtown\n* Nest by House & Home\n* Request {{small|(promoted by [[Ashlee Simpson]])}}\n* Sportek {{small|(unrelated to [[Sport Chek]])}}\n* [[Stuff by Hilary Duff]]\n* Truly\n* [[X Games]]\n* Zeddy {{small|(baby products)}}\n}}\n\n====Acquired labels====\nSome labels exclusive to [[Target Corporation]] in the United States were previously exclusive to Zellers in Canada. After Target's acquisition of Zellers leases until its closure, [[Target Canada]] became the exclusive store for the following brands\n*[[Cherokee Inc.|Cherokee]]\n* [[Mossimo]]\n*[[Wabasso Design Ideas|Wabasso]]\n\nHowever, Target Canada closed in 2015, leaving Wabasso, and Mossimo unavailable in Canada since then. Cherokee was then carried by [[Sears Canada]] for a short period, until it too closed in January 2018. With the demise of Zellers, Target Canada and Sears Canada, none of these brands are carried in Canada.\n\n==Customer service==\nOn January 6, 2012, [[CBC Television]]'s ''[[Marketplace (Canadian TV program)|Marketplace]]'' announced that Zellers received the title of Canada's Worst Customer Service as a department store, based on a survey conducted by CBC with the [[L\u00e9ger Marketing]] research firm in eight metropolitan areas. The retailer refused to be interviewed by ''Marketplace'' host [[Erica Johnson]] regarding its ranking, providing her with a written statement instead. Zellers also did not offer a refund to the mystery shopper who bought a used coffeemaker that was presented as new, and attempted to return the product after the advertised 30 day return period. Zellers Customer Service did not respond to this customer's Twitter message seeking satisfactory resolution.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/marketplace/episodes/2012-episodes/canadas-worst-customer-service-store-edition |title=Canada's Worst Customer Service |publisher=CBC |accessdate=2015-01-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105224451/http://www.cbc.ca/marketplace/episodes/2012-episodes/canadas-worst-customer-service-store-edition |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Advertising==\nZellers ran a Festive Finale advertising campaign in late 2011. Zeddy was also used as a mascot to advertise the retailer's toy selection.\n\n===Festive Finale===\nThe Festive Finale campaign was used to advertise Zellers last Christmas and holiday season sale in December 2011. There was a website called Zellers Facebook.ca which allowed customers to vote for their favourite coupon and musical genre. While Zellers recommended that customers have a Facebook account and Like the company, both of these steps were optional. It was also possible to record a radio commercial for Zellers Moonlight Madness sale by using a computer microphone and reading the site's [[teleprompter]]. Zellers also had social networking service accounts on Twitter and YouTube. Festive Finale was criticized for its Boxing Week coupon.\n\n===Loyalty program===\nAs a [[Hudson's Bay Company]] subsidiary, Zellers promoted the [[Hudson's Bay Rewards]] program also available at [[Hudson's Bay (retailer)|Hudson's Bay]] and [[Home Outfitters]]. It had been known as Club Z and HBC Rewards. The program used a points card, available at no charge but only accepted by Zellers and other partners. A Hudson's Bay MasterCard issued by Capital One is also available, which rewards customers with one point per dollar spent on the card at any retailer. Any Zellers cashier failing to inform a customer about the HBC MasterCard had to give that customer 10,000 HBC points. This is equivalent to 250 Hudson's Bay points, or one eighth of the requirement for a $10 gift card. Hudson's Bay points can still be redeemed for Hudson's Bay gift cards.\n\n===Slogans===\nNumerous slogans were used by Zellers:\n* Early 1980s: The low prices of Zellers are in the news (Zellers low prices are making headlines)\n* 1980s: Only you'll know how little you paid\n* 1980s: Shopping anywhere else is pointless\n* Late 1980s and 1990s Where the lowest price is the law!, followed by Where the lowest price is the law everyday and Because the lowest price is the law. as revisions including a few animated commercials featured Batman and Robin with the villains like the Joker, the Penguin, Catwoman and the Riddler.\n* 1990s Truly Canadian\n* 1997\u20132000 Better and Better\n* 2000\u20132013 Everything from A to Z\n<!--Please don't add the \"Expect More, Pay Less\" slogan, as it is Target's slogan and Zellers never used it-->\n\n===Zeddy===\n[[File:Zeddy Wheel.ogg|thumb|Zeddy encourages children to ride the Zeddy Wheel attraction at Zellers.]]\nZeddy is a teddy bear mascot used by Zellers all over Canada. He was first used in 1986<ref name=\"Zeddy contest\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.hbc.com/hbc/mediacentre/press/hbc/press.asp?prId=438 | title = Zellers Announces Everything Must Go\u2026 Including Zeddy\n| publisher = Zellers | accessdate = 2012-12-21}}</ref> as an advertising campaign, and then rose to his popularity by the early 1990s. The main purpose of Zeddy was to advertise Toyland, the toy section in Zellers stores. Zellers provided a stuffed Zeddy bear for any child who had a birthday party sponsored by Zellers. There was also a Zellers employee in a giant Zeddy costume hosting the party. Lineup toys of Zeddy were also created.<ref name=\"JasonFinale\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKs2mh0mY8U | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130810010039/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKs2mh0mY8U | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-08-10 | title = Zellers' Festive Finale presents: \"Pick the Playlist\" with Jason the Cashier | publisher = Zellers | accessdate = 2011-11-28}}</ref> In the final months before the last of the Zellers stores were closed permanently, the company distributed a large batch of stuffed Zeddy Bears for sale in stores throughout the network.\n[[File:Zeddy.jpg|thumb|right|195px|A Zeddy Bear, as sold in the chain's last months]]\nMany stores feature a Zeddy Wheel ride, which accommodates one young child on a miniature [[ferris wheel]] type ride. The ride costs $1 and plays carnival music when in use. When no one is riding the wheel, Zeddy says on a regular basis Come ride with me! All aboard the Zeddy Wheel! in an attempt to attract customers.<!--this was included with <ref> tags; updated to comment December 2016: Voice clips and pictures coming soon.-->  Despite Zeddy being withdrawn as Zellers official mascot in 2005, the Zeddy Wheel remained in operation at stores featuring it unless it is out of service, and the voice track was unchanged over the years. Some wheels removed the big Zeddy sticker in favour of multiple, small generic stickers.\n\nZeddy remains used as a baby brand for products such as diapers and baby bath products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zellers.com/content/en/kids/Zeddy/Zeddy.aspx |title=Zeddy |publisher=Zellers |accessdate=2011-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927115252/http://www.zellers.com/content/en/kids/Zeddy/Zeddy.aspx |archivedate=September 27, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nDuring the Festive Finale campaign in 2011, Zeddy was reintroduced in weekly flyers for Zellers Toyland before closing their stores for Target or Walmart. The character was used as a static picture, but no animated television commercials of him were made during this season. However, some employees decided to wear the Zeddy costume to celebrate the return of this teddy bear. Shortly thereafter, in December 2011, Zellers launched a Zeddy Bucks promotion. Those who spent at least $50 before taxes on toys received a pair of red [[2012 Summer Olympics]] mittens, plus a $10 Zeddy Bucks voucher. This voucher could only be used on a later date.<ref>Zellers December 2011 Flyer.</ref>\n\nWith the last Zellers stores set to close in 2013, the Hudson Bay Company announced in September 2012 that it was looking for a charity organization to adopt Zeddy so that the mascot could live on after Zellers.<ref name=\"Zeddy contest\"/> In a social media ad campaign, ''Zellers Everything Must GO Including Zeddy'', Zeddy was featured in an online video where the mascot was abandoned in the woods by a Zellers executive telling Zeddy that Zellers was liquidating, and everything must go, including him. Organizations were invited to submit on Zellers Facebook page what their plans for Zeddy were.<ref name=\"Zeddy after Zellers\">{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1257789--zellers-prepares-to-close-so-what-happens-to-zeddy-the-bear | location=Toronto | work=The Star | title=Zellers prepares to close, so what happens to Zeddy the bear? - thestar.com | date=September 17, 2012}}</ref> There were over 30,000 votes, and the final three contenders were Autism Ontario, Camp Trillium and [[Cystic Fibrosis Canada]]. Voters selected Camp Trillium as the winner and chosen adopter. There are several notable Zeddy iterations including most famously, bush pilot Zeddy.<ref name=\"Camp Trillium\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120015756/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1072675/zellers-iconic-mascot-zeddy-finds-new-home-with-camp-trillium|title=Zellers Iconic Mascot Zeddy Finds New Home With Camp Trillium|website=www.newswire.ca|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120015756/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1072675/zellers-iconic-mascot-zeddy-finds-new-home-with-camp-trillium|archive-date=November 20, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=National News: Zellers Iconic Mascot Zeddy Finds New Home With Camp Trillium|url=http://www.northumberlandview.ca/index.php?module=news&type=user&func=display&sid=18633|accessdate=17 November 2012|newspaper=Northumberland View|date=16 November 2012|location=Roseneath ON}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Zeddy4.jpg|1 \u2013 2003\nFile:Zeddy-Festive-Finale.png|2 \u2013 November 2011\n</gallery>\n#Zeddy, on the far right, is walking in a parade in 2003.\n#Zeddy appears in the Toyland section of Toyland in November 2011.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario|Canada}}\nOther discount retailer that once operated in Canada and similar concept as Zellers\n* Kmart opened first store in 1929 as Kresge and closed Canadian operations in 1998 some stores sold to Zellers\n* [[Woolco]] appeared in the 1960s and closed operations completely in 1994 most stores sold to Walmart some later acquired by Zellers\n* Towers Department Stores emerged in 1960 and ceased operations in 1991; all stores sold to Zellers \n* [[Horizon (store)|Horizon]], a competitor in the 1970s, created by the [[T. Eaton Company]]\nSuccessor of Zellers:\n* Target Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/business/target-leaving-canada-losing-money-every-day-1.2189973|title=Target leaving Canada: 'Losing money every day'|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> opened in 2013 after acquiring a number of former Zellers leases [[Retail apocalypse|all stores were closed in 2015]].\n\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Interior of a Zellers store.jpg|The inside of a Zellers store (Store 106) at Meadowlark Mall in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]] in 2007. Closed in May 2012, became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2013.\nFile:Zellers Etobicoke, ON, Canada 3 (35419700636).jpg|The former Kipling Queensway Mall Zellers in [[Etobicoke]], [[Ontario]] in 2017.\nFile:Zellers cornwall.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 6) in the Eastcourt Mall, [[Cornwall]], [[Ontario]], in 2013. Closed later that year, and has now been expanded into [[Ardene]], [[No Frills (grocery store)|No Frills]], [[Dollarama]], and Urban Planet.\nFile:Lawrence Square Shopping Centre.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 75) in the Lawrence Square shopping centre in [[North York]], [[Ontario]] in 2008. Closed in 2012, sat vacant for 3 and a half years, until [[Marshalls]] and [[HomeSense]] took over Zellers' former space in 2016. [[PetSmart]] was added in 2019.\nFile:County Fair Mall Thunder Bay.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 116) in the County Fair Mall in [[Thunder Bay]], [[Ontario]] in 2008. Closed in 2012, and became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2013.\nFile:Fairview Mall - panoramio.jpg|A Zellers store (Store 253) along with a [[Mark's]] and a former [[Future Shop]] at the Fairview Mall in [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]], in 2007. Zellers closed in 2012 and became a [[Walmart Canada|Walmart]] in 2012 or 2013. [[Future Shop]] closed in 2015 and became an [[IKEA]] in 2016.\nFile:Plaza C\u00f4te-Des-Neiges Listing Zellers Closing Inside Mall.JPG|A Zellers store (Store 213) during its' closing sale at Plaza Cote-Des-Neiges in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], in May 2012. As stated from the last days sign, this store closed on June 6, 2012 and got replaced by a Walmart in 2013.\nFile:Zellers Laval, QC 1 (8274483942).jpg|A Zellers store (Store 72) at the Les Galeries Laval in [[Laval]], [[Quebec]] in 2012. This store closed in 2013 and became an EconoMax in 2014.\nFile:Zellers Mega Centre Notre Dame Laval, QC 2 (8274486332).jpg|A Zellers store (Store 409) during its' closing sale at Mega Centre in [[Laval]], [[Quebec]] in 2012. Closed in 2013 and became a [[Target Canada|Target]] later that year. [[Target Canada|Target]] closed in 2015, then in 2016 or 2017, the former space became a [[Jysk]]. A [[Super C]] can be seen in the background.\nFile:Market-Mall.jpg|A sign for the Market Mall in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]], which includes [[Safeway (Canada)|Safeway]], [[Shoppers Drug Mart]], a liquor store, and Zellers. The Zellers part of the sign, along with the store, closed in 2012, sat vacant for 2 years and a half, but got replaced by a mini golf attraction in 2015. The liquor store part of the sign along with the store closed in 2018. It is unknown if the sign is still standing as of 2020.\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Zellers}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.zellers.com Official website] (from the [[Wayback Machine|Internet Archives Wayback Machine]])\n*[http://www.hbcheritage.ca/history/acquisitions/zellers Zellers history] at Hudson's Bay Company website\n\n{{Hudson's_Bay_Trading_Company,_L.P.}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Brampton]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Department stores of Canada]]\n[[Category:Hudson's Bay Company]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1978 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Laval\u2192Laval, Quebec(2),Super C\u2192Super C (supermarket)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zellers"}
{"title_page": "Carl G\u00fcnther Weiss", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish field hockey player}}\n'''Carl G\u00fcnther Hermann Weiss''' (April 29, 1915 &ndash; April 2, 2000) was a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[field hockey]] player who competed in the [[1936 Summer Olympics]]. He was born in [[Gentofte]].\n\nIn 1936 he was a member of the Danish team which was eliminated in the group stage of the [[Field hockey at the 1936 Summer Olympics|Olympic tournament]]. He played both matches as goalkeeper.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/carl-weiss-1.html Carl G\u00fcnther Weiss' profile at Sports Reference.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Carl Gunther}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Gentofte Municipality]]\n\n{{Denmark-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish field hockey player}}\n'''Carl G\u00fcnther Hermann Weiss''' (April 29, 1915 &ndash; April 2, 2000) was a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[field hockey]] player who competed in the [[1936 Summer Olympics]]. He was born in [[Gentofte]].\n\nIn 1936 he was a member of the Danish team which was eliminated in the group stage of the [[Field hockey at the 1936 Summer Olympics|Olympic tournament]]. He played both matches as goalkeeper.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/carl-weiss-1.html Carl G\u00fcnther Weiss' profile at Sports Reference.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Carl Gunther}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n\n{{Denmark-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Gentofte Municipality", 